<FIRST>r a PM-BarricadedNuns     04-05 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barricaded Nuns,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesting Nuns Enter Sixth Month Locked In Monastery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Carmelite nuns today entered
their sixth month barricaded in the infirmary of their monastery,
pledging to remain there until the Vatican's highest court hears
their appeal.
   The nuns began their protest Oct. 4, saying they were afraid of
being evicted because of their opposition to the liberalization of
the traditionally contemplative order through the introduction of
such things as candy and television.
   The Vatican court, the Apostolic Signatura, should consider the
appeal soon, said Tim Manning, spokesman for the Roman Catholic
Diocese of Paterson. The nuns would be allowed to remain in the
infirmary until the court rules, he said.
   He declined to say what action the diocese would take if the
court ruled against the nuns.
   The nuns have no plans to leave, said a close associate.
   ``They're not thinking of giving up because there's still that
appeal to be heard,'' said Betty Sutton, a spokeswoman for the nuns.
   The protest at the monastery of the Most Blessed Virgin Mary of
Mount Carmel initially involved five of its 13 nuns.
   Last month, the Vatican said two of the nuns whose temporary
vows had expired were no longer Carmelites and should leave. Two
other nuns were told to find other monasteries, and the oldest,
72-year-old Mother Philomena, was allowed to stay.
   Although the five initially ignored the order, one former nun,
Nicole Prescott, later left the monastery citing health reasons.
</TEXT>
