<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-05 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scandal-Ridden Firm Reportedly Gave Takeshita More Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, whose
administration is under fire in a major bribery scandal, received
$228,000 from the firm at the center of the scandal through ticket
sales for a fund-raising party, news reports said Wednesday.
   An aide to Takeshita, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed that Recruit Co., the information services firm at the
heart of the scandal, had bought tickets to the fund-raising party
in May 1987, but said ``our office did not directly handle the
party, so we do not know the amount.''
   Takeshita refused comment on the reports.
   The news followed the Takeshita's disclosure on Friday that
Recruit spent $152,000 on another of Takeshita's fund-raising
parties in May 1987. At the time, Takeshita was secretary general
of the governing Liberal Democratic Party and the leading contender
to the premiership.
   Reports by the major daily Asahi Shimbun and other local media
Wednesday said Takeshita had received a total of at least $380,000
from Recruit.
   Japanese politicians customarily use fund-raising parties to
sidestep legal restrictions on political donations and solicit
funds from business leaders and other politicians and supporters.
   Large corporations often buy large blocks of party tickets, but
Recruit's ticket purchases were unusually large. Takeshita
aknowledged last week that the $152,000 worth of tickets Recruit
bought for his party was ``slightly exessive'' for one company.
   There is no legal limit on the amount of money politicians can
raise from such parties without violating the Political Donations
Restrictions Law. The parties are considered legal ``as long as the
price of each ticket is within the range of common sense and the
number of tickets purchased is within a reasonable limit of what a
company can possibly use,'' an official at the Home Affairs
Ministry said on condition of anonymity.
   Recruit spent an estimated $685,000 on tickets for fund-raising
parties for 14 politicians from 1986-1988, of which $380,000
reportedly went to Takeshita.
   Executives of the firm, under investigation for suspected
bribery, sold about 500,000 shares in its real estate subsidiary,
Recruit Cosmos Co., to 159 influential people at cut-rate prices
before the company's stocks began over-counter trading. Recruit
Cosmos' share price shot up after public trading began and buyers
netted handsome profits.
   Opposition parties have demanded that Takeshita resign to take
responsibility for his administration's links to Recruit.
   ``Without intent to ask for specific favors, why should Recruit
give so much money to Takeshita?'' said Shun Ohide, secretary
general of the Japan Socialist Party, the largest opposition body.
   On Tuesday night, Socialist Party chairwoman Takako Doi proposed
a coalition government to replace Takeshita's Cabinet.
   ``The Takeshita Cabinet is no longer entitled to run the
government,'' she told reporters. ``The only alternative left for
the government is to resign en masse and accept the people's
judgment.''
   Doi said she would meet with other opposition party leaders
Friday to discuss ways to force Takeshita to step down and to iron
out details on a possible coalition.
   The opposition has stalled legislative business but cannot
legally force Takeshita out. The Liberal Democrats command 297 out
of 512 seats in the Lower House of Parliament and 143 out of 252
seats in the Upper House.
   Recent opinion polls indicate public support for Takeshita,
however, has fallen to 9 percent, the lowest level for any prime
minister since World War II ended in 1945.
   Three Cabinet ministers have resigned because of their links to
the Recruit scandal and prosecutors have arrested 14 people,
including former senior public officials and corporate executives
on suspicion of bribery and violations of securities laws.
   At least 17 politicians, including Takeshita and former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, have been implicated in the scandal,
although none has been arrested. Prosecutors reportedly have begun
questioning politicians and their aides.
</TEXT>
