<FIRST>u p AM-St.LouisMayoral     04-05 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St. Louis Mayoral,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incumbent Wins Third Term in St. Louis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr. easily won
re-election Tuesday, becoming only the third of St. Louis' 42
mayors to earn a third term.
   With about 50 percent of the votes counted, the Democratic
incumbent had 29,896 votes to Republican challenger Bernard J.
Elking's 10,943 votes, election officials said.
   ``It's a great honor, it really is,'' Schoemehl said.
   However, he added, ``I think politicians get in trouble when
they see mandates in things. In campaigning I found that people
expect things to get better. I certainly don't intend to sit back
and take it easy.''
   The city has not had a Republican mayor since 1949. Schoemehl,
who got little competition from Elking, conducted a low-key
campaign, relying on appearances at a few small gatherings and on
upbeat television commercials.
   The real race came in last month's Democratic primary, when
Schoemehl handily defeated Michael V. Roberts, a former alderman.
   Schoemehl raised and spent $842,000 on the campaign as of last
week. Elking's total available was $11,185.
   A spokesman for the mayor said most of the expenses were tied to
campaigning before the March 7 primary. Some television ads,
however, were run again last weekend.
</TEXT>
