<FIRST>u a AM-Mecham-Impeachment 2ndLd-Writethru a0414 04-05 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mecham-Impeachment, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0414,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ex-Gov. Mecham, Impeached a Year Ago, Will Run Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES urgent series. Minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham, impeached and removed
from office exactly a year ago, said Tuesday he'll run again in
1990.
   ``I committed no impeachable offense,'' the 64-year-old
Republican said at an evening rally at a hotel ballroom.
   The former auto dealer, elected in 1986 on his fifth try for
governor, convicted by the Senate on charges he misused funds and
obstructed justice, becoming the first governor impeached and
removed from office since 1929.
   However, lawyers are uncertain whether the impeachment vote
simply stripped Mecham of office or barred him from ever again
holding state office as well. And many moderate Republicans have
threatened to bolt if Mecham heads the ticket.
   ``I want to send word out to everyone in Arizona that I think we
can have a kinder and gentler Arizona,'' Mecham said. ``I think the
19 months between now and the general election of 1990 can be a
time of spirited debate on the issues but not name-calling and not
accusations without basis.''
   Mecham said he held no bitterness toward his critics but
considers himself to have been ``the object of more venemous
name-calling than anyone in our state and possibly in America.''
   Mecham has remained popular with a sizeable number of GOP voters
in a state where Republicans have an edge in registration.
   But former House Speaker Joe Lane, a Republican defeated in the
1988 primary after being targeted by Mecham supporters, said he was
``terribly distressed'' by Mecham's announcement. ``There'll be a
terrible primary. The Democrats will be organized and we'll have a
bloody primary, and I just hate to see that,'' Lane said.
   At the time of Mecham's removal, the the Senate stopped short of
explicitly approving a lifetime ban on his holding state office.
Attorney General Bob Corbin has been asked for an opinion on
whether Mecham can again hold office, but he noted that whatever he
comes up with can be challenged in court.
   Earlier Tuesday, Mecham said he had filed papers with the Senate
asking the Legislature to reconsider the votes by which it
impeached and ousted him.
   Legislative leaders said they doubted lawmakers would grant
Mecham a new impeachment trial and did not know how they could
consider the matter anyway because several incumbents had been
defeated in a post-impeachment election.
   The audience of about 400 Tuesday gave a standing ovation to
Mecham and his wife, Florence, when they arrived. Before Mecham
spoke, the crowd was entertained by tap dancers and a bluegrass
band and sang ``God Bless America.''
   The maverick conservative came under fire immediately after his
election for eliminating the state's Martin Luther King Jr.
holiday. Controversial appointments and statements that offended
blacks, Jews, Asians and others also ate away at his popularity
despite a no-tax stand that won support from many voters.
   He was impeached by the Republican-controlled House on charges
of misusing state money for his auto dealership, trying to thwart a
state investigation of a death threat and concealing a developer's
$365,000 campaign loan.
   The Republican-controlled Senate convicted him of misuse of
money and obstruction. It left the third charge to a Superior Court
jury, which acquitted Mecham.
   His removal put Rose Mofford, Arizona's Democratic secretary of
state, into the governor's office.
   During the evening rally, Mecham attorney Donald MacPherson said
that lawmakers failed to decide the issue ``according to the law
and evidence.'' He said he wasn't worried that the Senate might
refuse a new impeachment trial.
   ``If we don't get relief there, we have every intention of
taking it to the highest court in Arizona and, if need be, to the
U.S. Supreme Court,'' he said as the crowd rose to its feet and
applauded.
   In papers filed with the Senate, lawyers for Mecham claimed the
Legislature trampled on the rights of voters by ousting the
governor under rules of proceedure that were not as stringent as
those that apply in criminal trials.
   John Mawhinney, a Tucson Republican and Senate majority leader,
said he did not believe that ``there'd be any way in the world''
lawmakers would change their minds.
   ``We believe it was an appropriate, fair, constitutional
exercise of both the House of Representatives and the Senate,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
