<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seton Hall's appearance in the NCAA
basketball championship game was too good to pass up even for some
in the school's hometown who had vowed to turn off TVs for loftier
pursuits.
   School officials and librarians in South Orange and neighboring
Maplewood asked their communities this week to turn televisions off
and engage in more enriching activities.
   But that seemed next to impossible with Seton Hall in Monday
night's game, which it lost to Michigan by one point in overtime.
   ``This is a once in a very blue moon event,'' said Ruth
Greenwald, head of adult services at the Maplewood Library. ``On
the other hand, no one says I have to be glued to the television.
It's a minor infraction.''
   ``I'm watching the game, no question about it,'' said David
Javerbaum, 17, a senior at Columbia High School.
   During the campaign, families are supposed to keep a daily log
of their activities. To keep their minds off television, a puppet
show, a story telling festival for children and a celebrity read-in
were being held in the communities.
