<FIRST>r w PM-FuelEconomy     04-05 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fuel Economy,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Spill Shows Need to Tighten Fuel-Economy Standard, Senators Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators criticized the auto industry and its
regulators for failing to work for tighter fuel-economy standards
that would make it easier for the nation to cope with events such
as the Alaska oil spill that affect the fuel supply.
   ``The less the amount of gasoline consumed in this country, the
more able we are to respond to events,'' said Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and chairman of the Senate energy regulation
and conservation subcommittee, during a hearing Tuesday into the
fuel-economy standards adopted to reduce petroleum usage.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez last month ran aground in Alaska's
Prince William Sound, spilling more than 10 million gallons of oil.
The spill endangered wildlife in the area and prompted a sharp
increase in gasoline prices, especially in California.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration since August
has been considering where to set the corporate average fuel
economy standard, the gas mileage each automaker's fleet of cars
must attain, for the 1990 model year.
   NHTSA's managing director, Howard Smolkin, told the subcommittee
the present regulatory process required the agency to set the fue
economy standard at between 26.5 mpg and 27.5 mpg. The regulation
for 1989 required the mix ofmaker to average
26.5 mpg.
   The agency could require a significantly higher fuel-economy
standard only by beginning the rule-making process anew, Smolkin
said.
   Scrapping the present regulatory process in favor of a proposed
rulening ``would be one of the factors we
would cokin said.
   Legislation proposed by Metzenbaum would tighten the
fuel-economy standard to 34s per gallon by 2000.
   NHTSAesentatives of the Energy Department and
Environmental Protection Agency agreed agencies would support
greater fuel efficiencying refused to endorse
tighter fuel-economy standards.
   ``We seem to have an administration adrift on this issue, just
as the Exxon Valdez is adrift, and I hope we don't go up on the
sh,'' said Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo.
   Metzenbaum accused theakers of being too rigid in their
opposition toeconomy standards, saying the Big Three
``aren't working with us but are working against us.''
   The automakers have argued ning the fuel-economy
standards would cause theto reduce large-car production ider
to bring their mix of sales within the guidelines. The companies
contend the buying publicwants larger cars, and tightening the
standard would drive them into the showrooms of foreign makers to
buy the cars the U.S. makers could not provide.
   ``The source of our concern is not the desire to be adversarial.annot
go north and south at the same time,'' said Marine
Whitman, General Motors Corp. vice president.
   The fuel-economy law was adopted in 1975 to reduce gasoline
consumption at a time of rapidly rising oil prices.
   The law set a goal of 27.5 mpg beginning in 1985, but the Reagan
administration loosened the requirement to 26 mpg in 1986 at the
request of the automakers.
</TEXT>
