<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba-Dissidents     04-05 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Dissidents,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Arrested For Demanding Soviet-Style Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Cuban human rights activists were arrested
shortly before they planned to rally in support of reforms similar
to those embraced by visiting Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, a dissident spokesman said.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
condemned the arrests, saying they underlined ``the need for
ongoing monitoring of the human rights situation in Cuba.''
   Among those arrested on Tuesday was Samuel Martinez Lara, leader
of the Pro-Human Rights Party of Cuba, said Elizardo Sanchez, a
dissident activist.
   Martinez Lara's party and two other human rights groups had
planned to gather at the Soviet Embassy on Tuesday evening to ask
Gorbachev to pressure President Fidel Castro to adopt Soviet-style
reforms.
   Gorbachev, who was to leave for London today, is popular among
some Cubans because of his greater tolerance for opposing views and
his introduction of some capitalistic innovations.
   Castro, on the other hand, has been strongly committed to
maintaining Marxist orthodoxy and has rejected the concept of open
debate.
   Sanchez said that among others taken into custody was Roberto
Bahamonde, who gained attention last month by seeking election to a
seat on a municipal assembly by running as a dissident.
   It is believed the first time a dissident has launched such a
challenge in 30 years.
   Bahamonde lost the election against a pro-establishment
candidate but complained that he was not allowed to campaign on his
platform, which calls for a restoration of private enterprise.
   The arrest of Martinez Lara was confirmed by a Cuban Foreign
Ministry spokesman, Hector Argiles, who said the dissident had been
engaged in unauthorized activities.
   Sanchez said the families of the detainees have not been
informed of their whereabouts. ``They are being hidden,'' he said.
</TEXT>
