<FIRST>u i BC-Vietnam-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru   04-05 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Vietnam-Cambodia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0452,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam To Withdraw From Cambodia In June, Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with news conferences scheduled,
additional background; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam will withdraw all of its troops stationed
in Cambodia by the end of June _ ending a 10-year occupation, a
Japanese news agency reported Wednesday.
   Kyodo News Service, in a report from Hanoi, quoted ``reliable
sources'' as saying Vietnam had decided on a complete and
unconditional withdrawal of all its troops from Cambodia by June 30.
   Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach was expected to
issue a statement on the decision later Wednesday, Kyodo said in
the report monitored in Tokyo.
   Simultaneous news conferences on the decision were scheduled
Wednesday in Hanoi and Phnom Penh, the Cambodian capital.
   Vietnam previously has said it would withdraw its troops by
1990, but would move the pullout up to September if a political
settlement could be reached on the civil war. An estimated 70,000
Vietnamese troops are in Cambodia.
   The Vietnamese are fighting a coalition of three major
resistance groups: the communist Khmer Rouge of Khieu Samphan; the
non-communist Khmer People's National Liberation Front of former
Cambodian Prime Minister Son Sann; and followers of former
Cambodian head of state Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Sihanouk, who was deposed in 1970, heads the resistance
coalition.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, drove out the radical
Khmer Rouge regime that had defeated the U.S.-backed government in
the spring of 1975, and installed another communist administration.
   During the Khmer Rouge regime, it is estimated that about 2
million of Cambodia's 8 million people died from Khmer Rouge
executions, famine and civil unrest.
   Their role in a post-occupation coalition government has been a
major hurdle to a peace accord because their have the strongest
fighting force in the resistance.
   Fears of the Khmer Rouge returning to power have grown recently
as Vietnam withdrew part of its troops from Cambodia. There have
been at least six partial withdrawals since 1981, although foreign
critics charged that in some cases, fresh troops replaced those
that withdrew.
</TEXT>
