<FIRST>r w PM-US-CentralAmerica     04-05 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Central America,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arias Supports Non-Military Aid for Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias, endorsing
the Bush administration's package of nearly $50 billion in
non-military aid for Nicaraguan Contra rebels, wants Cuba to follow
suit and halt military aid to leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   After meeting Tuesday with President Bush, Vice President Dan
Quayle and Secretary of State James A. Baker III, Arias said the
so-called humanitarian aid was essential for integrating the
Contras back into Nicaraguan society.
   ``You cannot persuade the Contras to go back to Nicaragua if you
have nothing to offer them,'' he said. ``There's no freedom,
there's no democracy, they cannot integrate into political life;
and economic conditions are not the best.''
   Arias, who won the Nobel Peace Prize two years ago for his
Central America peace plan calling for a halt of all outside
military support for rebel groups in the region, said Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev now has to persuade Cuban President
Fidel Castro to stop sending arms to Salvadoran leftists.
   ``Ifupports sincerely the Central American peace plan he
has to ... persuade Fidel Castro not to ke
guerrillas in El Salvador,'' Arias said of Gorbachev, who is
meeting with Castro in Havana this week.
   ``We have learned that we must change bullets by ballots and we
can only do this with the support of the Cubans and the Soviet
Union,'' Arias said.
   Gorbachev told the Cuban National AssembTuesday that the
Soviet Union opposes the ``export of revolutioterrevolution,'' referring
to both Cuban and U.S. policy in
Latin America.
   But he also said his country will continue supplying weaponry to
Nicaragua's leftist government as long as the United States
continues to arm other Central American countries.
   And he called the Bush administration's continued non-military
support for the Contras ``worrisome.''
   Developed with bipartisan support after eight years of bitter
battles between Congress and the former Reagan administration over
military aid for the Contras, the new package of humanitarian aid
is intended to support the rebels until the Nicaraguan elections
next February.
   ``Now people here can talk with one single voice,'' Arias said
of the United States.
   He contrasted what he called ``lip service'' from the former
Reagan administration for his peace plan with officials in the new
Bush administration who are ``quite sincere and ... are doing what
they are doing in good faith.''
   ``I breathe a new atmosphere, a new environment, because I have
no doubts Mr. Bush and the Bush administration are going to
sincerely support the Guatemala accord, the Arias plan,'' he said.
   Quayle said Arias' s Bush's plan puts the ball in
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega's court to respond with
democratic reforms.
ayle said.
   Arias told Bush he still worries about how fair 
elections will be.
   He stressed the need to afford ample time for voter
registration, and said the Nicarans must allow establishment of
a TV station that is not controlled by the Sandinistas and as well
as assuring  access to the media by politicaes.
   ``Otherwise it will be very difficult to talk about free
elections,'' Arias said.
   An administration source said Arias told Bush that democratic
nations should closely scrutinize plans the Sandinistas are making
for the elctoral process.
   Arias said heso had told Castro that _ in vieush's
emphasis on non-military r the Contras _ ``It was time for
him ... if he supports our peace plan ... to stop supporting the
guerrillas in El Salvador.'   ``I told Fidel Castro ... that it was time
for him to step down
from the Sierra Maestra,'' ias said, referring to the mountain
range from where Castro orchestrated Cuba's revolution in 1959.
