<SECOND>PM-Charitable Chefs,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chefs Catering To Health-Conscious Connoisseurs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gourmet food doesn't have to be dripping in
calories and cholesterol to be sinfully delicious, according to
America's premier chefs, who are catering more and more to
health-conscious connoisseurs.
   ``There's a whole move toward freshness,'' said Lawrence
Forgione, chef proprietor of An American Place in New York. ``This
is what people want. They want to be informed. They want to know
what they're eating.''
   ``I see it becoming lighter, more natural,'' agreed Byron Bardy,
manager of national accounts research and development for Heinz
USA. ``You don't necessarily need a pound of butter to make a good
sauce.''
   Forgione and Bardy are among seven top chefs who have been
invited to dish out their best at a $1,500-a-person gourmet gala in
October for Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh. The world's leading
pediatric liver transplant center will launch its 1990 centennial
celebration with the culinary extravaganza.
   Half the 100 dinner tickets already have been gobbled up, solely
through word of mouth. Interest is just as keen at other
fund-raising affairs that feature the creations of leading chefs.
   ``How can you participate in fund-raising and cook something
that the average person doesn't want to eat anymore?'' Bardy asked.
``I mean, we all have to move ahead.''
   ``They're getting bored with always eating meat and potatoes,''
said Jean Banchet, chef and owner of Le FrancaiWheeling, Ill.,
near Chicago.
   A preview luncheon Monday featured a consomme of wild mushrooms,
grilled manated quail and California garden greens, all examples
of low-c
   Not that the great chefs have gotten out all the fat. The
luncheon also featured Banchet's duck liver with artichoke, truffle
and toast brioche and a butter-laden dish f creamed crawfish in
bread boaed by Cajun cook Paul Prudhomme, owner of K-Paul's
Louisiana Kitchen in New Orleans.
   Also on the high-calorie side was an apple dessert with
kiln-dried c sauce and topped with a sugar dome.
   ``Butter and cream are not something that you do in abundance,
nor do I think anybody does,'' Forgione said.
   Forgione cooks with only free-ranging chickens, those that are
chemical-free and allowed to graze naturally, while Banchet has
begun putting sauces on the side rather than on the food.
   Another chef offering his services ospital,
Jean-Louis Palladin of Jean-Louis at Watergate in Washington,
removes as much fat as possible from his dishes.
   ``If they are too heavy on the ch (customers) will
never come baladin said.
   Chefs with a conscience are blending what people want to eat
with what they should eat, according to Ferdinand Metz, president
of The Culinary Institute of America.
   ``Inot just the responsibility of the chefs to wait and say,
`Well, let's wait to e if they become more sophistica' said
Metz, who is baking the rt for the gala.
   ``We have a responsibility to lead, and I'm actually somewhat
disappointed in the lack ofcorporate responsibility that I see on
the part of some of the fast-food people.''
   Education is the main ingredient to healthy eating, and the New
York institute's 22,000 graduates are busy spreading the word,
according to Metz.
   ``The message will get around,. ``It's an enormous
undertaking, but I think we're making progress.''

</TEXT>
