<HEAD>Key Lenders Vow Action on U.S. Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spurred by concerns of social and political
turmoil in Third World countries, government-financed world lending
agencies hope to have a new U.S.-sponsored program in place by July
for reducing their foreign debt.
   ``We have an opportunity, if we seize it, to put the worst
aspects of the debt crisis behind us,'' World Bank President Barber
Conable said Tuesday at the close of the Bank's spring meeting with
the International Monetary Fund.
   The sister organizations ended their two-day conference with an
endorsement of the Bush administration's new debt initiative, which
for the first time asks private banks to voluntarily forgive part
of the Third World's $1.3 trillion debt.
   Elements of the plan could be put in practice by the time the
leaders of the world's economic democracies come together for their
mmit scheduled for July in Paris, officials said.
   A delay ``could be devastating in view ofated,'' Conable said.
   Throughout their meetings, officials ound the world spoke
repeatedly of social and political powder kegs that could be
ignited as living standards inue to stagnate or deteriorate in
debt-burdened developing countries.
   Riots in Venezuela in February that claimed 270 lives after the
government institung program to placate the
nation's creditors were an ``alarm signal,'' French Finance
Minister Pierre Beregovoy told reporters.
   B.T. Chidzero, Zimbabwe's finance minister and chairman of the
World Banelopment committee, said it was clear to the
finance officials ``that expectations have been raised. People
expect action. .... Expeditious action is required. ... Failure (tt) will
spell disaster.''
   Conable said the bank had created a task force that will start
work by the end of this week with the IMF on speeding
implementation of the new debt relief progon among the Bank, IMF, debtor
nations and commercial
banks is needed to ``flesh out ... a feasible plan,'' he said.
   A senior U.S. Treasury official, spea he not be
name likely be the first country to
qualify for debt relief. Mexico and Venezuela have also been
mentioned as earlfor assistance.
   IMF and World Bank approval of the so-called Brady plan named
after Treasury Secretary Nicrady was critical, since the
Bush administration is counting on most of the fincing for the
debt relief scheme to come from the two organizations.
   Basicaly, the plan seeks to entice banthey have made to Third World
countries in return for
assurances from the IMF and World Bank th paid.
   The administration projects cutting the debt of 39 major debtor
nations by 20 percent over the next three years with financing of
2 billion each from the IMF and the World Bank.
   IMF and World Bank officials refused to discuss specific dollar
amounts they would kick into the program, saying that depends on
how many countries adopt the economic reform programs required to
qualify for the debt relief.
   Micessus, the IMF's managing director, told reportenation organization
recognized the need to movepell out just how the debt relief will work
in order to
remove uncertainty in ongoing negotiations between debtor countries
and creditors.
   ``Nothing is worse than uncertainty,'' he said. ``The sooner we
can assemble  program and provide answers, the better the chance
for success
   In support of the plan, Japan has pledged to loan up to $4.5
billion to developing nations over the next several years, a
commitment that is viewed as critical since the flow of commercial
bank lending has been drying up.
   However, the meeting did not turn inctory for the
administration. Because of objections from the British in
particular, the steering committee refused to endorse a U.S.
proposal to use IMF and t
payments on the debt as well as the reduced amounts of princicountries
had objected that the more
costly intt-rate guarantees represented little more than a
bailout to comhe loans.
   The IMF promised only to ``examine'' the question of interest
rate subsidies.
