<FIRST>r w PM-Eastern-Congress     04-05 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Congress,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Pull Back on Eastern Airlines Strike Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic lawmakers say a measure they once
characterized as urgently needed to end the Eastern Airlines strike
is not necessary at all _ for now.
   Democrats pulled the legislation off the Senate floor on
Tuesday, arguing that the bill might impede efforts to purchase the
troubled carrier and hinder bankruptcy court attempts to find a
solution to the labor impasse.
   The action came the same day that The Associated Press learned
former Baseball Commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth would announce a
new deal to buy Eastern. An earlier offer collapsed after Jay A.
Pritzker, owner of the Hyatt Hotel chain, reportedly came in with a
higher offer.
   The airline's striking unions, which had originally sought
passage of the bill, asked senators to hold off action on the
measure to allow potential purchasers a chance to work out a deal,
said Senate Labor Committee Chairman Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and
Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the Senate aviation
subcommittee.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, took to the
Senate floor to say that the measure was being withdrawn to give
efforts to end the stalemate ``an unimpeded chance to work.'' He
said the measure might be returned to the floor in the future.
   The bill would require President Bush to appoint an emergency
board that would recommend a solution to the month-old walkout.
   Bush and congressional Republicans have opposed the measure,
saying the carrier's management and unions should work out their
dispute privately. Bush had threatened to veto the bill.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., noted Democratic claims
made last month just before the Senate's two-week Easter recess
that the emergency board legislation was urgently needed.
   ``No one can reasonably claim that the strike at Eastern is a
national emergency under any standard,'' Dole said.
   One of the driving forces of the strike has been the antipathy
union members have for Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent
company, Texas Air Corp.
   On March 9 _ five days after the walkout began, _ Eastern filed
for protection from creditors under the federal bankruptcy code. A
sale of the airline would require the approval of New York-based
U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland, who is handling the
reorganization, and by a court-appointed panel representing
creditors.
   The House passed the measure with overwhelming support from
majority Democrats last month.
</TEXT>
