<FIRST>r w PM-AIDS-Bush     04-05 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Bush,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Discrimination Law to be Considered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will propose legislation to bar
discrimination against people carrying the AIDS virus if an ongoing
review of state laws shows a federal statute is warranted, an
administration official says.
   James Allen, acting director of the Public Health Service's
National AIDS Program Office, told a House panel on Tuesday that a
study of the status and effectiveness of state laws is being
conducted by George Washington University under a federal contract.
   Allen said the survey will be completed in a few months.
   ``If it seems appropriate, the administration will propose
legislation,'' he said in response to a question from Rep. Henry A.
Waxman, D-Calif.
   Waxman is chairman of the Energy and Commerce health
subcommittee that called witnesses for the first overview of the
status of the AIDS epidemic conducted since Bush became president.
   Waxman had opened the hearing by complimenting Bush's wife
Barbara for symbolic gestures toward AIDS patients, but wondering
whether Bush would follow up on a campaign commitment to back
federal anti-discrimination legislation.
   ``The first lady has already moved us all with her visit to AIDS
patients and her hugs for both babies and adults who are ill,''
Waxman said. ``With one photo session she has probably done more to
alleviate fear and to create compassion than could be done with a
dozen studies or hearings.''
   He referred to a recent visit by Barbara Bush to an AIDS
facility in Washington where she was photographed holding an infant
with AIDS and also embracing an adult with AIDS.
   ``She should be congratulated and thanked for bringing us closer
together at this time when we need to be close,'' continued Waxman.
``But such feelings aren't enough. The president promised help and
protection, and we must begin to put that assistance together as
budgets and laws.''
   Allen said 88,096 cases had been reported to the Centers for
Disease Control through the end of February. There was a 45 percent
increase in the number of reported cases during the most recent
12-month period when compared to the previous 12-month period, he
said.
   The White House AIDS commission and the independent Institute of
Medicine have urged passage of a federal ban on discrimination
against AIDS patients, saying it is necessary to get people to be
tested for AIDS who otherwise would not do so out of fear they
would lose their jobs and be evicted from their homes if they test
positive.
   Opponents say writing laws to apply specifically to people with
AIDS would give them a protected status not extended to people with
other fatal diseases.
</TEXT>
