<HEAD>1987 Law Allows AIDS Victims to be Refused Entry to United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch AIDS victim refused entry to the
United States at the Minneapolis-St. Paul Airport was kept out of
the country because of a 1987 law passed by Congress, officials say.
   For years, immigration laws have required people who want to
visit or move here to establish that they do not have any
dangerous, contagious diseases.
   Congress added acquired immune deficiency syndrome to that list
of diseases in August 1987, and regulations preventing AIDS
patients from entering the country became effective that December,
said Joseph D. Cuddihy, the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's senior immigration examiner in the examinations branch in
Washington.
   ``It's not just the INS,'' said Greg Leo of the INS. ``This is
something that's been a congressional matter.''
   Cuddihy said Tuesday that, ``A person has to establish
eligibility at the time of application (for a visa) overseas and
each and every time he enters the United States.''
   Immigration officials detained Hans Paul Verhoef, 31, of
Rotterdam, the Netherlands, at the airport after U.S. Customs
officials discovered the drug AZT in his baggage Sunday.
   He then told immigration officials that he has AIDS, and he was
taken to the Scott County Jail outside the Twin Cities area where
he was being held.
   Verhoef, an AIDS prevenon worker in his country, was en route
to San Francisco to participate as a delegate to the International
Caucus of the 7th National AIDS Forum and the 11th National Gay and
Gay Health Conference that begins Wednesday.
   Ten to 15 othr AIDS victims previously have been turned away
from this country, and an unknown number have been denied visas
their native country because they have the disy said.
   Visa applications specifically ask those who want t to the
United States whether they have any of the prohibited diseases, he
said. Those applying for permanent visas must undercal
examinations, but ``unless there is any reason to believe tson is ill,''
those who want simply temporary viaminations, he said.
   Not all foreign visitors are asked about their health when they
arrive in this country.
   Cuddihy  assumed that Verhoef was questioned about it
only because he ts he planned to attend the AIDS
conference in San Francisco and the discovery of the container of
AZT.
   The information provided by Verhoef as well as thegage he
had with him ``led to these particular tions in this particular
case,'' Cuddihy said.
   ``Every person is not asked specifically about all of the 33
grounds of exclusion and seven excludible diseases,'' he said,
adding that the diseases include tuberculosis and several sexually
transmitt
   ``If we tried to cover all the issues withyou can imagine what that
would do to a place liK and LAX,''
he said, referring to the airports in New York City and Los
Angeles. ``One of the grounds of exclusion is illiteracy, but we
never tell them to write their names.''
   Cuddihy said he believrhoef ``did not indicate that he
had AIDS'' when he applied for the visa in June 1988 for another
visit.
   We are not sure that he may or may not have had the HIV
infectin at that time, or he may not have been aware of ... what
it implied,'' he said. The INS is not questioning whether Verhoef
lihe obtained the visa, he said.
