<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-05 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Rise A Bit To Another High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's leading index climbed
slightly to yet another record high, and the U.S. dollar edged up
against the Japanese yen Wednesday after a four-day decline.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose by 48.54
points, or 0.15 percent, closing at 33,360.79. The previous record
high was 33,312.25 on Tuesday.
   The dollar closed at 131.37 yen, up 0.32 yen from Tuesday's
close of 131.05 yen. It opened at 131.33 yen and ranged between
131.20 yen and 131.58 yen.
   The dollar had fallen a total of 2.20 yen in the previous four
trading days.
   Dealers said improved prospects for stable exchange rates, as
reaffirmed in the meeting of finance ministers from the seven major
industrial countries, encouraged investors' buying activities, and
most shares moved higher from the start of the day's trading.
   ``Market sentiment is traditionally bullish in April as it is
the beginning of the new fiscal year for most (Japanese)
companies,'' said a dealer at a major securities firm who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``The favorable news on currency rates
makes the market doubly bullish.''
   He said shares in electronics and heavy-industry companies were
particularly in demand due to the favorable climate for stable
exchange rates.
