<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-WarZone     04-05 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-War Zone,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Village Life Goes On Despite Heavy Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Namibia, Bjt ^By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMBALANTU, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after an intense firefight, the
only clues that life around this northern border village had been
disturbed were the hundreds of expended rifle shells lying on a
sandy road, shining in the sun.
   Police and black nationalist guerrillas waged a fierce battle
for several hours Monday night and early Tuesday along parts of the
25-mile road that connects Ombalantu to Tsandi, police said.
   But in the daylight, local residents casually rode their
bicycles past the shells casings, carried on with herding their
goats and drank beer in the local shops.
   The residents say they have grown accustomed to the fighting
after 23 years of war between the South African-led security forces
and the guerrillas of the South-West Africa People's Organization.
   Like many people in the region, the villagers are SWAPO
supporters. Their loyalties are undoubtedly strengthened by the
fact that SWAPO leader Sam Nujoma comes from a nearby village.
   The residents said they heard shooting and saw flares until 3
a.m. Tuesday, and were worried renewed battles could catch their
village in the crossfire.
   Ombalantu has a police base, a few shops, some small farms and
not much else. The harsh, hot land is flat and sandy, covered with
low scrub bushes.
he numerous shell casings, from rifles used by the territorial
police force, gave some hints as to the intensitof the fighting.
It showed that the police stayed on the road for several miles
firing into the bush at guerrillas.
   Police Capt. Jumbo de Villiers said his men, many of whom are
members of the Himba tribe, have spent the last four days tracking
guerrillas in the bush.
   ``SWAPO (guerrillas) he best track disguisers in the
world,'' said de Villiers. ``But Himba are the best trackers.''
   According to de Villiers, a six-month cease-fire was broken
Saturday morn when nine policemen, tracking suspected cattle
thieves, were ambushed by SWAPO guerrillas.
   The guerrillas, with small armand grenades, killed three of
the policemen, de More than a dozen SWAPO fighters
were killed, he added.
   Sen, the police have staged their own surprises, de
Villiers sai Police trackers on Monday came across 40 guerrillas
bathing nesmall dam, he said.
   He did not give details of the fighting, saying only that ``a
contact was made.''
   SWAPO leaders say security forces broke the cease-fire.
