<FIRST>r w PM-Medigap     04-05 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medigap,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell Threatens Push for Federal Regulation of Medigap Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House committee is
threatening to push for federal regulation of the supplemental
health insurance industry on grounds the states are doing an
inadequate job of protecting the elderly from exploitation.
   ``Preliminary reports from the General Accounting Office
indicate that many of the largest commercial insurers continue to
bilk elderly citizens by offering unlawful and unconscionably low
returns on premium payments,'' Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., wrote
to the national Association of Insurance Commissioners on Tuesday.
   ``This finding suggests the need for immediate action and raises
serious doubts about the effectiveness of the present regulatory
structure,'' said Dingell, head of the Committee on Energy and
Commerce.
   So-called Medigap policies are sold by private insurance
companies to supplement the coverage 32 million Americans have
under Medicare, the federal health program for the elderly and
disabled. Like other insurance, it historically has been regulated
by the states.
   But Dingell's letter to David Gates, president of the
Washington-based National Association of Insurance Commissioners,
suggested that might not remain a permanent arrangement.
   Gates, the Nevada state insurance commissioner, was traveling
when the letter was made public _ in advance of being made
available to the association _ and could not be reached for comment.
   ``We will respond to Mr. Dingell's letter when we receive a
copy,'' said Kevin Cronin, the organization's Washington counsel.
   Dingell said the Energy and Commerce oversight and
investigations subcommittee, which he also chairs, has scheduled a
hearing April 26 ``to further explore these issues in some detail
and to reveal the complete findings of our investigation.''
   Dingell closed his letter by informing Gates that he intends to
introduce legislation ``aimed at strengthening federal standards to
assure that all (Medicap) policies are vigorously regulated
irrespective of how or where they are sold, to require that
insurers meet reasonable loss ratios or return windfalls to policy
holders, and to combat sales abuses by offering appropriate
deterrents to those who insist on selling duplicative policies.''
   He said the GAO survey found that ``the majority of companies,
many with tens of millions of dollars in premiums, were found to
return less than 60 percent of premiums collected.''
   ``These windfall profits earned at the expense of the elderly
are particularly harmful given the rising health care expenses that
so many elderly people face,'' Dingell wrote.
   The overhead cost of Medicare is about 3 percent, meaning 97
cents of every dollar handled by the program goes to actual patient
benefits.
</TEXT>
