<FIRST>r w PM-UnionCorruption     04-05 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Union Corruption,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teamsters President Denies Mob Ties, Blasts Predecessors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters leader William J. McCarthy says he
has never had dealings with organized crime figures and told
Congress he knew of no current members of the union's governing
board with mob ties.
   ``If I get the facts, if I know what's going on, I will move,''
McCarthy said Tuesday in promising to root out any corruption that
came to his attention. ``It's not anywhere that I know of,'' he
said when asked whether the current international union leadership
was under mob influence.
   McCarthy testified at a Senate Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigations hearing to review the recent settlement of a
racketeering suit against the Teamsters, part of a larger committee
look at government efforts to battle union corruption.
   The suit sought the ouster of the Teamsters' entire 18-member
governing board, alleging the leadership was rife with mob
corruption, but the settlement allowed all current members of the
board to keep their jobs.
   Benito Romano, U.S. attorney for Manhattan, defended the
settlement as the quickest way to reform the union, telling the
hearing the agreement included election reforms that would end a
``sick joke'' system under which Teamsters leaders are now chosen.
   McCarthy, under questioning, denied an account by his immediate
predecessor, Jackie Presser, who told the FBI that McCarthy said he
would have to get approval from Mafia leaders before seeking the
union's No. 2 post in 1984.
   ``That's not so,'' McCarthy said before lashing out at Presser
and another former Teamsters president, Roy Williams.
   ``Both were mixed up with La Cosa Nostra by their own
admissions. I didn't care for either one of them,'' he said.
   McCarthy said it was Presser who in 1984 suggested McCarthy
would have to meet with Raymond L.S. Patriarca, the reputed New
England crime boss, if he wanted to be appointed secretary
treasurer of the union.
   ``I said, `No way,''' McCarthy said. ``I didn't talk to him nor
would I.''
   Patriarca died in 1984 and, according to law enforcement
officials, was suceeded by his son, Raymond ``Junior'' Patriarca.
McCarthy said he never has met or spoken to the younger Patriarca
and gave the same answer when asked if he ever had met or spoken to
a number of other reputed mob figures.
   McCarthy said the only pervasive mob corruption he was aware of
was in the Teamsters Central States division _ from which both
Presser and Williams rose through the union's ranks.
   Asked about an account that quoted him calling Presser a ``stool
pigeon,'' McCarthy said: ``It could be, yes sir. ... I call him a
crooked stool pigeon. He lies. That's why I gave him that name.''
   As part of the settlement, the union agreed to hold open
elections by secret ballots and to appoint three monitors with
broad powers to oversee union elections and management.
   Although the settlement, reached last month, took effect
immediately the Teamsters agreed to submit pertinent portions of it
to their next convention for ratification, a step designed to
prevent future challenges to the legality of amending the union's
constitution through a court agreement.
   McCarthy denied assertions made by a dissident Teamsters group
that during regional meetings last week he boasted that the union
could escape terms of the agreement by having delegates to the
convention vote against the amendments.
   McCarthy and Teamsters general counsel James T. Grady said they
were responding to questions when they said it was possible for the
union's delegates to reject the amendments. Grady said McCarthy
made it clear that if that happened the government had vowed to
reopen the case or seek other legal recourse.
   ``I'm going to do everything in my power to support them,''
McCarthy said when asked whether he would urge passage of the
amendments. ``My word is my bond.''
</TEXT>
