<FIRST>r w PM-BenefitsSurvey     04-05 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Benefits Survey,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: One Third of Workers Get Maternity Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unpaid maternity leave was available last year
to 33 percent of workers at companies with at least 100 employees,
according to a government survey of benefits that also found
intensified efforts to control health care costs.
   Nine in 10 workers at the medium and large companies surveyed
were offered some form of medical coverage and more of them are
choosing to enroll in health maintenance organizations and other
non-traditional plans, the Labor Department said Tuesday.
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics' annual benefits survey found
that 63 percent of workers in the firms with at least 100 employees
were covered by defined benefit pension plans, most commonly plans
which peg pension payments to a percentage of a worker's earnings
in the last few years before retirement.
   Ninety-two percent were provided some form of life insurance, 96
percent paid holidays, 98 percent paid vacations, 69 percent some
form of sick leave, 85 percent funeral leave and 91 percent jury
leave, the survey said.
   In all, the survey provided representative data for 31 million
full-time employees in the private sector _ up from 21 million
workers covered in prior surveys _ and for the first time addressed
parental leave, a subject likely to face considerable debate in the
current Congress.
   Unpaid maternity leave was available in benefit plans covering
33 percent of the employees and unpaid paternity leave under plans
for 16 percent of the workers. When offered, four months was the
average maximum length of both maternity and paternity leave,
according to the survey.
   Just 2 percent of employees had benefit plans which allowed paid
maternity leave and 1 percent were eligible for paid paternity
leave, the survey found.
   The health care section of the survey found expanded efforts to
lower benefits costs through use of HMOs, pre-admission
certification, mandatory second opinions before some treatments and
expanded coverage for home health care and extended care facilities.
   Alcohol and drug treatment were available in benefits plans
covering 80 percent and 74 percent of the workers.
   The survey showed that participation in HMOs and other
non-traditional health care programs nearly doubled between 1986
and 1988, from 14 percent to 26 percent. Of those employees, 19
percent were enrolled in HMOs and 7 percent in Preferred Provider
Organizations, under which subscribers are provided services at a
lower cost if they are treated by designated health care providers.
   Two-fifths of the workers were required to contribute toward the
cost of their medical coverage and three fifths toward the cost of
family coverage, with the average monthly employee contribution for
individual coverage being $19 and the average employee contribution
for family coverage being $60 a month, the survey found.
</TEXT>
