<FIRST>r a PM-People-Pavarotti-Protest     04-05 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Pavarotti-Protest,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art Students Stage Noisy Protest Over Theater Switch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arts students angrily protested being made
to play second fiddle to tenor Luciano Pavarotti, who needed their
stage for an opera because of a structural problem that has closed
the Academy of Music.
   About 200 students held a noisy demonstration Tuesday because
the University of the Arts is allowing Pavarotti to use its
Schubert Theater on nights that had been reserved for two student
productions.
   Demonstrators said they weren't told about the switch.
   ``We've been rehearsing for months, and then I had to hear on
the news about being put out of the theater,'' complained senior
Sharon Nordlinger, who is in the cast of ``Hamlet Machine.''
   Pavarotti and the Opera Company of Philadelphia needed a new
theater for the April 9 and 13 productions of Verdi's ``Luisa
Miller'' when the 132-year-old Academy of Music was closed on
Friday because of a cracked ceiling beam.
   After about five hours of chanting and dancing in front of the
university administration building, the demonstration broke up when
school President Peter Sohmssen came out to announce a settlement
negotiated with faculty and student leaders.
   Under the terms, the student productions will be rescheduled.
``Hamlet Machine'' will be staged April 15 and 16, and the
university's spring dance concert will be May 9 and 10.
   Sohmssen expressed satisfaction that the demonstration had been
about an issue related to their work and study, said university
spokesman Kirby Smith.
   ``He said in an ideal world, the students should have been
consulted, but this happened over the weekend, and he had to move
quickly,'' Smith said.
   The University of the Arts was established in 1987, through the
consolidation of two 100-year-old institutions, the Philadelphia
College of Art and the Philadelphia College of the Performing Arts.
More than 1,450 full- and part-time students are enrolled in its
undergraduate and graduate programs.
</TEXT>
