<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-05 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Hit Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained against the Japanese yen in Tokyo
today following four days of decline, and the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's main index rose to another record high.
   After opening higher at 131.33 yen, the dollar edged up in
moderate trading, closing at 131.37 yen, up 0.32 yen from Tuesday's
finish. The U.S. currency ranged between 131.20 and 131.58 yen,
with volume estimated at $7.4 billion.
   ``Although the dollar weakened temporarily following a series of
central bank interventions in recent days, demand for the U.S.
currency is still quite strong,'' said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa
Bank.
   ``Because nothing has really changed in the basic economic
fundamentals, market participants, especially speculators, are
inclined to buy the dollar because of higher interest rates in the
United States,'' he said. Higher U.S. interest rates make the
dollar more attractive to investors.
   Traders said news reports today that Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita had received an additional $230,000 in funds from Recruit
Co., the firm at the heart of a widening stock-trading scandal, had
discouraged yen purchases.
   Recruit, an information conglomerate, sold hundreds of thousands
of bargain-priced shares in its real estate subsidiary,
Recruit-Cosmos Co., to influential government and business
officials prior to public trading. The recipients reaped large
profits when the share price soared in value after being listed on
the over-the-counter market.
   Fourteen people have been arrested and three Cabinet members
have resigned because of the scandal.
   Concern over political instability due to the scandal has
prompted yen selling in overseas and local currency markets,
traders said.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues rose 48.54 points, or 0.15 percent, closing at 33,360.79,
another record high.
   The index initially declined because of profit-taking, but then
rose because of buy orders from institutional and individual
investors near the end of trading, dealers said.
   Trading was heavy, with volume on the exchange's first section
estimated at 1.8 billion shares, compared to Tuesday's 1.7 billion.
   Among the issues which attracted participants were chemicals and
machineries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
