<DOCNO> AP890405-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 0715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-DaleyProfile     04-05 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Daley Profile,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Shoes To Fill, But Daley Says He's His Own Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley has legendary shoes to fill, but
says he will stride into City Hall on his own two feet.
   Flush with victory Tuesday and preparing to occupy the mayor's
office held 21 years by his father, the late Richard J. Daley, he
said, ``Throughout this campaign I've been asked about my father
and what I learned from him. He taught me to love this city.
   ``He taught me that public service is not just a job,'' he
continued. ``Public service is a high calling.''
   Throughout a political career that had its beginnings nearly 30
years ago, the Daley name made many of his achievements possible,
diminished others, and left him forever open to the charge that his
vision extends only as far as his father's shadow.
   ``Both my father and Mayor (Harold) Washington loved this city
and both were strong mayors,'' Daley said. But people running for
mayor ``should stand on their own two feet.''
   He lived at home until he was 30, and now, at age 46, still
lives only a few blocks from the bungalow where he grew up in the
working-class Bridgeport neighborhood. He looks, walks, talks, and
occasionally misspeaks in a way that makes it obvious he is an heir
of the last of the big-city bosses.
   And that is what scares his critics most. During the campaign,
black rival Timothy Evans labeled Daley a ``pharoah'' and said his
election would revive the once-vaunted political machine his father
built on patronage and used to control City Hall.
   ``We will likely return to plantation politics,'' said Lu
Palmer, a black activist and radio personality.
   Daley, who friends and colleagues say began to emerge from his
father's shadow after the elder Daley's death in 1976, is sensitive
to the charge.
   ``The people of Chicago want to move forward, not back,'' he
said, ``they want a government that is fair and open and
representative of every community and so do I.''
   But he does not entirely shy away from his legacy.
   ``I think the best lesson my father taught me had nothing to do
with politics or government,'' he said Tuesday night as supporters
roared. ``It had to do with my family. And I want to thank my
family for their support in bad times and in good times.''
   And Daley recalled that he and wife, Maggie, never needed
support more than when the family lost Kevin, the third of their
four children, to the crippling disease spina bifida at age 2.
   After he spoke, Daley hoisted his 5-year-old daughter,
Elizabeth, to his shoulder as his wife, daughter Nora, 15, and son,
Patrick, 13, beamed.
   The eldest of seven children, Richard M. Daley cut his political
teeth working as an 18-year-old page for the Illinois delegation to
the 1960 Democratic National Convention.
   He graduated law school in 1968 and his father rewarded him with
a job as an assistant city attorney after he passed the bar exam on
his third try. He handily won a seat in the 1969 Illinois
Constitutional Convention.
   In 1972, a machine Democrat was pulled from the Illinois Senate
to make room for young Daley.
   He was criticized by some colleagues early on as his father's
``eyes and ears,'' and he helped block reformist legislation.
   But he later forged cautious alliances with the same reformers
who often had opposed his father.
   As a result, when he ran for the first of his three terms as
Cook County state's attorney in 1980, Democrats slated Alderman
Edward Burke to run against him. The younger Daley clobbered Burke,
then twice won re-election.
   The combination of an old name and a new face proved a winner
again Tuesday.
   ``It shows Americans love sequels,'' said Eugene Kennedy, a
Loyola University professor and author of ``Himself,'' a biography
of the elder Daley.
</TEXT>
