<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-05 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firmer, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was firmer in early European
trading today, supported by plenty of commercial demand. Gold
prices fell.
   Foreign currency dealers said they think the currency has
entered a consolidation phase that is likely to last until Friday's
release of U.S. unemployment figures.
   Traders said they are optimistic about the dollar's strength,
but believe continued fear of central bank intervention and
lingering effects of statements made at last weekend's meeting of
the Group of Seven major industrialized nations would serve as an
effective cap on any sharp movement higher.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.32 yen to a closing 131.37. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 131.53 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8741 West German marks, up from 1.8670
   _1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6358
   _6.3260 French francs, up from 6.3100
   _2.1131 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1080
   _1,374.50 Italian lire, up from 1,372.75
   _1.1895 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1875
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6987, cheaper for buyers
than $1.7043 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $384.90 a troy ounce,
down from $386.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $384.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $384.20, down from $386.50 bid late
Tuesday.
   All financial institutions in Hong Kong were closed today for
the Chinese Ching Ming grave-sweeping holiday.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.80 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $5.84.
</TEXT>
