<FIRST>r p PM-ElectionsRdp     04-05 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elections Rdp,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley Wins in Chicago; Dems Keep Alabama House Seat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chicago Mayoral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard M. Daley captured the office his father held for 21
years, and Alabama Democrats held on to a House seat in a special
election that could signal a rough road for Republicans hoping for
big gains in the South in 1990.
   In other elections Tuesday, residents of Winnetka, Ill.,
approved a non-binding handgun ban prompted by a deadly shooting
spree at an elementary school there last May.
   Omaha's former mayor, Michael Boyle, ousted in a 1987 recall,
made a successful comeback bid in a primary; Joseph Sensenbrenner,
the three-term incumbent mayor of Madison, Wis., lost to Paul
Soglin, a former three-term mayor; St. Louis' Democratic Mayor
Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr. won easy re-election; and Wichita, Kan.,
elected its first mayor in 74 years.
   In Alabama's 3rd Congressional District, Secretary of State Glen
Browder, a Democrat, swept all 13 counties despite Republican John
Rice's attempt to brand him a liberal in a mostly conservative
region. Browder claims the seat left vacant by the death of
Democratic Rep. Bill Nichols in December.
   Browder had 47,229 votes, or 65 percent, to Rice's 25,008, or 35
percent.
   Browder, 46, adopted a get-tough strategy to counter Rice's
liberal-bashing. Rice, 37, a real estate developer, had labeled
Browder a liberal, a liar and a ``wimp.''
   The race was one of three special congressional elections this
spring. In Indiana last week, Democrat Jill Long defeated
Republican Dan Heath to fill a vacant seat whose previous two
occupants were Republicans, including Vice President Dan Quayle.
Voters in Wyoming will choose a successor to Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney on April 26.
   In Chicago, the 46-year-old son of the late Mayor Richard J.
Daley defeated Alderman Timothy Evans, a black who ran as an
independent and had claimed the mantle of the late Harold
Washington, the city's first black mayor.
   Former alderman Edward Vrydolyak, who won the Republican primary
as a write-in, lagged far behind.
   ``We were determined to prove to a doubting world that Chicago
has grown beyond the politics of division and name calling,'' Daley
said as supporters in a hotel ballroom roared their approval.
   The Democratic Cook County prosecutor captured overwhelming
white support in the Democratic primary in February to oust the
city's second black mayor, Eugene Sawyer.
   Race remained the underlying issue in Chicago, where elections
tend to divide voters by color more than party, but in his victory
speech, Daley reached out to blacks.
   ``The late Mayor Washington opened city government to many
citizens who felt excluded and ignored,'' he said. ``As long as I
am mayor, those doors will remain open to all citizens.''
   In other mayoral races, St. Louis' Schoemehl won a third
four-year term by defeating Republican challenger Bernard J. Elking.
   In Wichita, where residents decided last November to make the
post an elective position, longtime City Councilman Bob Knight
defeated businessman John Bell. In recent years, council members
had elected a largely ceremonial mayor from among themselves.
   In Omaha, where Boyle had been ousted after feuding with the
police chief, the former mayor was the top vote-getter in a
non-partisan primary that trimmed a field of seven candidates to
two for May 9's general election. He will face real estate manager
P.J. Morgan, who slipped by incumbent Mayor Walt Calinger to
capture the other runoff spot.
   In Topeka, Kan., incumbent Mayor Douglas S. Wright was defeated
by former Parks Commissioner Harry Felker III.
   In Northmoor, Mo., just outside Kansas City, one acknowledged
member of the Ku Klux Klan and two men identified as a Klan
sympathizers lost bids for seats on the Board of Aldermen and as
town marshal.
   And in Winnetka, Ill., voters approved the handgun ban in their
Chicago suburb where a woman carrying three guns shot to death a
young boy and wounded several others before killing herself last
May.
</TEXT>
