<HEAD>Highlights of Tuesday's Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Elections Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of elections held around the nation Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MAYOR'S RACES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   CHICAGO _ Richard M. Daley, son of the late Mayor Richard J.
Daley, won election to complete the last two years of the term of
Mayor Harold Washington, who died in office in November 1987.
Daley, the Democratic Cook County prosecutor, defeated Alderman
Timothy Evans, a Democrat running as the nominee of the Harold
Washington Party, and former Alderman Edward Vrdolyak, the
Republican candidate.
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Former two-term Mayor Mike Boyle, ousted in a
recall in 1987, captured the most votes in a mayoral primary to win
one of two runoff spots in a May 9 general election. Real estate
developer P.J. Morgan slipped past incumbent Mayor Walt Calinger to
capture the other runoff spot.
   ST. LOUIS _ Democratic Mayor Vincent Schoemehl Jr. easily
defeated Republican Bernard J. Elking to win a third term.
   MADISON, Wis. _ Former three-term Mayor Paul Soglin defeated
three-term incumbent Mayor Joseph Sensenbrenner.
   WICHITA, Kan. _ City Councilman Bob Knight defeated businessman
John Bell to become the first elected mayor in 74 years. Voters had
passed a resolution last November to make the job an elective
position.
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Incumbent Mayor Douglas S. Wright was defeated by
former Parks Commissioner Harry Felker III.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER VOTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   ALABAMA CONGRESSIONAL _ Democrat Glen Browder, Alabama's
secretary of state, soundly defeated Republican state Sen. John
Rice for the 3rd District congressional seat left vacant by the
death of Rep. Bill Nichols, a Democrat.
   HANDGUNS _ In Winetka, Ill., a Chicago suburb, voters passed a
non-binding resolution to ban handguns. The measure was prompted by
a shooting spree at an elementary school there last May in which a
woman carrying three handguns shot and killed an 8-year-old boy and
critically wounded several other people, later committing suicide.
   NORTHMOOR, Mo. _ One Ku Klux Klansman and two other men who were
identified as Klan supporters lost their bids for seats on the
board of aldermen and as town marshal in this small community
outside Kansas City.
</TEXT>
