<FIRST>r a PM-TankerCaptain     04-05 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Captain,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Will Give Hazelwood Several More Days To Turn Himself In</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they were getting ready to
pursue the fugitive captain of the oil tanker Exxon Valdez after
waiting in vain a second day for the skipper to surrender.
   The family of Joseph Hazelwood said he wanted to turn himself in
to face charges of operating the vessel while drunk but was
awaiting advice from his lawyer, said Lt. Thomas Fazio, commander
of the New York State Police on New York's Long Island.
   ``Right now if we see him on the streets, we will lock him up,''
Fazio said Tuesday. ``We are anxious to bring him into custody.''
   A lawyer representing Hazelwood had ``continued limited
discussions'' with Suffolk County District Attorney Patrick Henry
on Tuesday, said John Williams, a spokesman for Henry.
   Hazelwood faces three misdemeanor charges in Alaska stemming
from the March 24 grounding of the Valdez, which spilled more than
10 million gallons of oil into Prince William Sound. Exxon fired
the 20-year veteran last week.
   A source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
42-year-old skipper left Anchorage, Alaska, March 28 on a flight
bound for New York. He lives in Huntington, on Long Island.
   The captain's parents, Joseph and Margaret Hazelwood also of
Huntington told police they do not know where their son is.
   ``We talked to his parents,'' Fazio said. ``They told us
something will probably be happening soon. But they said it was up
to the attorney to decide when and where.''
   If Hazelwood doesn't surrender within the next two days police
will actively pursue him, Fazio said.
   Hazelwood is charged with operating a ship while under the
influence of alcohol, reckless endangerment and negligent discharge
of oil. The charges carry a maximum penalty of 2\ years in prison
and a $10,000 fine.
</TEXT>
