<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 0732EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Colombia-Radar     04-05 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Radar,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S Accused of Siting Radar to Monitor Nicarauga Instead of Drug
Trafficking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Colombian government has accused the Defense
Department of using the fight against drugs as a ruse for
installing a radar system on an island to monitor activities in
Nicarauga, a newspaper reported today.
   The Defense Department's insistence on placing the radar on
Colombia's San Andres Island in the Caribbean rather that on its
southern border has hurt attempts to curtail drug operations in
that country, an aide to Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., told The
Boston Globe.
   Richard McCall, Kerry's foreign affairs aide, said Colombia
proposed putting the radar near its border with Brazil to monitor
flights coming into the country from Bolivia, Ecuador and Brazil _
major sources for the raw materials and chemicals used to process
cocaine in Colombia.
   Pentagon officials told the Colombian government they wanted the
radar on San Andres to monitor the export of the finished product.
The Colombians countered that radar there would be of little help
since planes could take many different routes from Colombia, the
newspaper said.
   ``The only utility for that radar was to monitor Nicaragua,''
McCall said.
   San Andres is 200 miles off the Nicaraugan coast, but some 500
miles from Colombia.
   The newspaper said a Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee was
scheduled to take up the radar location issue today.
   The Globe reported that a Defense Department spokesman, Maj.
Michael Stepp, said Tuesday night that the Pentagon had signed an
agreement in February to place radar on San Andres and on
Colombia's northern coast.
   But the Colombian Embassy in Washington insisted no agreement
exists, and negotiations over the radar's placement is continuing.
</TEXT>
