<DOCNO> AP890405-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 0734EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     04-05 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Say Stock Scandal Company Contributed Thousands To Takeshita</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company at the center of a stock scandal that
has shaken the government to its core contributed more than
$380,000 to fund-raising parties for Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita, news reports said today.
   Takeshita had disclosed last Friday that Recruit Co. spent
$152,700 on a fund-raising party for him in May 1987, when he was a
leading contender for leadership of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party and the prime minister's post.
   The nationwide newspaper Asahi Shimbun and other newspapers
reported today that Takeshita received another $229,000 from
Recruit at another fund-raising party that month.
   Asked by reporters about the reports, Takeshita said: ``I can't
comment on the matter because I do not have detailed information.
It is difficult to confirm it quickly.''
   An aide to Takeshita, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed that Recruit had bought tickets to the second party, but
said ``our office did not directly handle the party, so we do not
know the amount.''
   Recruit, an information services conglomerate, sold
bargain-priced unlisted shares in a subsidiary to about 150
influential politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen, who profited
handsomely when public trading in the stocks began.
   So far, 14 bureaucrats and businessmen have been arrested on
bribery or securities law violation charges in connection with the
deals. Three Cabinet ministers have resigned because of links to
the scandal.
   The leaders of four major opposition parties planned to meet
Friday in Kyoto, in western Japan, to discuss forming a coalition
government in hopes Takeshita could be forced to step down.
Meanwhile, lower-level opposition meetings were discussing strategy.
   ``The Takeshita Cabinet is no longer entitled to run the
government,'' Japan Socialist Party Chairwoman Takako Doi told
reporters Tuesday. ``The only alternative left for the government
is to resign en masse and accept the people's judgment.''
   Takeshita has refused to resign, despite public opinion polls
showing approval ratings as low as 9 percent for his government. He
has vowed instead to reform politics and regain public trust.
   Japanese politicians customarily use fund-raising parties to
sidestep legal restrictions on political donations and solicit
funds from business leaders and supporters.
   Large corporations often buy large blocks of party tickets, but
Takeshita acknowledged last week that the $152,700 purchase by
Recruit disclosed then was ``slightly excessive'' for one company.
   There is no legal limit on the amount of money politicians can
raise from such parties. The parties are considered legal ``as long
as the price of each ticket is within the range of common sense and
the number of tickets purchased is within a reasonable limit of
what a company can possibly use,'' said an official at the Home
Affairs Ministry, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The opposition has stalled legislative business but cannot force
Takeshita out. The Liberal Democrats hold 297 of the 512 seats in
parliament's lower house, and 143 of the 252 in the upper house.
   At least 17 politicians, including Takeshita and former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, have been implicated in the scandal,
although none has been arrested.
   Prosecutors reportedly have begun questioning politicians and
their aides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
