<FIRST>r a PM-LettermanIntruder     04-05 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Letterman Intruder,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Believes She's Letterman's Wife Found Incompetent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with breaking into the
home of talk show host David Letterman was sent from prison to a
state hospital by a judge who found her incompetent to stand trial.
   Margaret Ray, who claims to be Letterman's wife, understands the
charges against her but is not capable of assisting in her defense,
Superior Court Judge Harold H. Dean ruled Tuesday.
   Interrupting testimony, Ray said, ``I wanted to plead guilty,
but I wasn't given any credibility for that stance.''
   Ray, 36, was transferred from a prison where she has been held
on $5,000 bond since her arrest in February to state-run Fairfield
Hills Hospital in Newtown.
   The judge ordered the hospital staff to report on Ray's
condition every 90 days. If she is not found competent to stand
trial within 18 months she could be committed to a psychiatric
hospital, Assistant State's Attorney Robert G. Hall Jr. said.
   Ray was charged with break-ins at Letterman's New Canaan home on
Feb. 24 and 28. A psychiatrist found her competent to stand trial,
but her attorney requested review by a three-member panel, whose
report led to Tuesday's ruling.
   A judge previously found Ray incompetent to stand trial last
June after authorities found her driving Letterman's Porsche.
   Mark W. Ford, Letterman's attorney, attended the hearing
Tuesday, but would not comment afterward. He has said that
Letterman does not know Ray.
</TEXT>
