<HEAD>Prosecutors To Charge Suspect In Palme Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said today they will file
charges against a man who was arrested in December and questioned
about the 1986 slaying of Prime Minister Olof Palme.
   After four months of investigation, the prosecutors said they
believe they have compiled enough circumstantial evidence to
convict Christer Pettersson, 42, in the shooting of Palme in
downtown Stockholm. However, they did not say what charges would be
filed against Pettersson.
   Assistant prosecutor Axel Morath asked the Stockholm district
court for 14 more days to prepare the charges. It was not clear
when the trial would begin.
   Palme was gunned down on Feb. 28, 1986, and his wife Lisbet was
grazed by a second bullet. The assailant escaped down a dark alley.
   Palme was a controversial four-term prime minister and champion
of Third World liberation movements and an international
disarmament activist.
   The prosecutors said in a statement today that ``the evidence
against the suspect has been strengthened during the time he has
been detained.'' The communique said ``the evidence is judged to be
so strong that the prosecutors have decided charges should be filed
and the case should be tested in court.''
   ``More time is needed to conclude the investigation,'' the
statement said.
   Swedish newspapers say Pettersson has a long criminal record and
a history of violent behavior, accompanied by drug and alcohol
abuse. Investigators reportedly believe he acted alone but have not
disclosed any motive.
</TEXT>
