<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 0849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Spycatcher     04-05 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spycatcher,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Begins Contempt Proceedings Against Newspapers Over Excerpts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has begun contempt of court
proceedings against three newspapers for printing excerpts of
``Spycatcher,'' the best-selling book by former British
intelligence officer Peter Wright.
   In hearings that began Tuesday in the High Court, government
attorney John Laws described the 74-year-old Wright as ``a
disgraced and discredited former member of the British security
services'' who owed Britain a lifelong ``duty of confidentiality.''
   Wright, now retired, lives in Australia.
   Laws accused The Independent, The Sunday Times and the
now-defunct News on Sunday of committing a ``grave contempt of
court'' for publishing the excerpts in 1987.
   Temporary injunctions, granted by the High Court at the request
of the government in 1987, had banned British newspapers from
publishing excerpts from the book but no longer are enforced.
   If found to have been in contempt of court, the newspapers can
be fined, or, at worst, their editors jailed. The extent of the
fine or jail term is at the discretion of the judge.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government has failed to
suppress the book in three years of court fights in London,
Australia, Hong Kong and elsewhere.
   The government unsuccessfully argued that Wright, once a senior
officer with Britain's counterespionage agency MI5, violated a
pledge by British intelligence officers never to reveal details of
their secret work.
   ``Spycatcher,'' published in 40 countries including the United
States, became a best seller despite government attempts to quash
its publication.
   British authorities made no attempt to stop the book being
brought into Britain, but temporary injunctions banned British news
media from publishing extracts readily available in newspapers
abroad.
   After several court hearings, the Law Lords, Britain's highest
court, last October rejected the government's request to make the
interim injunctions permanent.
   The Law Lords charged Wright with violating his secrecy oath but
lifted the temporary injunctions, saying any damage to British
security already had been caused by the book's publication abroad.
Nevertheless, ``Spycatcher'' effectively has been banned in Britain
as publishers will not publish it for fear of being prosecuted
under the Official Secrets Act.
   In a statement Tuesday, The Independent editor Andreas Whittam
Smith said he decided it was in the public interest to publish
Wright's allegations of treason in MI5.
   ``Spycatcher'' alleges the late MI5 chief Sir Roger Hollis was a
Soviet agent, a claim the government says never was substantiated.
The book also claims MI5 officers eavesdropped on foreign
embassies, bungled operations, stole documents, plotted to
assassinate Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser and plotted to
destabilize Harold Wilson's Labor Party government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 0858EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0494 04-05 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Killing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0494,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorneys Seek Release Of Father Convicted In Children's Poisoning
Deaths</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``He thinks ...' to clarify that York was referring
to Butterworth.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys are seeking the release of a
man whom state officials now agree didn't get a fair trial when he
was convicted in the poisoning deaths of his seven children.
   James J. Richardson, 53, was sentenced to die in the electric
chair after his 1968 trial. His sentence was commuted to life in
prison after the U.S. Supreme Court struck down the death penalty
in 1972.
   Last fall, newspaper reports claimed that prosecutors withheld
evidence from defense attorneys. Richardson's advocates say
prosecutors framed him and suggest DeSoto County officials
protected a more likely suspect, the children's babysitter.
   After months of investigation this year, a special prosecutor
appointed by Gov. Bob Martinez confirmed evidence was withheld and
Attorney General Bob Butterworth concluded Richardson received an
unfair trial.
   Chief Justice Raymond Ehrlich of the Florida Supreme Court said
he intends to appoint a special judge to reconsider Richardson's
conviction.
   In the meantime, Richardson's attorney, Ellis Rubin, said
Tuesday that he has asked that Richardson be released from prison,
and he predicted Richardson could be out this week.
   A clemency hearing had been scheduled for Thursday, but the
governor postponed it after his special prosecutor concluded
evidence was withheld.
   ``He (Butterworth) thinks there's an injustice. He's going to
want to see that guy out yesterday,'' said Jim York, the attorney
general's chief deputy. ``The Constitution doesn't require that
every trial be perfect, but it sure requires that it be fair.''
   Richardson is serving his sentence at the Tomoka Correctional
Institution near Daytona Beach. He is eligible for parole in 1993.
   Once an illiterate and indigent migrant worker, Richardson
educated himself while behind bars and earned the respect of
corrections officials by compiling an immaculate disciplinary
record.
   He was convicted of only one count of first-degree murder for
the death of his eldest child, 8-year-old stepdaughter Betty Jean
Bryant. She and her six siblings, the youngest 2 years old, died
Oct. 25-26, 1967.
   On Oct. 25, they had eaten a lunch of rice, beans, hogshead
cheese and grits that was laced with the pesticide parathion.
   The food had been prepared ahead of time and served at noontime
by their neighbor, Betsy Reese, while Richardson and his wife,
Annie Mae Richardson, were miles away picking oranges.
   Among questions now raised about the prosecution was the
contention that Richardson had purchased life insurance policies
covering the children.
   Jurors weren't told that although Richardson intended to buy the
policies, he hadn't made the first premium payment and the policies
hadn't taken effect when the children were killed.
   In 1970, attorney Mark Lane published a book called ``Arcadia''
in which he concluded Richardson had been railroaded, but nothing
came of it. The family lived in a Arcadia, about 35 miles east of
Sarasota.
   Then, last fall, Rubin and Lane contended the now-senile baby
sitter confessed to the killings.
   A spokesman for Frank Schaub, who prosecuted Richardson,
contends there was no wrongdoing and that if retried today,
Richardson would be convicted.
   ``I don't agree that any evidence was withheld from the
defense,'' said the spokesman, Sarasota attorney Larry Byrd.
   Schaub has filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit against Rubin and
Lane, charging that they defamed him by suggesting last fall that
he should be tried on an attempted murder charge because Richardson
once faced death in the electric chair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0066 </DOCNO>
