<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0527 04-05 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon Fighting Leaves 7 More Dead, 30 Wounded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 5-6, ``Police...forces.'' with 6 grafs to UPDATE
with more casualties, message from pope. Pickup 7th graf, ``Shells fell...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderous blasts echoed across Beirut
and the surrounding mountains today as Syrian and Christian gunners
fought with howitzers and rocket launchers for a fifth straight day.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman denied a radio report that the
residence of U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy in the Christian suburb
of Yarze was on fire after taking a direct hit.
   ``The house of the ambassador has been hit repeatedly during the
last week, and recently some shells fell near the compound, but not
in the compound. There was no fire,'' said the spokesman, speaking
without using his name.
   Police said seven people have been killed and 30 wounded in the
exchanges since midnight Tuesday.
   The latest casualties raised to 162 killed and 536 wounded the
overall toll from the 29-day confrontation between Gen. Michel
Aoun's Christian troops and an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross called on the
combatants to spare the civilian population.
   ``Once again, we call on all parties to respect the basic
humanitarian principles...and respect the civilian population which
is suffering more casualties every day,'' Red Cross chief delegate
Michel Dufour told a news conference at the mission's headquarters
in Moslem west Beirut.
   Dufour said the Red Cross mission in Lebanon had enough supplies
to ``cover emergency needs in Lebanon for the next two or three
months.''
   Pope John Paul II also today appealed for an end to the
``terrible bombardments'' in Lebanon today, saying the fighting
threatened the very existence of the country.
   Shells fell randomly into Christian and Moslem residential areas
despite a call from the Arab League for a cease-fire.
   The appeal was stressed Tuesday by Kuwaiti Foreign Minister
Sheik Sabah Ahmad Sabah upon his arrival in Damascus, Syria. Sabah
was to meet with leftist Lebanese leaders on ways of settling a
six-month political crisis that threatens to cement the nation's de
facto partition.
   ``In the name of the Arab World, in the name of humanity, I
appeal to all to cease firing immediately ... Once the cease-fire
is in force, all solutions are possible,'' said Sabah, who heads a
six-man Arab League panel on Lebanon.
   The Lebanese Front alliance of right-wing Christian factions, in
a statement published today, said it will not take part in talks
with Sabah.
   Aoun's command said in a communique its gunners ``scored direct
hits'' on two Syrian tanks around the mountain resort of Aley,
southeast of Beirut, and a Syrian howitzer emplacement in the
seaside Khaldeh junction, south of Beirut.
   The report could not be verified with the Syrian command.
   However, Syrian army checkpoints in Khaldeh were deserted early
in the day and helmeted soldiers were seen taking cover in foxholes
along the sand coast, an indication the area was under shelling.
   Smoke billowed from the wooded hills of Aramoun where the
Syrians maintain artillery and rocket batteries south of Khaldeh.
   Witnesses said Syrian gunners also opened fire at the
310-square-mile Christian enclave from several rocket launchers
mounted on trucks and driving across several Moslem residential
neighborhoods in west and south Beirut.
   A police spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said Christian
militiamen of the right-wing Lebanese forces alliance opened fire
at Moslem west Beirut from twin-barrelled, anti-aircraft guns.
   He said the rounds from both the mobile launchers and fixed
emplacements in east Beirut are ``exploding in most streets of west
Beirut.''
   A mortar round slammed into a narrow street off west Beirut's
Hamra commercial thoroughfare, seriously wounding two pedestrians,
witnesses said.
   A witness said the mortar round explosion ``chopped off the legs
of a male pedestrian near a stationery shop.
   The current crisis began Sept. 22 when President Amin Gemayel's
six-year term expired with parliament failing to elect a successor.
   Gemayel appointed Aoun head of an interim military cabinet to
rule pending the election of a new president.
   Syrian-backed Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment because it
violated a 45-year-old tradition of having a Sunni Moslem premier,
a Christian president and a Shiite Moslem parliament speaker. They
pledged allegiance to acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni who
governed under Gemayel.
</TEXT>
