<FIRST>r i PM-Gorbachev-Britain     04-05 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-Britain,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Legislators Sign Ad Accusing Soviets of Human Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 legislators from the House of
Commons signed an advertisement in today's Times of London accusing
the Soviet Union of human rights abuses.
   ``We welcome President Gorbachev's arrival in Britain,'' said
the full-page advertisement, which appeared the same day as the
Soviet leader's arrival from Cuba. ``We also welcome the concluding
statement of the Vienna Conference and the Soviet government's
renewed commitments to improving human rights conditions in the
Soviet Union which are contained in it.
   ``We note the British government's conditions for attending the
Moscow human rights conference in 1991 and we would measure Soviet
performance of their commitments against the following checklist:
   ``Freedom to emigrate; freedom of religious and cultural
expression; freedom from discrimination; freedom of all prisoners
of conscience; freedom of speech; freedom to monitor these basic
human rights.
   ``These basic human rights, guaranteed by international law,
continue to be abused in the Soviet Union. We look forward to the
Soviet Union fulfilling its undertakings. At that time we would
feel able to give our warm support to the British government's
attendance at the Moscow human rights conference.''
   The ad was placed by the Parliamentary Committee for the Release
of Soviet Jewry and was signed by 212 of the 650 members of the
House of Commons.
   No ministers in Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
government were among the signatories.
   Mrs. Thatcher in January listed the release of all religious and
political prisoners in the Soviet Union as among Britain's
conditions for attending a 1991 human rights conference in Moscow.
   The human rights group Amnesty International said on Friday that
despite improvements in the Soviet Union, at least 100 dissidents
remained imprisoned there, including 25 in psychiatric hospitals.
   Gorbachev will spend three days in Britain.
   He will have lunch Friday with Queen Elizabeth II at Windsor
Castle and deliver a speech in London's ancient Guildhall, seat of
city government for 1,000 years.
   Mrs. Thatcher and Gorbachev are to sign agreements on visas and
mutual trade promotion and for Britain to rebuild an Armenian
school destroyed in the December earthquake.
</TEXT>
