<HEAD>Vietnam To Withdraw From Cambodia By Sept. 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd pvs, `Today's announcement...' to ADD
possible reasons for move. Pickup 4th pvs, `However, Cambodia...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam announced today it will
withdraw all its troops from Cambodia by Sept. 30, ending a 10-year
occupation and conflict with resistance forces.
   Vietnam previously had said it would withdraw its troops,
estimated at 70,000, by 1990 and would be out by September only if
a political settlement were reached.
   Today's announcement, made simultaneously at news conferences in
Phnom Penh, Hanoi, and Laos, gave no indication conditions were
attached to the September pullout.
   It appeared aimed at removing a major obstacle to peace talks.
It could also enhance Vietnam's efforts to improve relations with
its non-communist neighbors in Southeast Asia, who have been
involved in a major effort to remove Vietnamese forces from
Cambodia and restore peace to the country.
   However, Cambodia would reserve the right to ask for foreign
assistance if anti-government guerrillas threatened the
Vietnamese-backed administration.
   ``Vietnam will withdraw from Kampuchea (Cambodia) all of her
forces by the end of September 1989,'' said a statement read to
reporters by Cambodian Prime Minister Hun Sen.
   He gave no timetable for the pullout.
   ``From now until September, time is very short,'' he said.
``Therefore, the problem of withdrawal by phase or territory is not
of any importance now. What is important is that there will be no
more Vietnamese troops.''
   ``The total withdrawal of Vietnamese forces and the cessation of
all foreign interference and all military aid will put an end to
the civil war and stimulate the Kampuchean parties to settle the
internal aspects of the Kampuchean question before September 1989
on the basis of national reconciliation,'' Hun Sen said.
   He said he would meet with Prince Norodom Sihanouk, leader of
the three-member Cambodian resistance alliance, in Jakarta,
Indonesia, on May 2 in a new effort ``to resolve the problem of
Kampuchea.''
   But he rejected the prince's demand the Vietnamese-backed
government be dissolved prior to a general election. ``Only the
Kampuchean people have the right to dismantle,'' he said. ``The
other side has nothing and they want everything.''
   In a statement released by Sihanouk's Bangkok office, the prince
said the withdrawal should be monitored by the United Nations ``and
not be controlled by countries chosen unilaterally by Vietnam.''
   He said China would end its support for the resistance ``when
the United Nations has verified the reality of this withdrawal,
which has been barely credible so far.''
   Hun Sen's statement said Canada, Poland, Indonesia and India
were invited to jointly monitor the pullout in coordination with a
representative of U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Japan's Kyodo News Service reported that Foreign Minister Nguyen
Co Thach of Vietnam confirmed the pullout during a Hanoi news
conference.
   In Bangkok, Thai Foreign Minister Siddhi Savestila told
reporters he was informed of the Vietnamese decision today during a
meeting with Hanoi's ambassador in Thailand, Le Mai.
   Siddhi said the Vietnamese envoy urged all other countries to
refrain from supporting resistance groups seeking to topple the Hun
Sen government.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and ousted the
government of the communist Khmer Rouge, under which an estimated
one-fourth of the country's 8 million people died from famine and
execution.
   As of August, Vietnamese had about 140,000 troops in Cambodia,
but Vietnam began withdrawing troops last year and an estimated
70,000 remain.
   Siddhi said the Vietnamese ambassador told him there were 50,000
troops left in Cambodia.
   Fear that the Khmer Rouge _ the strongest force in a resistance
coalition _ might return to power has been a major hurdle in
negotiations on a post-occupation coalition government for Cambodia.
   The resistance is led by Prince Sihanouk, the former Cambodian
ruler. It includes the non-communist Khmer People's National
Liberation Front.
   Officials of the Vietnamese-installed Cambodian government had
urged an earlier withdrawal target provided neighboring Thailand
denied the guerrillas sanctuary and other countries stopped arming
the resistance groups.
   Thailand denies providing sanctuary to the guerrillas, but armed
groups move in and out of Cambodia from refugee camps along the
border. China arms the guerrillas while the Soviets support
Vietnamese forces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
