<FIRST>r w PM-Judge-Cranston 1stLd-Writethru a0485 04-05 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge-Cranston, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Judicial Nominee Comes Under Fire From Cranston</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 5, Walker was, to include what court Walker nominated
to.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of President Bush's first nominees for the
judicial bench is coming under heavy fire on Capitol Hill, with
Sen. Alan Cranston urging his defeat over membership in a San
Francisco club that excludes women.
   ``I urge that the nomination of Vaughn Walker not be approved,''
Cranston said Tuesday in a letter to Senate Judiciary Chairman
Joseph Biden, D-Del.
   Cranston's action represented a sharp setback for Walker, a San
Francisco attorney, since negative recommendations from home-state
senators have in some cases proven fatal to candidates for the
federal judiciary.
   There was no certainty, however, that Cranston's recommendation
would wreck the chances of Walker, a Reagan judicial pick whose
nomination was still pending when Congress adjourned last fall.
   Walker was among five Reagan judicial nominees who were stranded
when lawmakers adjourned and whose names have now been resubmitted
to the Senate by Bush for confirmation. He was nominated to U.S.
District Court in San Francisco.
   Cranston took aim at Walker's membership in San Francisco's
Olympic Club, which until recently barred blacks from membership
and still excludes women. One of its best known members was Supreme
Court Justice Anthony Kennedy, but he resigned a month before his
1987 confirmation hearings.
   Cranston said Kennedy's stand stood in ``stark contrast'' to
Walker's attitude toward the club. Walker, himself, was not reached
for comment. His office said he was busy in court.
   ``I have reached the conclusion that his actions with respect to
his membership in a discriminatory club are disqualifying,''
Cranston said.
   Learning of Cranston's action, an aide to California's other
senator, Pete Wilson, R-Calif., long a champion of Walker's cause,
said the attorney had resigned from the club a month ago.
   ``He said he wanted to enact reforms internally and if he were
unsuccessful in gaining the changes he wanted, then he would resign
from the club,'' press secretary Bill Livingston said.
   Cranston press secretary Murray Flander retorted that ``nobody
on the Judiciary Committee has been told that, and even if true it
wouldn't change Alan's mind because he was just too slow.''
   In his letter, Cranston said Walker's ``persistent refusal to
terminate his membership in this club and his testimony regarding
this issue ... demonstrate an attitude and an insensitivity which
is unacceptable for a member of the federal judiciary.''
   He cited Canon 2 of the American Bar Association Code of
Judicial Conduct, which holds that ``it is inappropriate for a
judge to hold membership in any organization that practices
invidious discrimination on the basis of race, sex, religion or
national origin.''
   The senator quoted Walker testimony June 13 before the Judiciary
Committee that ``in the past, there had been no formal exclusion of
blacks or, indeed, any other racial minorities.''
   He said this was contradicted by an Aug. 8 letter to the
Judiciary Committee in which George Riley, a special assistant to
the San Francisco city attorney, said the club's bylaws
``restricted membership to `only white male citizens of the United
States of good moral character, integrity and reputation.''' The
policy was challenged in 1967 by community groups, and the club
dropped the ban against minorities a year later.
   Cranston said Walker told the panel the club had made
``substantial'' change in regard to this policy when, according to
Riley, the club had ``announced that it had admitted two black men
into its membership of more than 4,700 members.''
   The Judiciary Committee received a June 30 press release issued
by the club describing certain procedures as designed to avoid
coverage under a San Francisco ordinance barring discrimination,
Cranston said.
   He quoted the press release as saying the club acted to ``defend
the fundamental rights of its members against the strong arm of
political oppression.''
   Such action, Cranston said, was ``wholly inconsistent with Mr.
Walker's characterization of an organization voluntarily moving
toward compliance with basic civil rights principles.'' The senator
also criticized a statement that a vote to drop a bar against women
members was ``very close'' when in fact it was 1,540 to 2,082.
</TEXT>
