<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-UprisingSong     04-05 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Uprising Song,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Radio Restricts Broadcast Of Uprising Song</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Armed Forces radio restricted broadcasts of
a newly released Israeli pop song about the Palestinian uprising,
saying the subject is sensitive, an army official said today.
   The song, ``The Flood Is Behind Us,'' written and sung by Nurit
Galron, implies that Israelis in coastal Tel Aviv show indifference
toward Arab suffering in the 16-month rebellion in the occupied
territories.
   The military station played the song several times before
station commander Nahman Shai ordered that it be played only with
his consent, two Israeli dailies, Hadashot and Maariv, said.
   ``It is an unusual step, but we are a military framework and
some consider this sensitive because it discusses the uprising,''
said an official in Shai's office, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Hadashot said Shai criticized the song as ``a glorification of
the subject, with lines that are hard to accept.''
   Part of the song's lyrics, are:
   ``There is a country of stones and firebombs,
   And there is a Tel Aviv on fire with nightclubs and lewdness.
   There is a country of rebels where the wounded are being
bandaged,
   And there is a Tel Aviv that makes merry with food and drink.
   No, don't tell me about a little girl who lost an eye,
   It only makes me feel bad.
   I don't feel like hearing about people oppressed or tortured,
   I don't care what is happening in the territories ....
   We will make love and live our lives. Tel Aviv is life.''
   Last year, Israeli radio stations restricted broadcast of
another protest song about Israel's handling of the uprising called
``Shooting and Crying,'' by rock star Cy Hyman.
   The uprising, which began Dec. 8, 1987, has claimed the lives of
419 Palestinians in the territories as well as 18 Israelis.
</TEXT>
