<FIRST>r w PM-PayRaise 1stLd-Writethru a0503 04-05 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pay Raise, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Considering Judicial Pay Raise</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Recasts to move pay figure to lead; reworks thruout; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is weighing the possibility of
asking Congress to approve a 25 percent pay raise for federal
judges, a senior administration official said today.
   This official, discussing Bush's options on grounds he not be
named publicly, also said, however, that ``no final decision memo''
has reached the president's desk.
   Bush had said last week that he intends to make ``very specific
proposals'' on pay increases for top federal officials, even though
Congress two months ago rejected a proposal that would have given
lawmakers a 50 percent pay raise. This proposal, advanced by the
Commission on Legislative, Executive and Judicial Salaries, also
would have included substantial hikes for the judiciary and
approximately 7,000 top executives.
   The Bush administration official said today that among other
options still under consideration at the White House is a series of
pay hikes for certain categories of federal officials, rather than
a single, across-the-board raise for these officials.
   The Washington Post initially reported in its Wednesday editions
that Bush would propose a 25 per pay hike for the judges. Most
federal judges now make $89,500 per year, the same salary as
members of Congress and top federal officials.
   One administration source said that Bush had not yet settled on
a figure. But another official noted that a commission studying
public service jobs in the federal government had recommended a 25
percent pay raise, and that that figure was the one being focused
on by the White House. The commission, headed by former Federal
Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker, made its report public late last
month.
   Bush's plan is expected to be announced next week, White House
officials have said, and presidential advisers were said today to
be discussing which federal officials to peg for raises in addition
to the federal judges.
   The president also is preparing a package of ethics legislation,
and the administration hasn't decided whether to tie the two issues
together.
   The 50 percent hike was voted down by Congress in February after
a rising tide of public opposition to the pay hike.
</TEXT>
