<FIRST>r a PM-UndercoverBeating     04-05 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Undercover Beating,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Says Fellow Officers Attacked Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black police officer has filed a lawsuit
against three fellow officers and the city of Oakland, saying the
officers hit him with their car and beat him before recognizing him
as an undercover colleague.
   Derrick Norfleet, then 25 and a police officer for two years,
said he had just finished making an undercover drug purchase in
July when he was chased, hit by a patrol car, and kicked and beaten
while he lay face down. The beating stopped only after he rolled
over and the officers saw his face, he said.
   ``Mr. Norfleet appears to have been assaulted for no other
reason than that he appeared to be just another black person who
may or may not have committed some criminal offense,'' said his
lawyer, John Burris.
   He said the officers who attacked his client were two whites and
an Asian.
   Police Chief George Hart and city lawyers did not return
telephone calls about the case. The city denied Norfleet's
administrative claim for damages in December.
   The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, seeks at
least $500,000 in damages against the city for emotional distress,
and another $1 million in punitive damages against the three
officers. It comes a day after criminal charges were filed against
two Long Beach police officers in an incident in which a black
police officer posing as a motorist was shoved through a window.
   Norfleet's lawsuit said he was on an assignment to buy drugs
undercover and provide information to uniformed officers who would
arrest the sellers. He said he had made his purchase at a home and
was walking through a park when he realized he was being pursued by
a car occupied by the uniformed officers.
   Thinking a ``simulated arrest'' was about to take place,
Norfleet first started to run away, but then stopped and stood with
his hands in the air and his back to the car, the lawsuit said.
   He said the car sped up and hit him from behind, sending him
over the hood and onto the ground. As he lay face down, he said,
three officers got out and struck him with their fists, feet and a
flashlight. He then rolled over and the three, on the same
narcotics assignment as Norfleet, recognized him, the lawsuit said.
   ``Even if he had been a criminal, no conduct that he engaged in
was provocative or aggressive,'' Burris said.
   Burris said Norfleet suffered mainly bumps and bruises and was
on disability leave for a short period before returning to the
police force, where he still works. The most serious effects were
psychological, the lawyer said, the result of ``a horrible
nightmarish experience which he has relived often.''
   The suit accuses the three officers of ``a racially motivated
misuse of government power.'' It says the city and its Police
Department had ``an informal custom or policy of condoning and
encouraging the use of excessive force and the infliction of
summary corporal punishment against black citizens.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
