<DOCNO> AP890405-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 0953EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-IRA     04-05 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-IRA,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Flawed Inquest Into Killings Failed to Get Truth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer who observed the inquest into the
shooting of three unarmed IRA members in Gibraltar last year says
the inquiry was flawed, fell short of international legal standards
and raised doubt about the legality of the killings.
   The inquest raised ``serious doubt as to whether U.K. law on the
use of force meets international standards,'' Hilary Kitchin wrote
in her report released today. It urged another inquiry into the
March 6, 1988, deaths of Mairead Farrell, Daniel McCann and Sean
Savage, who were shot in Gibraltar by British anti-terrorist
operatives.
   The government alleged they were plotting a car bombing in the
British colony on the southern tip of Spain, and the Irish
Republican Army acknowledged the three were on an ``active
service'' mission.
   It was later revealed, contrary to initial government accounts,
that the three were unarmed and that no car bomb was found.
   Amnesty International and other human rights groups then called
for an independent inquiry into whether lethal force was necessary.
   The 19-day inquest in September ruled 9-2 the killings were
lawful.
   Ms. Kitchin, sent to the inquest as an observer by Britain's
National Council for Civil Liberties and the New York-based
International League for Human Rights, said the hearing left some
questions unanswered. She called for a judicial inquiry with wider
powers than the Gibraltar coroner's.
   The government had no comment on Ms. Kitchin's report,
reiterating that it stood by the initial verdict.
   Ms. Kitchen said Coroner Felix Pizzarello should have questioned
witnesses more fully and that the government lawyer, responsible
for representing the public interest, was in fact ``representing
parties with a definite interest in the outcome.''
   It noted there were contradictory reports of Spanish-British
cooperation in tracking the trio's movements before they entered
Gibraltar.
   British authorities told the inquest there was no such
surveillance.
   ``It is a matter of serious concern that the contradictory
Spanish accounts ... were excluded from consideration at the
inquest,'' Ms. Kitchin wrote.
   She said no testimony was taken from witnesses who might have
shed light on a controversial description of a man shooting Savage
and then pumping bullets into him as he lay on the ground.
   Kenneth Asquez, a Gibraltar bank clerk, gave that account to a
television crew but retracted it at the inquest with an
``unsatisfactory'' explanation, the report said.
   ``Normal police procedures were forgotten at the scene of the
shootings,'' Ms. Kitchin wrote. Spent cartridges weren't marked,
the bodies weren't photographed where they lay, and the
post-mortems were flawed, her report said.
   The coroner failed to use his power to disqualify jurors who
might be biased through being employed by or related to members of
the armed forces, the lawyer wrote.
   The coroner also misdirected the jury into thinking its only
choice was between ruling the killings lawful or unlawful, she
said, and the jury ``may have felt under pressure'' to reach a
speedy verdict when it was told, less than six hours after
retiring, that time was running out.
</TEXT>
