<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1010EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LotteryWinner     04-05 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lottery Winner,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse Finally Becomes Big Lotto Winner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nurse who thought she was a millionaire for
five seconds before the California Lottery reduced her fortune to
$10,000 has won her $3 million back and then some.
   A Superior Court jury ruled Tuesday that Doris Barnett was
entitled to the larger payoff plus $400,000 in damages.
   Deputy Attorney General Norman Peek, representing the State
Lottery, said the verdict probably would be appealed.
   Ms. Barnett won the right to appear on California Lottery's Big
Spin on Dec. 30, 1985. In the contest, players spin a wheel, watch
a ball bounce around and fall into a slot labeled with a sum of
money. The lowest amount that can be won is $10,000.
   When Ms. Barnett spun the wheel, the ball fell into the $3
million hole and show host Geoff Edwards proclaimed her a
multimillion-dollar winner.
   Then the ball slipped out of the hole and into a $10,000 slot.
The lottery awarded Ms. Barnett the lesser amount, contending the
ball failed to stay in the $3 million slot for five seconds as
required under lottery law.
   In closing arguments last week, Ms. Barnett's attorney, Lawrence
Sperber, argued that the five-second rule was superseded when
Edwards declared her a winner.
   ``If they're not going to wait five seconds, then they can't
come into this courtroom today and say to you that she had to wait
five seconds,'' he asked.
   Peek argued that Edwards was mistaken when he made the early
announcement. He said Ms. Barnett was aware of the five-second rule.
   ``She agreed when she bought her ticket to abide by the rules _
all of them,'' he said. ``I think Ms. Barnett is asking for you to
make an exception for her.''
   ``It feels so wonderful,'' Ms. Barnett, 54, said after the
verdict was announced. ``I'm going to take care of my mother and
take care of my children. I want to send my kids to school to get
them some of the opportunities I didn't have.''
</TEXT>
