<FIRST>r a PM-BoldBanker     04-05 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bold Banker,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banker Fears Police Delay, Stops Robber Himself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DERRY, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank president who feared that police
wouldn't arrive in time to stop a would-be robber blocked the man's
escape and persuaded him to return the money he had taken.
   ``I wanted him to be apprehended, so I followed him,'' Robert
Smith, president of Derry Bank and Trust, said after the robbery
Tuesday.
   William Abrams, 29, of Derry, was arrested shortly after the
robbery and was held on $10,000 bond on a robbery charge.
   Smith said tellers called his attention to a suspicious-looking
man as the person entered the bank.
   ``When I saw the guy on our video (monitor), I said, `I think we
are going to get it.'''
   The man approached a teller, pulled out a knife and yelled,
``This is a robbery.'' At that point, Smith told another teller to
call police.
   The robber took an undetermined amount of money and headed for
the door, but was blocked by Smith.
   ``I said, `Leave the money and I'll let you go,''' Smith said.
``But he didn't want to do that.''
   The man headed for another door and again was stopped by Smith,
who told the man he had called police and persuaded him to return
the money. But when Smith suggested that he sit down and wait for
officers to arrive, the man fled.
   Smith said he chased the suspect because, if the stolen cash had
left the building, ``then the FBI would have been down here messing
around for three days. Things go a lot easier if you can get the
guy, rather than let him go.''
</TEXT>
