<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     04-05 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistan Dismisses Afghanistan's Call For Emergency UN Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today dismissed as
propaganda Afghanistan's request that the U.N. Security Council
hold an emergency meeting to discuss the Afghan war.
   In a letter requesting the meeting, Afghanistan alleged that
Pakistani support for Moslem guerrillas threatened to create a
``serious regional conflict.''
   A Pakistan Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said, ``The effort is being made to externalize the
problem and we don't appreciate that. It is a propaganda move to
involve the Security Council.''
   Pakistan has been the conduit for millions of dollars in
military hardware supplied to the insurgents by their backers,
particularly the United States. Pakistan denies persistent Afghan
government allegations that it has troops fighting alongside the
guerrillas.
   Moslem guerrillas, also backed by several Arab states, have
waged a decade-long war against the communist government, which for
nine years received military backing from the Soviet Union. On Feb.
15, the Soviet army completed its withdrawal from Afghanistan in
accordance with a U.N.-mediated agreement.
   The Pakistani spokesman said Afghanistan's ruling Marxists are
trying to draw the 15-nation Security Council into what is now an
internal conflict.
   Pakistan's official news agency, APP, said Pakistan's U.N.
ambassador, S. Shah Nawaz, told Security Council chief Aleksander
Belongov of the Soviet Union the situation does not warrant a
council meeting because it poses no threat to regional peace and
security. It is an internal matter for the Afghans to settle
themselves, he was quoted as saying.
   Also today, Afghanistan announced it was putting two Pakistani
nationals on trial for allegedly spying. Official Afghan media said
the two were captured inside Afghanistan more than three weeks ago.
   An Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman, Mohammad Nabi Amani, told
reporters in Kabul both men confessed. An espionage conviction
carries a prison sentence of 10 to 20 years. The Pakistani Foreign
Ministry spokesman said there was no proof the two are Pakistani
nationals.
</TEXT>
