<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Britain-Strike     04-05 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Strike,0189</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wildcat Strike Cuts London Subway Service By Half</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 24-hour wildcat strike by train drivers on
London's subway halted half the 254-mile network today, London
Regional Transport reported.
   The pay strike, coinciding with a snowstorm, upset travel plans
for many of the 3 million people who use London's underground train
system each day.
   ``Clearly it's a large proportion of the Underground,'' said a
spokesman for London Regional Transport, the government-appointed
board that runs the 126-year-old system. Only three of the 10
subway lines were operating fully after 256 of 476 drivers on the
morning shift stayed away.
   Subway cars grew crowded on these and another three lines that
offered a fraction of their normal services. Four lines were halted
completely, the spokesman said.
   To cut costs, the board wants to phase out conductors
responsible for opening and closing train doors. Drivers have
demanded more cash for operating trains without conductors. The
board has refused their demand.
   The transport spokesman said he did not know how many of drivers
would show up in the afternoon. The subway employs 2,400 drivers.
</TEXT>
