<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil     04-05 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>33 People Injured In Riot At Rio Train Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commuters rioted at Rio's main
train station after drivers announced an impromptu wage strike, and
33 people were injured when police shot and clubbed the protesters,
witnesses and doctors said.
   Riot police took control of Rio's Central station at about 6:00
p.m. Tuesday after drivers, demanding better pay and shorter
shifts, refused to move packed commuter trains, Sandra da Silva, a
station employee, said.
   The angry crowd shouted and threw stones at police, who opened
fire when protesters began attacking incoming city buses, da Silva
said.
   Television footage showed screaming mobs shattering bus
windshields, police beating protesters with rubber truncheons and
gunshot victims being carried to ambulances. Dr. Marcos
Albuquerque, head of Rio's Souza Aguiar Hospital emergency ward,
said eight people were shot and 25 seriously hurt in the clash.
   Train drivers are demanding a cut in their work shift from eight
to six hours, wage increases and improved safety conditions, Ertha
Murcia Buys, director of the Railworkers Union said.
   The average wage for drivers is $40 for a 48-hour work week.
   ``The trains are run with the minimum of safety standards,''
said Buys.
   The trains carry about 1 million commuters a day, mostly from
Rio's slum suburbs. Most commuters work in Rio as manual laborers
or maids.
</TEXT>
