<SECOND>PM-BRF--Cursed Ticket,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Apologizes to Man Who Wrote Obscenity on Traffic Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was charged with harassment for
scribbling an obscenity on a parking ticket and sending it with
payment to the city has won an apology and $7,380 to cover his
legal fees.
   Last August Rochester dismissed the second-degree harassment
charge against George Morgenstern, who then filed a $1.8 million
lawsuit in federal court claiming his right to free speech had been
violated by the leveling of the charge against him.
   The lawsuit was settled out of court Tuesday.
   Morgenstern, 41, wrote the obscenity on the back of a $12
parking ticket he received June 4.
   Parking Violations Bureau supervisor Lester Roden Jr., who filed
the charge against Morgenstern, signed the letter of apology, said
Municipal Lawyer Patrick Naylon.
