<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--ParkingLotJustice     04-05 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Parking Lot Justice,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Holds Court In Parking Lot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A big stink closed the Kanawha County
courthouse, but it didn't stop a circuit judge from dispensing some
parking lot justice.
   As lawyers, clerks and judges arrived for work Monday, they were
told to wait outside until an odor, probably sewer gas, could be
cleared from the building.
   Chief Judge Herman Canady later ordered the Judicial Annex
closed for the day.
   Judge Paul Zakaib Jr. decided to hold court in the annex parking
lot. Attorneys who had scheduled hearings in his courtroom agreed
to the procedure.
   In a dispute over a rental property, Zakaib leaned against a car
while the lawyers presented their arguments.
   ``You've got to use the time you have,'' Zakaib said. ``I
disposed of my personal docket.''
