<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1104EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Election     04-05 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Election,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>88 Percent of Deputies Elected to Soviet Parliament Party Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the striking election defeat of many top
communists, Soviet voters chose party members for 88 percent of the
parliament seats that have been filled so far, the Communist Party
daily Pravda reported today.
   About 80 percent of candidates running in the Soviet Union's
first multicandidate elections in seven decades were Communist
Party members. They were running for the country's new 2,250-member
Congress of Peoples Deputies.
   Pravda, citing official results released Tuesday, said voters in
one out of every eight Soviet parliamentary districts on March 26
refused to elect anyone even though they had a choice of only one
or two candidates.
   That means that in 195 of the 1,500 geographical districts
across the country, and in three others in which less than 50
percent of the electorate voted, new campaigns will start for a
second election to be held May 14.
   The official news agency Tass said runoff elections will be held
in 76 other districts on Sunday for seats in which the vote was so
split among three or more candidates that no one received a
majority.
   Party officials and party-dominated bodies selected the
remaining 750 members to the new congress, which will choose a new
Supreme Soviet, the policy-making body.
   Across the country 89.8 percent of the voters took part in the
election, Orlov told Tass, adding:
   ``That high degree of activity gladdens us more than the
notorious 99.9 percent participation which we were proud of
earlier. In this election there was no race for percentage of
participation, the previous mandatory measures practiced previously
were fully excluded.''
   The Soviet Union in the past proclaimed an almost total
participation in elections as proof of citizens' satisfaction, even
though voters were not offered a choice.
</TEXT>
