<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HitlerHouse     04-05 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hitler House,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Fascist Memorial Stone Put Up In Front Of Hitler's Birthplace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAUNAU, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials today put up an
anti-fascist memorial in front of the house where Adolf Hitler was
born. The installation came just two weeks before the 100th
anniversary of his birth.
   Mayor Gerhard Skiba ordered the block, made from granite
quarried at a former Nazi death camp, to be put on public property
outside the house, which is now a school for retarded children.
   City spokesman Johann Dax said the memorial ``is to help to
express the opinion of the city of Braunau as a rebuttal to the
often one-sided sensational reporting'' on this city.
   He said it was put up without ceremony or incidents.
   Dax said he has no knowledge of Nazi demonstrations planned for
April 20 _ Hitler's 100th birthday _ but police were said to be
taking every possible precaution to avoid disturbances.
   They approved an April 20 anti-fascist demonstration by
university students, but all other rallies are banned.
   Occasional clashes between neo-Nazi activists and police have
broken out near the Hitler house, and the idea to place a plaque
was prompted by officials' desire to improve the city's image.
   City officials have long been worried by the flow of tourists
getting photographed in front of the house.
   The memorial is made of granite from the quarry of the
Mauthausen concentration camp, where tens of thousands of Jews,
gypsies and others died under the Nazi dictator. It measures 46 by
41 by 28 inches.
   An inscription says, ``For Peace, Freedom and Democracy. Never
Again Fascism. Millions of Dead Warn.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
