<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Defector     04-05 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Defector,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Official Blames Father for Young Chess Player's Defection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old Soviet chess whiz who defected last
week in New York is the victim of exploitation by his money-hungry
father, a Soviet chess official was quoted today as saying.
   Gata Kamsky ``is destined to become a robot for earning dollars,
and his father has consciously agreed to that,'' Alexander Roshal,
editor of the Soviet chess journal 64-Chess Review, told the
newspaper Sovietsky Sport.
   A friend of the Kamsky family, chess champion Lev Alburt, said
in New York last week that the boy defected with his father because
he wanted the freedom to make choices about his chess career and
his personal future. Alburt is a Soviet grand master who defected
10 years ago.
   Roshal maintained that the Kamsky family had been very well
treated by the Soviet chess establishment, and it called their
defection a case of ``the blackest ingratitude.''
   Roshal told Sovietsky Sport that Kamsky had played in five
masters tournaments over the last year, placing average or lower in
all of them. He defected during the New York Open tournament, at
which he was the youngest member of the Soviet delegation.
   Roshal accused Kamsky's father, Rustem, of pressuring his son so
heavily that the boy's performance suffered.
   ``Acting as coach and manager of his son, he demanded results
from Gata whatever the cost, without stopping short of beating him,
according to many accounts,'' Roshal was quoted as saying.
   Asked if he thought Kamsky had turned from a ``caring daddy''
into a ``greedy exploiter,'' Roshal said, ``It looks that way.''
   Gata Kamsky has been called the Soviet Union's leading young
chess player. World champion Garry Kasparov and other experts have
predicted Kamsky will reach the highest echelons of chess play.
   Other top Soviet chess players who defected include former world
championship finalist Victor Korchnoi, who now plays for
Switzerland, and International Master Igor Ivanov, now Canada's
second-ranked player.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
