<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   04-05 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: endangered species.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 30
   The News and Courier, Charleston, S.C., on Three Mile Island's
legacy:
   It seems almost incredible that 10 years have flown by since the
``accident'' at Three Mile Island.
   It seems incredible, too, that this one misfortune, bred more by
gross negligence on the part of the operators than by any inherent
design faults in the nuclear power plant there, should have stopped
an entire industry dead in its tracks. ...
   Historians one day will look back on the incident at Three Mile
Island and shake their heads in wonder at America's reaction to it.
   Perhaps then, if we are lucky, scientists will have harnessed a
new form of energy _ clean efficient and safe solar cells, nuclear
fusion, or things undreamed of today.
   If we are not lucky, those who survive may live in a dark and
desolate world, where the sea rolls 40 fathoms deep over
once-lovely coastal cities ..., and the sun, dull red, burns in a
yellow, birdless sky.
   This would be the real legacy of Three Mile Island.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 29
   The Intelligencer, Wheeling, W.Va., on curbing acid rain:
   During his campaign for the presidency, George Bush promised
acid rain legislation. The White House chief of staff, former New
Hampshire Gov. John Sununu, has fought for pollution reduction for
years. Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, long has
pushed for passage of acid rain legislation.
   Given these political imperatives, it is obvious that this is
the year an acid rain bill is going to pass Congress, although coal
industry officials remain unconvinced that there is any real need
for such legislation. ...
   Proposed legislation which has aroused substantial support has
resulted from an unlikely coalition _ Rich Trumka, president of the
United Mine Workers, and Sen. Mitchell.
   Their bill calls for having electricity consumers pay a small
fee of about 75 cents a month to help defray industry's cost of
installing new scrubbers in order to meet a goal of reducing the
level of sulphur dioxide emissions by 10 million tons. ...
   The Mitchell-Trumka bill appears to be about as good a deal on
acid rain as the industry can expect.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 30:
   The Westerly (R.I.) Sun on airline terrorism:
   Transportation Secretary Samuel K. Skinner says that he and
European officials plan to develop ``a unified, global approach to
the threat of terrorism'' in civil aviation.
   Good. The wonder is that, after years of terrorist activity
involving commercial aircraft, such an initiative is only now
getting under way.
   Aviation authorities here and abroad seem agreed on asserting
that all appropriate precautions were taken prior to the Pan AM 103
disaster at Lockerbie in December. These protestations do not
wholly jibe with the facts that have come to light. ...
   We are inclined to concur in the advice of Sen. Alfonse M.
D'Amato of New York in a letter to Skinner and Secreary of State
James A. Baker: ``The entire process of receiving and evaluating
security information must be reviewed from top to bottom.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 2
   The Natchez (Miss.) Democrat on private school tuition tax
credits:
   President Bush took the correct position when he came down on
the side of public education and said he does not support the idea
of tuition tax credits for parents of children in private schools.
   Bush's statement runs counter to the general position taken
during the Reagan administration.
   The president is correct in stating that people have the right
to choose to send their children to a private or parochial school.
   However, the public school system must be kept strong for the
good of the entire community. It must have the resources to do that
job.
   If those resources were diluted by tuition tax credits for
parents of private school students, it would make an uphill battle
even more difficult.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 3
   Pittsburgh Post-Gazette on Islamic fundamentalism:
   The only saving grace is that ... fanaticism has turned most of
the Moslem world against Iran's brand of revolution.
   Still, recent events in Iran are sadly reminiscent of the
Cultural Revolution in China initiated by Mao Zedong in 1966 to
``complete'' the Communist revolution of 1949.
   That devastating crusade against everything not totally Marxist
lasted until his death in 1976 _ a disquieting omen for any
suggestion of change in Iran's new course so long as (Ayatollah
Ruhollah) Khomeini is alive.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
