<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSTrial     04-05 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Trial,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor, AIDS Patient Reach Six-Figure Settlement Before Verdict Returned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS patient who sued his doctor for
negligence reached a six-figure settlement with him today shortly
before a jury returned with a verdict in favor of the physician.
   Robert Taylor, 36, of Norfolk, had sued Dr. Duane G. Wombolt, a
kidney specialist, alleging that the doctor failed to tell him that
he had tested positive for antibodies to the AIDS virus and had
given him medication that hastened the onset of the fatal disease.
   After a weeklong trial, a Circuit Court jury began deliberating
late Tuesday. Before jurors returned with a verdict this morning,
lawyers reached a settlement that both sides said was in six
figures.
   Judge John Winston told jurors that a settlement had been
reached and did not let them announce their verdict.
   ``We had decided for the defendant, Dr. Wombolt,'' said one
juror who asked not to be identified. ``All the facts in the case
pointed to the fact that he was absolutely reasonable in everything
he did.''
   ``I feel a little cheated, in a way,'' said John Heilig, an
attorney for Wombolt, on learning that the verdict would have been
in his client's favor.
   ``I'm elated,'' Taylor said, when asked about the settlement.
Taylor, who is thin and has facial lesions caused by AIDS, said he
plans to use the money to travel and for charitable causes,
including perhaps an AIDS hospice.
   Heilig said he and Wombolt agreed to settle because they were
concerned that the jury might be hung.
   Heilig said Wombolt admitted to no wrongdoing in his treatment
of Taylor.
   ``He did nothing wrong,'' Heilig said.
   Taylor, a former waiter, testified last week that he asked
Wombolt in December 1986 whether he might have AIDS and the doctor
told him he had no symptoms of the disease.
   Wombolt said a hospital that tested Taylor for AIDS never told
him what the test showed, so he assumed the test was negative.
   Taylor's physician, Dr. John F. Warner, testified that Taylor's
kidneys are functioning close to normal but he will probably die of
AIDS within a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
