<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial 1stLd-Writethru   04-05 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0596,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charter 77 Leader Gets Suspended Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with outcome of second court case.
Pickup 3rd pvs, `Charges agains...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak court today sentenced a
Charter 77 human rights activist to a 13-month suspended sentence
for inciting rebellion and trying to harm state interests, emigre
sources said.
   The sources, who demanded anonymity, said another court
acquitted an actress accused of interfering with a state
investigation of an activist.
   The activist, Tomas Hradilek, was convicted and sentenced to 13
months by a court in Moravia, but the sentence was suspended two
years, said the sources.
   The sources said another court in Moravia acquitted Eva
Vidlarova, who was charged with obstructing the execution of a
state decision. If convicted, she could have been jailed up to five
years.
   Ms. Vidlarova, a leading actress in Brno, Moravia, was detained
Dec.19 after she allegedly obstructed a legal investigation against
another independent cultural activist.
   Charges against Hradilek, a spokesman for the Charter 77 human
rights group, were based on two letters he wrote last month to
Communist Party leader Milos Jakes and President Gustav Husak
protesting police violence used to break up peaceful gatherings in
January.
   On Tuesday, a Prague municipal court upheld sentences against
seven activists charged in connection with the banned January
demonstrations.
   They included a second Charter spokesman, Alexander Vondra.
Another group spokesman, Dana Nemcova, is hospitalized, but also
faces charges of hooliganism connected to the January rallies.
   Also Tuesday, activist Jaroslav Popelka was sentenced to four
months' jail for disturbing public order by distributing leaflets
calling for genuine reform and environmental protection.
</TEXT>
