<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine     04-05 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assistant DA's Involved In Adams Case Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prosecutors involved in the case of ``The Thin
Blue Line'' defendant Randall Dale Adams have resigned.
   The Dallas Morning News today quoted an unidentified source who
said the assistant district attorneys' resignations this week were
related to the office's handling of the case.
   ``It's just time to move on,'' John Creuzot, 31, told the
newspaper. Creuzot had been with the Dallas County district
attorney's office more than six years. The other prosecutor
resigning was Leslie McFarlane, 32.
   The district attorney's office had come under national scrutiny
for its handling of Adams' conviction and retrial attempts. Adams
was imprisoned for 12 years, during one period when he was
condemned to death, for the 1976 slaying of Dallas police officer
Robert Wood.
   Adams was freed March 22 and District Attorney John Vance
announced the next day 23 that his office would not retry Adams
because of a lack of evidence and witnesses.
   The case was featured in last year's film documentary ``The Thin
Blue Line,'' directed by Errol Morris, which questioned Adams'
conviction.
   Creuzot and Ms. McFarlane represented the district attorney's
office in the December hearing at which state District Judge Larry
Baraka recommended a new trial for Adams.
   The two filed a brief with the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals
saying the district attorney's office didn't object to a new trial.
   Ms. McFarlane also testified that former assistant district
attorney Doug Mulder, the original prosecutor, suppressed evidence
in the 1977 trial.
   Assistant District Attorney Winfield Scott, who was involved in
jury selection in the original trial and was responsible for the
case during retrial hearings, had criticized Ms. McFarlane for not
being more aggressive.
   Both resignations take effect this month. McFarlane and Creuzot
reportedly were starting private law practices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
