<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   04-05 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0587,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Palestinian Prisoners Released on Eve of Ramadan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with more prisoners released. Pickup
3rd, `About two...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today freed more than 430
Palestinian prisoners as a Moslem holiday gesture that also
coincided with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's talks with U.S.
leaders in Washington.
   According to army figures, 224 detainees were bused to the Gaza
Strip and 210 were sent to the West Bank.
   About two dozen of the detainees knelt on the ground and uttered
prayers of thanks before being embraced by friends and relatives, a
witness in Gaza City said. One detainee said he was 12 years old.
   Israeli authorities said the releases were a gesture on the eve
of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan, which starts Friday.
   ``We wanted by this gesture to deliver a message to the
Palestinians in the territories that we bear in mind your holy
days,'' Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin told reporters. ``Hopefully
they understand that we would like to see tranquility restored and
we can do it on the one hand by force, on the other hand by
gestures.''
   Also today, soldiers shot and wounded two Palestinians in the
occupied lands, Arab reports said. The army confirmed one wounding
_ that of a 13-year-old in a stone-throwing clash near the Balata
refugee camp in the West Bank.
   Arab reports also said a 14-year-old in Gaza City was shot and
hospitalized in serious condition.
   Israeli news reports noted that the prisoner releases came as
Shamir headed to Washington, where he was expected to come under
pressure from American leaders to take steps that would ease
tensions in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Haaretz newspaper said the decision for the gesture was
timed so that the prisoners would be freed before Shamir met
President Bush.
   The prisoners freed were among about 10,000 Palestinians
believed held in connection with the nearly 16-month uprising,
which has killed at least 419 Palestinians and 18 Israelis.
   Those released had either been charged with stone-throwing
assaults on Israelis or were detained without trial as alleged
inciters of disturbances.
   In addition to the releases, Gaza's military governor, Brig.
Gen. Arieh Ramot, announced Tuesday he had ordered the army to stay
away from schools and mosques ``because I know how sensitive
Ramadan is for Moslems, and we have no intention of killing or
wounding anyone in the strip.''
   Ramadan, the most important holiday for Moslems, marks the
period when the Prophet Mohammed began receiving the Koran, or
Moslem holy book, from God.
   More than 80 percent of the 1.7 million Palestinians in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip are Moslems.
   Other measures taken by the Israelis included lifting curfews
that confined tens of thousands of Palestinians to their homes in
villages and refugee camps.
   But five refugee camps in Gaza remained under curfew, among them
Jabaliya, whose more than 50,000 residents have been kept indoors
now for eight consecutive days. Jabaliya is the camp where the
uprising started.
   The army announced today, meanwhile, that an Israeli naval
patrol stopped two Lebanese boats on their way to Cyprus on Tuesday
and detained some Palestinian guerrillas who were on board,
bringing them to Israel.
   The crew and other passengers were allowed to continue their
trip, an army spokesman said. He declined to elaborate.
</TEXT>
