<FIRST>r i BC-Poland-Chronology     04-05 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Chronology,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Events Leading Up to Round-Table Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key events in Poland's ``round-table''
talks:
   Aug. 26, 1988 _ Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, faced
with a second severe wave of strikes, proposes negotiations with
the opposition, which is led by the independent Solidarity union
movement that has refused to fade seven years after being banned
under martial law.
   Sept. 3, 1988 _ Strikes end after 19 days when Solidarity leader
Lech Walesa appeals for time to talk with the government.
   Oct. 24, 1988 _ A round, pine table is set up at a government
palace but the date for the start of the talks remains in doubt as
both sides argue.
   Nov. 25, 1988 _ With prospects for talks dim, the table is
dismantled.
   Nov. 30, 1988 _ Walesa and Alfred Miodowicz, head of the union
alliance created by the government to replace Solidarity after
martial law, hold a live television debate, and Walesa's convincing
performance rekindles plans for the talks.
   Jan. 17, 1989 _ The Communist Party leadership decides
Solidarity can be legalized under certain conditions, meeting
Solidarity's prerequisite for the talks.
   Jan. 22, 1989 _ Solidarity leadership agrees to negotiate with
the government.
   Feb. 6, 1989 _ The talks begin. The government and opposition
representatives form teams to handle political, union and economic
reforms and smaller committees are assigned specific issues.
   Feb. 9, 1989 _ As small strikes break out nationwide, Walesa
asks workers to stay on the job and give the talks a chance.
   Feb. 24, 1989 _ Negotiators agree on allowing legal independent
unions, including Solidarity, the farmers' Rural Solidarity and the
students' union known as NZS.
   March 9, 1989 _ Negotiators agree on election reforms that will
create a senate, the first freely elected legislative body in the
East bloc. They also agree to create the office of the presidency,
expected to be retained by the Communist Party and its allies,
which is guaranteed a majority in the existing sejm for the first
election.
   March 22, 1989 _ The Sejm begins considering the reforms even
before end of the talks.
   April 4, 1989 _ Kiszczak and Walesa end their final meeting but
snags remain and Walesa returns to Gdansk as aides struggle to
resolve the final issues, including indexing wages to price
increases.
   April 5, 1989 _ Walesa announces Solidarity has its key demand
_legalization _ and will sign the accord. Kiszczak and Walesa
conclude the new ``social contract'' for Poland's future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1308EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-USEmbassy     04-05 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US Embassy,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Aides Suggest Retaining Part of U.S. Embassy in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two aides Secretary of State James A.
Baker III sent to Moscow to inspect the U.S. Embassy in the Soviet
capital have recommended that part of the chancery be salvaged, a
Bush administration official said Wednesday.
   Their recommendation is to dismantle the top floors, which are
believed to be riddled with eavesdropping devices, and to replace
them with bug-free floors or an adjoining annex, said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The inspection was conducted two weeks ago by Nicholas M. Salgo,
a former U.S. ambassador to Hungary, and Ivan Selin, who is to be
undersecretary of state for management.
   They told Baker on their return that refurbishing the building
or even constructing an annex would be cheaper than razing the
chancery and starting over. The estimated cost of tearing down and
rebuilding is $500 million.
   The official said Baker would take into consideration the views
of key members of Congress. Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, chairman of a
House appropriations subcommittee, last month opposed spending the
$500 million. Others on Capitol Hill are inclined to agree with the
conclusion last year of a Washington area engineering firm that
starting over was the only way to make the chancery secure.
   A trade group headed by Dwayne O. Andreas, chairman of Archer
Daniels Midland Co., offered to buy the building for use as
business offices.
   Andreas is co-chairman of the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Trade and Economic
Council, which promotes trade between the two superpowers. He made
the offer on behalf of a consortium of U.S. companies, which would
use the building as a Moscow headquarters.
   The Soviets would have to approve any sale because the building
was intended for use as a new embassy, built under a 1972 agreement
between the two countries.
   A study done for the Reagan administration by former Defense
Secretary James R. Schlesinger recommended last year that the top
three floors be dismantled and rebuilt while an annex also was put
up next to the chancery.
   In 1987, Anne Armstrong, who was head of then-President Reagan's
Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board, called for the use of existing
technology and development of new methods to clear the chancery of
eavesdropping devices.
   Reagan last October concluded the building should be razed and
rebuilt, but that decision is under review by the Bush
administration and Baker has not decided whether to approve the
recommendations of Salgo and Selin, the U.S. official said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
