<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Arts     04-05 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Arts,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filmmaker Andrzej Wajda Approved as Theater Director</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reknowned filmmaker Andrzej Wajda, often
at odds with the government and at times forbidden to show his
works, has been approved as artistic director of a prestigious
official Warsaw theater.
   Wajda's nomination, put forth by the theater's actors, was
approved Tuesday by authorities as the economically pressed
government tries to build an atmosphere of reform.
   ``We now find ourselves in the most difficult situation since
1945,'' he said. ``Our audiences are so tired from everyday life
that they cannot think of art.''
   His films have chronicled resistance fighters during World War
II, the dehumanization of Stalinism and the birth of the
independent trade union Solidarity. Deeply rooted in Poland, Wajda
has continued to work here rather than leave, as have other
cultural figures seeking greater artistic freedom.
   Wajda said the government retains its influence in the arts by
its control over the economy.
   Wajda, who leads the culture commission of the Citizen's
Committee, an opposition shadow government formed by Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa, saw his award-winning film on the union, ``Man
of Iron,'' return to a Warsaw theater in February for the first
time since its premiere before the 1981 martial-law crackdown.
   Wajda's appointment at Teatr Powszechny _ he replaces the late
Zygmunt Hubner, who offered him the first opportunity to move from
film to theater in 1956 _ comes as other banned cultural and
political figures are allowed to surface in official settings.
   Wajda, who presided at a forum on independent culture last
weekend, emphasized that ``there is only good and bad art and it
can be independent or not. But we would not like to make
differences betweeen official culture and non-official culture.''
   Teatr Powszechny, established in 1944, was the first theater to
open in postwar Warsaw. Wajda directed the first play at the
theater in 1975 when it reopened after five years of renovations.
   The theater created a stir in February when it presented a play
by Vaclav Havel, the jailed Czechoslovak writer. Polish Prime
Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski attended the opening.
   ``It is our duty to support artists and their freedom as we are
part of this group of people who try to create art involved in
reality,'' Wajda said.
   Although best known for his movies, Wajda said ``film is an art
that exists today and can disappear tomorrow if there is a new
technique found ... Whereas theater will live eternally ... People
will always come to listen to others conversing in an intelligent
way.''
   Wajda said theater ``should be less dependent on the moment than
cinema. Theater is not here to give us immediate answers to
questions, it responds to more general problems.''
   The director said he is preparing a documentary on the massacre
of more than 4,000 Polish army officers _ including his father _ at
Katyn in the Soviet Union in 1940.
   Although official histories in Poland and the Soviet Union have
blamed the Nazis for the massacre, a Polish-Soviet review under way
could lead to the conclusion widely held in the West that Soviet
secret police actually committed the atrocity.
   The director said he started the documentary last year and may
visit Katyn with families of victims later this month.
   Wajda said he is concerned by the tendency to blame Katyn and
many other repressions on ``Stalinism.'' ``I do not see any
guarantee that this will not come back,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
