<FIRST>u a PM-Abortion-Vandalism 1stLd-Writethru a0548 04-05 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Vandalism, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0548,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plaintiff In Landmark Abortion Case Target of Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with police comments, that Ms. McCorvey never
reported any previous harassment. CORRECTS that Ms. McCorvey is not scheduled
to speak at NOW rally.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman known as ``Jane Roe'' in the landmark
Supreme Court ruling legalizing abortion has gone into hiding
indefinitely after three shotgun blasts were fired at her home and
car, her roommate said.
   ``She's real emotional right now,'' Connie Gonzales, Norma
McCorvey's roommate, said Tuesday. ``She cries and cries. We just
want to stop her crying.''
   FBI agents and the Dallas Police Department were conducting
separate investigations into the 4:45 a.m. shootings Tuesday at Ms.
McCorvey's home.
   ``We've got no leads, no suspects,'' said Sgt. Ron Ellison.
``There were three shots fired from a .410-gauge shotgun.''
   The gunfire damaged windows in Ms. McCorvey's car and two
windows in her home, he said.
   ``It knocked the glass out of the back of the vehicle and I
believe it shattered one of the windows in the living room and
another in the front door,'' Ellison said.
   Ms. McCorvey was the plaintiff in Roe vs. Wade, which resulted
in the 1973 U.S. Supreme Court decision, and has been organizing a
pro-choice Jane Roe Foundation.
   She told police she believes the shots were intended for her
because she plans to attend a weekend march and rally in Washington
sponsored by the National Organization for Women to support
legalized abortion.
   Ms. Gonzales told The Dallas Morning News that Ms. McCorvey was
not available for comment and that the two were going into hiding
indefinitely while their house remained under surveillance.
   ``There are some sick people out there,'' Ms. Gonzales told the
newspaper.
   Bill Price, president of the Greater Dallas Right to Life
Commission, said he will be ``totally surprised'' if investigators
find a link between the shooting incident and Ms. McCorvey's stance
on abortion.
   ``Certainly I hope it didn't have anything to do with that,''
Price said. ``I don't know what else she may be involved in. But
this would be the worst possible way in which to try and protest
and stop abortion.''
   In recent years, Ms. McCorvey's home and car have been egged,
she has found baby clothes scattered in her yard and she has
received hate mail. But Ms. Gonzales said Ms. McCorvey never before
felt personally threatened and Ellison said she did not tell police
about any previous incidents.
   ``It's frightening for Norma that after all these years she is
now willing to come out and be public about her role in the
pro-choice movement and she has to now deal with this,'' said Janie
Bush, president of the Texas Abortion Rights Action League.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
