<DOCNO> AP890405-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Malaysia-Refugees     04-05 0115</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Malaysia-Refugees,0118</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Refugees Land in Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boat carrying 152 Vietnamese
landed Wednesday northeast of the capital, the Bernama news agency
reported.
   The refugees were turned over to officials at Kuala Trengganu,
located 180 miles northeast of Kuala Lumpur, before they were sent
to camps, the agency said.
   Malaysia and other Southeast Asian countries recently began a
new policy of not automatically considering Vietnamese who arrive
on their shores eligible for resettlement in Western nations. Under
the new policy, Vietnamese must prove they faced political
persecution in their homeland.
   There are about 16,500 Vietnamese refugees in Malaysia awaiting
resettlement, compared to the peak of 76,500 in June 1979.
</TEXT>
