<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Dissident     04-05 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Dissident,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Says Talks To Reunify Two Koreas A Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By K.P. HONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean dissident clergyman said Wednesday
he believes his secret visit to North Korea for talks with
President Kim Il Sung on reunification was a success.
   The Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, an adviser to South Korea's main
dissident United National Democratic Movement, arrived in Tokyo on
Wednesday following an unauthorized, nine-day visit to North Korea
via Japan and China.
   He said he plans to go back to Seoul before April 14. South
Korea says the 71-year-old Princeton-educated Protestant minister
will be arrested for violating national security laws by serving
North Korean interests.
   ``I was not afraid of being arrested before. But I really hope
such an unfortunate development will not occur this time,'' Moon
said.
   He has been arrested and imprisoned several times since the
mid-1970s for anti-government activity.
   North Korea has warned that Moon's arrest would rupture an
ongoing dialogue between Seoul and the communist government in
Pyongyang.
   Moon said he had four meetings totaling nearly 10 hours with Kim
to exchange ``frank and a wide range of views.''
   ``I told him it would be a shame and tragedy if the division of
Korea is prolonged more than half a century, and he agreed that we
all should exert all-out efforts to reunify the country at least
before the 50th year of the territorial split,'' Moon said.
   Korea was divided at the end of World War II in 1945, and the
two nations fought a war 1950-53.
   The nations are involved in a variety of contacts ranging from a
possible non-aggression pact to trade, sports and cultural
exchanges. Some talks have stalled because North Korean protests
over recently concluded U.S.-South Korean military exercises.
   ``I would say it was a success in that I have just initiated a
move to discuss problems related to reunification on the peoples'
level,'' Moon said. However, he said he met only with communist
leaders and 18 of his relatives living in North Korea.
   He said he hoped Seoul would understand contacts between the
general public in the divided halves ``are as important as those
between government delegates.''
   Many South Koreans, who hold Kim responsible for the Korean War,
expressed anger at televised scenes of Moon hugging Kim.
   Moon was the first prominent South Korean dissident living in
South Korea to visit North Korea secretly and meet with Kim since
the war hardened enmity. A joint statement issued in Pyongyang
described Moon's visit as ``an inspiring dynamism for our nation''
that could help in ``clearing away the longstanding mistrust and
hostility between the North and the South.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
