<DOCNO> AP890405-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-PeaceCorps     04-05 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Peace Corps,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Peace Corps Volunteers Coming to China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peace Corps will dispatch its first
volunteers to China this summer, a group of 20 people to teach
English in southwestern China's Sichuan province.
   ``The Peace Corps is extremely excited about having people in
China,'' said Kathleen Corey, the American volunteer group's
training director for China. ``We're really happy to become a part
of opening the doors of China.''
   China will become the 65th nation and the first socialist
country with a Peace Corps program.
   Winston Lord, U.S. ambassador to China, and Ge Shouqin,
secretary general of the China Education Association for
International Exchanges, exchanged letters Wednesday on the Peace
Corps program.
   Ms. Corey said the first group will arrive in August following
an 11-week training program in Washington. They are to teach
English at three teacher training colleges, a medical college and
an animal husbandry college in the provincial capital of Chengdu,
Mianyang and two other Sichuan cities.
   She said the Chinese will decide after a year whether to
continue with the pilot program, but the volunteers are expected to
stay for the ordinary two-year term. ``Nobody thinks this isn't
going to work,'' she said.
   ``We definitely hope for expansion into other provinces and into
other technical fields,'' she said.
   Ms. Corey said many Americans, some who speak Chinese, have
applied for the China program, and they will be very selective in
choosing the first volunteers.
   She said one challenge will be for the volunteers to convince
their Chinese hosts that ``they don't want to be set apart as
guests. They don't want to be behind walls.''
   She said that during a recent three-week tour of Sichuan she
explained to the colleges receiving volunteers that one objective
of Peace Corps volunteers is to become part of the community they
are working in.
   Since opening to the outside world 10 years ago, China has
recruited what it calls ``foreign experts'' to help in its
modernization drive.
   Most of the estimated 20,000 foreigners in China, while
receiving salaries well below what they could earn in their own
countries, are provided with living quarters far better than those
of the average Chinese and tend to be isolated from their Chinese
colleagues.
   The Peace Corps, which has about 5,500 overseas volunteers, has
been sending American teachers, technicians, professionals and
community workers to foreign cities and villages since 1961.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
