<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--China-Defector     04-05 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Defector,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwanese Defector Joins China's Air Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air force pilot from Taiwan who defected to
mainland China has been made a ranking officer in the communist air
force, the government said Wednesday.
   Lt. Col. Lin Xianshun was given the same rank he held in
Taiwan's air force. He was also appointed deputy chief of staff at
a Chinese military institute, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   Lin, 35, flew his F-5E fighter across the 110-mile wide Taiwan
Strait to southeastern China's Guangdong province on Feb. 11, the
news agency said.
   Lin said he defected because he wanted to visit his ancestral
home in Guangdong. Although Taiwan's government in 1987 lifted a
ban on visits to the mainland, military personnel and government
workers are not allowed to go.
   Chinese Nationalists set up a rival government on the island
province of Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war on the mainland
to the communists. They still claim to be the rightful rulers of
all China. More than a dozen Nationalist air force officers have
defected to the mainland since 1949.
</TEXT>
