<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1338EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FoodProjects     04-05 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Food Projects,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 States Share in Test Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department said Wednesday that
10 states will share in a $2 million program that will let
low-income families spend government coupons at farmers' markets, a
test project ordered by Congress.
   Participants must already be in the government's WIC program,
which provides special supplemental food for women, infants and
children.
   Assistant Secretary John W. Bode, who oversees department food
and consumer services, said the project ``will test a concept
intended to improve the diets of women and children while also
helping farmers'' boost sales of fresh produce.
   Participating states and the federal grants for 1989 are
Connecticut, $164,800; Iowa, $264,600; Maryland, $52,200;
Massachusetts, $235,000; Michigan, $115,800; New York, $509,600;
Pennsylvania, $167,400; Texas, $416,800; Vermont, $40,800; and
Washington, $51,000.
   The project, which will operate during the growing and
harvesting season, was included in the Hunger Prevention Act of
1988 and was authorized for three years. The $2 million currently
available for 1989 will provide approximately 88,000 participants
with a federal benefit of about $20 for the year.
   Bode said states may use their own matching funds to serve
additional people or increase the value of benefits. Additional
federal funding will depend on future appropriations.
   The law also directed USDA to report to Congress about the
project and how it worked.
   Nationally, the WIC program serves 3.6 million people a month
and costs $1.8 billion a year. Participants are given food vouchers
worth approximately $32 a month, which can be redeemed for specific
foods such as milk, eggs, cereals high in iron, and vitamin-rich
juices.
</TEXT>
