<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     04-05 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sweden to Prosecute Suspect in Palme Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Wednesday they have
assembled enough evidence to try a suspect arrested in December in
the fatal shooting of Prime Minister Olof Palme in 1986.
   Discarding the conspiracy theories police pursued for years, the
prosecutors will press charges against Christer Pettersson.
   Pettersson, 42, has a previous manslaughter conviction, a long
record of petty crime, a history of mental disturbance and of drug
and alcohol abuse. He has denied he shot Palme.
   Assistant state prosecutor Axel Morath said he expected to file
charges within a month. He did not say exactly what the charge
would be.
   ``The evidence against the suspect has been strengthened during
the time he has been detained,'' Morath said. ``The evidence is
judged to be so strong that the prosecutors have decided charges
should be filed and the case should be tested in court.''
   Under Swedish jurisprudence, prosecutors should be virtually
certain of a conviction before trying a case.
   Palme was shot Feb. 28, 1986, while walking home from a movie
with his wife. He was a controversial figure at home and abroad, a
committed socialist and a champion of Third World liberation
movements.
   The killing stunned Sweden, where no political leader had been
slain for 200 years.
   Morath said he would ask the Stockholm district court to order
Pettersson's detention for another 14 days to complete the
investigation and then will turn the file over to the defense to
prepare its case.
   It was not clear when the trial would begin.
   Investigators reportedly believe Pettersson acted alone, but
they have not disclosed any motive.
   Authorities found no murder weapon, but Morath said the case
strengthened after several accounts from witnesses of the slaying.
   ``As far as we can tell, he (Pettersson) has no alibi,'' Morath
said.
   Pettersson had been questioned within weeks of the shooting but
was investigated again after police received a tip that he had lied
about his whereabouts on the night of the shooting.
   Pettersson's arrest on Dec. 14 came as a surprise after a
three-year manhunt that focused on theories of international
conspiracies.
   Pettersson was most recently arrested in August and fined by a
court for assault and the theft of $7 in beef. He was convicted of
1970 of stabbing a stranger after a street brawl just a few yards
from where Palme was shot 16 years later. He was released from
detention after seven months under psychiatric care.
   The strain of failure in solving the murder exposed Swedish
authorities to brutal criticism from the public and parliament.
   Justice Minister Anna Greta-Leijon was forced to resign in June
after disclosures that she supported a private probe of the killing.
   The secret investigation came to light when the group, led by
book publisher Ebbe Carlsson, tried to smuggle illegal wiretapping
equipment across the border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
