<FIRST>u w PM-US-Poland     04-05 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Poland,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Lauds Polish Accord; Raps Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House today hailed the accord
reached between the communist government of Poland and the
Solidarity movement, calling it ``a great day for the Polish people
and for freedom.''
   Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater told a news briefing that
President Bush, who visited Poland in September 1987 as vice
president, was ``very pleased by the accords that have started
Poland on this new path toward reconcilation.''
   Fitzwater said that Americans several years ago ``lit candles''
in hopes that ``darkness and oppression'' in the Warsaw Pact nation
would someday be lifted.
   ``This is a great day for the Polish people and for freedom,''
the spokesman said. ``The discussions have been long and arduous.
We welcome the round table accords and see them as a historic step
... which will take Poland far from totalitarianism.''
   Fitzwater said the Bush administration was following
developments in Poland closely, in consultation with U.S. allies
and with members of Congress.
   Fitzwater also said the United States was disappointed that
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev did not go further in a
speech he gave to the Cuban National Assembly Tuesday, in which the
Kremlin leader spoke out against the export of revolution.
   ``We listened carefully to what President Gorbachev had to
say,'' the spokesman said. ``While his words about not exporting
revolution are welcome, they are not matched by deeds which would
give his words credence.''
   ``Today we call on the Soviets to call off their
half-billion-dollar aid to Nicaragua,'' Fitzwater said.
   Responding to longstanding U.S. concerns about Moscow's
intentions in Latin America, Gorbachev said the Kremlin would
refrain from putting military bases or nuclear weapons in the
region.
   With President Fidel Castro sitting nearby, the Soviet leader
said Moscow supports the creation of a ``zone of peace'' in Latin
America and an end to all outside military aid to the region.
   Fitzwater said the U.S. bipartisan plan for humanitarian aid to
the Nicaraguan Contras ``has the support of the Central American
democracies. It is time for the Soviet Union to support us in this
plan.''
   He said the Soviets ``should demonstrate through their behavior
that they are adhering to this principle, and they should pressure
their client states and the revolutionary groups they support to do
the same.''
   ``We trust that the Soviets will follow these words with
concrete action,'' the press secretary said. But he also said that
Gorbachev ``could have proposed a cutoff of military supplies to
all irregular forces in the region. This would have suggested a new
thinking in Central America.''
</TEXT>
