<HEAD>State Department Praises Vietnam's Announced Pullout</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vietnam-Cambodia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Wednesday praised
Vietnam's announcement that it would pull out of Cambodia by Sept.
30, saying such a step would restore peace there.
   ``Although we have not yet seen complete details of the
Vietnamese statement, we do believe that if the withdrawal is
carried out, it would be a positive development,'' said Richard
Boucher, a department spokesman.
   ``The United States has long called for an expeditious
withdrawal of all Vietnamese troops as a key component of the
Cambodian settlement,'' he said.
   ``Clearly, a total and verifiable withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops from Cambodia would contribute to the process of returning
peace and stability to that war-torn nation,'' he said.
   Vietnam previously had said it would withdraw its troops,
estimated at 70,000, by 1990 and would be out by September only if
a political settlement has been reached.
   Wednesday's announcement gave no indication that any conditions
were attached to the September pullout.
