<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1415EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ParamedicHero     04-05 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paramedic Hero,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramedic Called Hero for Rescuing Abducted Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty paramedic who noticed a
bloodied woman in the seat of a car that sped past him rescued her
and helped capture her abductor, police said.
   ``I made direct eye contact with her and she mouthed `Help
me,''' Robert Hodorowicz said Tuesday. ``There was blood
everywhere. I knew she was in great danger.''
   Hodorowicz, 25, heard the car honking behind him as he sat in
his truck at a stop light on Saturday. He was shocked as the car
passed by to see a woman covered in blood kicking and screaming,
and set off in pursuit, he said.
   Jeffrey Harvey, 32, was charged with aggravated kidnapping,
armed robbery and aggravated battery. He was being held in lieu of
$350,000 bond.
   Ann Mate, 45, was released from a hospital Monday after
receiving 100 stitches to sew up gashes on her head. A hospital
spokeswoman said Mate also had numerous bruises on her head, arms,
legs and back.
   She was abducted as she was getting into her car in a shopping
center parking lot, said William Kujawa, deputy police chief in
Burbank, a southern suburb of Chicago. The assailant beat her with
a blackjack as he drove off in the hijacked vehicle, Kujawa said.
   Hodorowicz followed Mate's car for about a mile, at times
reaching speeds of 70 mph, until it smashed into a bridge on
Chicago's South Side and bounced into two other vehicles.
   Hodorowicz screamed at two men standing nearby to ``get that
guy,'' he said. Others at the scene held Harvey until police
arrived, while Hodorowicz bandaged Mate's wounds and reassured her.
   Harvey was released in February from the Joliet Correctional
Center, where he served four years on a drug charge, Kujawa said.
He earlier spent 10 years in a Tennessee prison for robbery.
   Kujawa credited Hodorowicz and other bystanders with saving the
victim's life.
   ``In my experience as a police officer, it's very difficult to
get citizens involved,'' he said. ``And they did it on their own.
All the credit goes to them.''
</TEXT>
