<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Mosque     04-05 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Mosque,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Inaugurates Jordan's Largest Mosque</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein on Wednesday inaugurated the
Martyr King Abdullah Mosque, the kingdom's largest Islamic
religious structure.
   ``What a happy day and what a glorious event for me to have the
honor to inaugurate one of God's houses just before the emergence
of the holy month of Ramadan,'' Hussein told a crowd of Moslem
worshipers.
   The $12 million mosque is named after the monarch's grandfather,
Jordan's first king.
   Hussein's Hashemite family is descended from Islam's Prophet
Mohammed. King Abdullah, who ruled Jordan from its creation in 1921
until his assassination in Jerusalem in 1950.
   The royal court chief, Field Marshal Zeid Bin Shaker, Prime
Minister Zaid Rifai and other senior aides and religious figures
joined the monarch at the ceremony, which included readings and
teachings of the Koran, the Islamic holy book.
   The blue Ottoman-style mosque can hold 3,500 worshipers in its
20,000 square yards of floor space.
   The building also holds a Koranic teaching school, conference
rooms, a library and housing for religious figures.
</TEXT>
