<DOCNO> AP890405-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1534EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Lawsuits     04-05 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Lawsuits,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 14 Lawsuits Filed, Lengthy Litigation Predicted</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 14 lawsuits have been filed in
connection with the Alaskan oil spill, including a
multimillion-dollar one claiming the spill led to higher gas prices
for California drivers.
   The plaintiffs who have sued in federal and state courts are for
the most part area fishermen, fish processors and businessmen such
as tour boat operators seeking unspecified damages and
environmental restoration from Exxon USA and other defendants.
   A lawsuit filed by attorney Melvin Belli, however, goes beyond
actual damages and asks the court to assess at least $1 billion to
punish or make an example of the defendants. The San Francisco
attorney said he also has turned to the courts to tap a $100
million cleanup fund established as part of the federal
authorization for the trans-Alaska oil pipeline.
   Belli, known for his litigation of disasters, said Tuesday about
100 plaintiffs had joined in a class-action lawsuit and he expected
many more. ``We've been deluged,'' he said.
   Other lawsuits include a class-action complaint filed in federal
court in California, charging that the spill led to higher prices
at the gas pump for drivers in that state.
   Exxon Corp. has promised to accept liability for the disaster
and pay for the cleanup, lost income and all valid claims.
   The oil that spilled into Prince William Sound from the Exxon
Valdez on March 24 had flowed through the 800-mile pipeline from
Prudhoe Bay to Valdez. About 240,000 barrels of crude oil spilled
into the resource-rich sound, killing wildlife and bringing the
cancellation of at least three fish harvests.
   Claims in the lawsuits include negligence, stemming partly from
Capt. Joseph Hazelwood's absence from the vessel's bridge at the
time of the crash. Tests conducted about nine hours after the
accident showed Hazelwood was intoxicated.
   Alyeska Pipeline Service Co.'s response immediately after the
spill also is presented as a basis for damages. The company is a
consortium of oil companies.
   ``It's going to be fairly complex litigation,'' said John
McCarron, an Anchorage lawyer whose office has filed four lawsuits,
including one on behalf of Cordova District Fishermen United and
Prince William Sound Aquaculture Corp.
   ``It could last for quite awhile.''
   Exxon officials have said they do not know how many lawsuits
have been filed around the country, and they will not comment on
litigation.
</TEXT>
