<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     04-05 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Crew Trains For Planetary Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five astronauts who will fly the
first space shuttle planetary mission assembled Wednesday for three
days of training, including a practice countdown.
   Commander Dave Walker, pilot Ron Grabe and Norm Thagard flew in
from the Johnson Space Center in Houston, landing in a rainstorm,
to join Mary Cleave and Mark Lee, who arrived earlier in the week
to take part in a test that verified electrical and other
connections between the shuttle Atlantis and the Magellan-Venus
spacecraft in its cargo bay.
   NASA lists April 28 as the target for launching Atlantis, but
preparations have been running behind schedule because of minor
technical problems at the launch pad, and officials expect liftoff
will slip as much as four days.
   Shuttle managers are to meet here April 14 to set a launch date.
   Once in Earth orbit, the astronauts will dispatch the $378
million Magellan payload on the start of a 466-day outward journey
to Venus. The craft is to orbit the cloud-shrouded planet and map
its surface with high-resolution radar.
   On Thursday, the astronauts will rehearse launch pad emergency
procedures and on Friday they will board Atlantis for the final two
hours of a countdown rehearsal.
</TEXT>
