<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-Cuba Bjt   04-05 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba &amp; Soviet Union: International Odd Couple Endures</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XHAV5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet-Cuban alliance seems reasonably intact
after the visit of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, but the two
countries _ so different in so many ways _ still give the
impression of an international odd couple.
   For nations that were barely aware of each other's existence 30
years ago, the Soviet Union and Cuba have come a long way. No
overseas ally of the Soviets has been more durable than Cuba.
   They are improbable partners _ temperamentally and
geographically distant, sometimes seemingly from different planets
_ but a common ideology and shared hostility for the United States
cemented the relationship in ways few would have thought possible.
   To this day, Cuba soaks up more than half the Soviet foreign aid
program while lending itself to Soviet strategic purposes. As an
example, Cuba has routinely dispatched soldiers to bolster remote
but ideologically congenial regimes troubled by unrest.
   For almost two decades, even the most persistent analysts were
unable to detect more than minor chinks in the Moscow-Havana axis.
   With the ascendancy of Gorbachev, however, sharp differences
began to emerge and it was against this background that his
Ilyushin-62 jetliner touched down here Sunday night.
   In a variety of ways, Castro had indicated deep reservations
about Gorbachev's policies: his accommodating attitude toward the
United States, his less-than-resolute backing for pro-Soviet
regimes in such places as Afghanistan and Cambodia, his willingness
to borrow some capitalistic practices, his eagerness to allow
public debate on key issues.
   Castro made no secret of his disdain for some of those reforms,
but during Gorbachev's visit the Cuban leader sought to be the
perfect host, effusively praising the visitor while dismissing
Western accounts of a rift.
   Soviet-Cuban friendship and cooperation, Castro said in a speech
Tuesday, ``has, does and will exist and and will increase.''
   Gorbachev was less forthcoming on this point but told a news
conference Tuesday there was no truth to Western reports that, he
said, treated the two ``almost as enemies.''
   There was some hint of Gorbachev's widely advertised
dissatisfaction with the way Cuba has used Soviet aid.
   He told the Cuban National Assembly the ``immediate task'' is
``stricter accountability and more discipline'' on joint projects.
   That was an elegant way of saying, ``Look, Fidel, we've poured
hundreds of millions of pesos into extravagant projects begun over
a decade ago and the return on the investment thus far has been
non-existent.''
   Castro is not one to play the role of sycophant, even to a
patron as generous as Gorbachev. In contrast to the measured way
the Kremlin leader discussed Soviet relations with the United
States, Castro made a bitter attack on U.S. policies while
Gorbachev sat impassively nearby.
   In corrosive terms, he criticized U.S. support for
anti-communist insurgencies and the American refusal to give Third
World countries more of a break on their huge foreign debt.
   Polemical diatribes are part of Castro's repertoire, but not
Gorbachev's. While Castro sees himself as the guardian of socialist
purity, Gorbachev has emerged as a no-apologies defender of
pragamtism.
   It appears Castro has decided he can coexist with what Gorbachev
describes as the ``new thinking'' in Moscow, distasteful as the
Cuban may find it.
   He has backed away from criticizing Gorbachev's policies in
recent months, perhaps sensing that what unites the two countries
is far more powerful than what divides them.
   Cuba gets roughly $5 billion in aid from the Soviets annually
and the Kremlin remains Castro's best insurance against a U.S.
attempt to eradicate communism in Cuba. Moscow almost certainly
would extract a heavy price from the United States in such a case.
   Gorbachev benefits from his alliance with Castro, who is, after
all, a hero to the world's dispossessed and has given Moscow
irreplaceable facilities for electronic spy activities against U.S.
military and space installations along the East Coast.
   The two countries may not seem meant for each other, but to
Castro the relationship is more than an ephemeral infatuation.
   ``Our gratitude toward the Soviet leadership, led brilliantly by
comrade Gorbachev, will be eternal,'' he said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has made 16 reporting trips to Cuba
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1508EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-DemocratsCheer Bjt   04-05 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats Cheer, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Cheer Win in Alabama, Victory Over Jackson's Candidate
in Chicago</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats were celebrating two more election
victories Wednesday, but some of their heartiest cheers were
prompted by the party's clean triumph in its latest confrontation
with Jesse Jackson.
   Democrat Glen Browder was a landslide winner in the race for an
open House seat in Alabama Tuesday, his triumph coming exactly a
week after Jill Long upset Republican hopes of holding Dan Quayle's
old House seat in Indiana.
   Browder easily beat Republican John Rice who had labeled the
Democrat a liberal, a liar and a wimp. Browder will succeed the
late Democratic Rep. Bill Nichols.
   But the race that held the attention of Democrats was for mayor
of Chicago, where Richard M. Daley scored a solid victory over a
black independent backed by Jackson.
   That was a contest where all the winners and losers weren't on
the ballot.
   A clear winner was Ronald H. Brown, the new national Democratic
Party chairman.
   Also picking up some points for likely use in 1992 was Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee who risked involvement in the snake
pit of Chicago politics by campaigning for Daley.
   Jackson backed independent candidate Timothy Evans and shared
his loss.
   ``People are quick to say Jackson failed here in Chicago,'' the
two-time presidential candidate said. ``But it's not the winning or
losing.''
   But in politics it often is the winning or losing, or at least
how people deal with triumph or defeat.
   Jackson quickly shifted to talk of building bridges. But he left
the burden on Daley.
   For Democrats who've long been irritated by Jackson's free-lance
manner of operating, the Chicago race offered hope that his
influence was diminishing.
   James Ruvolo, Ohio Democratic Party chairman and head of the
Association of Democratic State Chairs, speculated that Jackson
could lose support within the party because of his support of Evans.
   That might prove wishful thinking. But other Democrats also were
assessing the impact of the mayoral race held on Jackson's home
turf.
   ``Jesse's traveling extensively without portfolio politically,''
said one Democrat who insisted on anonymity.
   Yolanda Caraway, who was a top aide to Jackson in his campaign
for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination, said he ``has
heard from quite a few people'' who are urging him to run for mayor
of Washington, D.C., a city troubled by a wave of drug-related
murders.
   ``I'm very much for it,'' said Ms. Caraway.
   The only office Jackson has ever sought is president and some of
his supporters believe he could strengthen his standing by winning
another office.
   Brown clearly gained strength from the Chicago contest and
accomplished it without appearing too eager to provoke a
confrontation with Jackson.
   A black lawyer, Brown was convention manager for Jackson when
the Democrats met last summer in Atlanta. His tie to Jackson was an
argument used against him when he sought the party chairmanship.
   When Daley defeated incumbent Mayor Eugene Sawyer for the
Democratic nomination, Brown quickly endorsed the nominee, a step
that brought an angry outcry from some blacks, including Rep. Gus
Savage who was backing Evans.
   Despite denunciations from Savage, Brown twice appeared in
Chicago to support Daley.
   Jackson made it easier for the chairman by not making an issue
of Brown's support for Daley.
   Both the party chairman and the mayor-elect were quick to issue
unity appeals.
   ``I pledge my help in bringing Democrats together,'' said Brown.
   Daley, whose father was Chicago's mayor for 21 years, succeeds a
black incumbent and he pledged to ``bring top professional people _
black and white and Hispanic and Asian'' into City Hall.
   The victories of Long and Browder in the two House races this
spring puts greater pressure on the Republicans to hold the seat
vacated by Dick Cheney of Wyoming when he became secretary of
defense.
   Cheney won the House seat in 1978 and it was considered solidly
Republican. But the GOP has no assurance of holding it in the
special election scheduled for April 26.
   Democrat John Vinich nearly upset Republican Sen. Malcolm Wallop
last November and is considered far better known than his GOP
opponent Craig Thomas.
   Asked about the Republican prospects in Wyoming, John Buckley,
spokesman for the House GOP campaign committee, said, ``They're
tough, they're tough.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
