<HEAD>Columbia Announces Bancroft Winners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professors Eric Foner and Edmund S. Morgan were
named Wednesday as winners of the 1989 Bancroft Prizes in American
history from Columbia University, the school announced.
   Foner, 46, DeWitt Clinton professor of history at Columbia, was
cited for ``Reconstruction: America's Unfinished Revolution
1863-1877,'' a work on the aftermath of the Civil War.
   Morgan, 73, Sterling professor of American history emeritus at
Yale University, won for ``Inventing the People: The Rise of
Popular Sovereignty in England and America,'' on English and early
American political culture.
   The Bancroft Prizes were established in 1948. Each winning
author receives $4,000.
