<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Arrests     04-05 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Arrests,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Activist Says at Least 21 Reform Supporters Detained</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev-Cuba, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 21 Cubans who support the reforms of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev have been arrested, a leading
dissident said Wednesday, the day the Soviet leader left Cuba.
   Most of those arrested had planned to take part in a
pro-Gorbachev demonstration at the Soviet Embassy on Tuesday night,
said Elizardo Sanchez, a local human rights activist.
   Government spokesman have confirmed that some arrests were
carried out starting Tuesday morning but have not given precise
figures.
   Among those arrested was Samuel Martinez Lara, leader of the
Pro-Human Rights Party. He was the principal organizer of the
demonstration, which was canceled.
   There was a heavy police presence Tuesday night outside the
embassy, where Gorbachev attended a reception.
   Several people who were monitoring developments in the area were
taken into custody, Sanchez and other witnesses said.
   The demonstration was to have been aimed at seeking Gorbachev's
support for a liberalizing reform program in Cuba similar to the
one Gorbachev has carried out in the Soviet Union.
   Sanchez, who heads the Cuban Commission for Human Rights and
National Reconciliation, said scores of others may also have been
arrested but he could confirm only 21.
   Sanchez, interviewed on ``CBS This Morning,'' said he was
doubtful Gorbachev's reforms had rubbed off on Cuban leader Fidel
Castro.
   ``I did not have a great deal of hope,'' he said. ``We never
expected miracles to result from this visit. We trust more in what
we Cubans can do for ourselves.''
</TEXT>
