<FIRST>r a AM-SkunkLoversAnonymous     04-05 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Skunk Lovers Anonymous,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Revels in Eau de Skunk Sniffs Out Kindred Souls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Pounds abbreviated as `pds' and `skunks' with no apostrophe
in 20th graf and whiff spelled as wiff in 22nd graf are in the original
letters.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn knew she was different: Most people hold
their noses and roll up their windows when they drive past a dead
skunk in the middle of the road.
   But she's always found something wonderful about that pungent,
musky, unmistakable scent. And now she knows she's not alone.
   Marilyn, who does not want her last name known because some
folks might not understand, turned up scores of people who do
understand with her classified ad in a national newspaper.
   ``If you like the smell, you really like the smell. It isn't
something you can take or leave,'' Marilyn says of the skunk's
scent, a spray designed by nature as the animal's first line of
defense.
   For most of her 50 years, the suburban woman has reveled in the
odor.
   ``Everybody else rolls up their windows,'' says one of her two
daughters. ``She rolls them down.''
   Marilyn began to wonder if there were others who shared her
passion, so she ran this ad in USA Today in January:
   ``Calling All Skunk Lovers.
   ``My family and friends think I am the only person in the world
that likes the skunk scent. I would like to prove them wrong, so if
you or anyone you know likes the scent, please reply.''
   Within five weeks, she got 71 replies.
   ``Sensuous,'' wrote one fellow skunk lover.
   ``Intriguingly delicate,'' wrote another.
   ``Has always reminded me of burnt toast,'' offered a third.
   Some said they had never shared their secret before. Others
wrote of being teased by relatives. A few confessed weaknesses for
other strong scents.
   ``I can think of no combination of things using the five senses
that can rival ... the feel of a warm summer breeze, the taste of a
cool drink, the sights of a beautiful garden, the sound of rushing
water, and the faint smell of skunk,'' said one letter from West
Virginia.
   Others suggested that Marilyn start a club, and a Missouri
sporting goods store owner offered T-shirts and other paraphernalia
to get it off to a good start.
   Marilyn and her husband travel about 30,000 miles a year in
their antique business, and she said she was hitting the road
Wednesday.
   Ah, springtime, with its warming breezes, budding trees and _
with a little luck _ maybe even the tang of skunk spray.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Kindred spirits can write Skunk Lovers, 931 S. Roselle Rd.,
Suite 128, Schaumburg, Ill. 60193.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
