<FIRST>r w AM-SovietJets-Libya     04-05 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Jets-Libya,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Registers Concern Over Libya Amassing Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has sold Libya from 12 to 15
high-performance fighter-bombers capable of striking long-range
targets in the Middle East and posing a potential threat to Egypt
and possibly Israel, Bush administration officials said Wednesday.
   Without confirming the transaction, the State Department sharply
criticized Libya and, indirectly, the Soviet Union.
   ``The sale of any kind of sophisticated weaponry to Libya would
be a dangerous thing, given (Libyan leader Moammar) Gadhafi's past
behavor,'' spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   And, he said, if the Soviets made such a deal, ``we would be
concerned.''
   Because the transaction was uncovered through U.S. intelligence,
administration officials publicly would neither deny nor confirm
reports of it. But privately, officials speaking on the condition
of anonymity said the Soviets had begun delivery of the supersonic
SU-24 Fencers.
   One official found even more disturbing Soviet assistance to
Libya in lengthening the range of Soviet-build refueling planes. He
said that could pose a danger to Egypt, long at odds with Libya,
and possibly with Israel, whose existence is hotly challenged by
Gadhafi.
   ``We have long been concerned with Gadhafi's erratic and
dangerous behavior,'' Boucher said. ``Libya continues to act in an
unacceptable fashion, particularly in its support for terrorism and
international subversion.''
   He said the United States had talked to the Soviets about arms
sales in the region. With Soviet bombers ``Libya could threaten all
of its neighbors,'' Boucher said.
   The SU-24 Fencers, which can fly within an 800-mile radius
without refueling, were broken into pieces, crated in large boxes
and delivered to the Libyans aboard Soviet transport planes,
Pentagon sources said.
   The Fencers, whose cost was not known, are likely to be based in
eastern Libya. Egypt is directly east of the North African country.
</TEXT>
