<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland     04-05 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Hails Polish Accord; Suggests Economic Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Wednesday welcomed
the Polish accord recognizing the Solidarity trade union movement,
suggesting ``the historic step'' will warm relations between
Washington and Warsaw.
   ``This is a great day for the Polish people and for freedom,''
White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said.
   He said the United States was weighing a variety of economic
moves aimed at encouraging the movement toward freedom in Eastern
Europe.
   Fitzwater spoke soon after the communist government in Warsaw
signed a pact recognizing Lech Walesa's trade union movement and
clearing the way for the first free elections in post-war Poland.
   Fitzwater said the United States hopes the agreement ``will
eventually take Poland far from totalitarianism and towards a
better political and economic future.''
   Fitzwater said Bush administration officials are ``following the
developments in Poland closely and are consulting with Congress and
our friends and allies on this issue.''
   He noted that as vice president, Bush had traveled to Poland in
September 1987, visiting with both Walesa and Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, the Communist party chief, and that Bush at the time
``urged dialogue and reconciliation to bring about economic growth
and political freedom.''
   ``The president today is very pleased by the accords that have
started Poland on this new path of reconciliation,'' Fitzwater said.
   A thaw in U.S.-Polish relations since early 1987 has led to the
lifting of some sanctions Washington imposed on the Warsaw
government after its military quashed the Solidarity free trade
union movement in December 1981.
   Asked whether the United States was willing to expand trade and
commerce with Poland in view of the latest accord, Fitzwater said,
``We feel very confident about the process that is under way in
Poland.''
   He said that Bush has talked of ``the American interest in
promoting economic change and reform in that country and in
fostering reconciliation. Now that we have these accords, we are
considering issues or moves that might be taken which would, in
various ways, foster economic development and help move that
process forward.''
   Asked what steps were under consideration, Fitzwater said, ``I
don't have a timetable . ... But we are looking at various actions
that could be taken and hopefully within the not-too-distant
future, we'll have something to announce.''
</TEXT>
