<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--London-Subway     04-05 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--London-Subway,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Subway Workers Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 60 percent of the train drivers on
London's subway system staged a wildcat strike Wednesday, shutting
down service to wide areas of the capital.
   The results included one-hour delays on some city buses and
heavy traffic jams on the approaches to Heathrow airport.
   The Circle, Metropolitan, District, East London and Jubilee
lines were closed, and the Piccadilly line, which serves Heathrow,
closed after a few hours of service. Normal service was maintained
only on the Northern, Victoria and Central lines.
   London Underground reported that more than 1,500 of the system's
2,400 drivers took part in the action.
   Wednesday's action was taken by drivers seeking a pay raise of
$108 per week for operating trains without a second crew member,
known as a guard, who operates the doors.
   ``Now that most of our trains are one-person operated we need
quickly to talk through the impact on working arrangements and to
establish a new pay and conditions package,'' said Denis
Tunnicliffe, managing director of the Underground.
</TEXT>
