<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Poland     04-05 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Poland,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Measures Aim to Cut Illegal Polish Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Wednesday announced
new measures to cut the number of Poles who enter West Germany on
tourist visas illegally to work or sell goods.
   They are also expected to reduce the number of Poles applying
for political asylum each year, said government spokesman Friedhelm
Ost.
   Under the measures, Polish citizens who apply for tourist visas
will be required to carry the equivalent of $27 for each day of
their visit. Those without the required money will be turned back
at the border, Ost said.
   He said West German authorities would be more stringent in
granting visa requests and would deny visas to Poles previously
involved in illegal activities in West Germany.
   He said the new measures were aimed at discouraging Poles from
visiting West Germany soley to earn hard currency.
   West Germany is the favored destination of thousands of Poles
who sell goods that they buy cheaply in Poland or offer their labor
at rates that undercut those of Germans.
   Some Poles say they earn in just three months in West Germany
what they would earn in a year in Poland.
   But the new restrictions were not meant to discourage Poles from
visiting or moving to West Germany, Ost said.
   Juergen Chrobog, spokesman for the West German Foreign Ministry,
said he did not know how many Poles worked illegally in West
Germany but estimated the number as ``tens of thousands.''
   According to government figures, in 1988, 29,000 Poles who
entered West Germany with a tourist visa later applied for
political asylum. Only 2.6 percent of those applications were
approved.
</TEXT>
