<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2043EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildAbuse     04-05 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Abuse,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Kicks Off Anti-Chilc Abuse Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush, kicking off a
national campaign to end child abuse, said Wednesday that even
small things can make a difference in preventing abuse.
   ``Sometimes it's as simple as being a good neighbor, listening
to a young mother talk over a cup of coffee or, even better,
offering to take the children for an hour or two,'' she said.
   Addressing a news conference kicking off the sixth annual
National Child Abuse Prevention Month, the first lady said that
``it's not enough to just feel, and when we hear of a child who's
been seriously injured or even killed, to be sad. That's not
enough. Then it's too late.
   ``The time to get involved is before the blow lands.''
   She urged that, ``if we know of a problem, we should reach out
to the parent and suggest they get help; and, if we know of a child
who is at serious risk, we must not be afraid to get involved, even
if that means picking up the phone and calling the authorities.''
   Mrs. Bush led off a list of celebrity speakers, including Cheryl
Ladd, Efrem Zimbalist Jr., Edward Woodward, Carol Lawrence, Norm
Crosby and Jack Scalia, who said he spoke as an ``adult survivor''
of abuse.
   Scalia said he suffered emotional and verbal abuse, but he said
it was just as devastating and carried some of the same
consequences as physical abuse, including drug and alcohol
addiction.
   Scalia, a former Montreal Expos baseball pitcher and
international model turned actor who is now a regular on
``Dallas,'' said he kicked both alcohol and drugs, but said the
scars of his abuse remain.
   ``My biggest phobia in life is what am I going to do if somebody
ever loves me ... and what am I going to do when I have to love
somebody else. How do I do that,'' Scalia, his eyes glistening with
tears, said to the hushed audience.
   Verbal assaults on children are the focus of a major new media
campaign being coordinated by the Advertising Council, a nonprofit
organization established by the advertising industry to create
public service ads addressing key issues.
   The theme of the campaign is ``words can hit a child as hard as
a fist,'' said Molly Hudson, senior vice president of Lintas: USA,
which is developing the print and video campaign.
   A nationwide survey by the National Committee for the Prevention
of Child Abuse estimated that more than 2.2 million child abuse
reports were filed in 1988, an increase of 3 percent over the
number reported in 1987. Also last year, more than 1,200 children
died as the result of maltreatment, about 5 percent more than the
previous year.
   Childhelp, a national nonprofit organization involved in the
treatment, prevention and research of child abuse, said its
nationwide hotline _ 1-800-4-A-CHILD _ received 175,000 calls last
year, up 18 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
