<FIRST>r i BC-Cambodia-Chronology     04-05 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cambodia-Chronology,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Chronology of Major Cambodian Events Since 1970</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vietnam-Cambodia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key events in Cambodia beginning with
the coup in 1970:
   March 18, 1970 _ A coup by Gen. Lon Nol ousts Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, who had ruled since 1941, and Cambodia becomes a major
front of the Vietnam war.
   April 17, 1975 _ The communist Khmer Rouge, led by Pol Pot, gain
power and try to create a primitive agrarian society, killing
hundreds of thousands of people in slave labor camps and execution
chambers.
   Dec. 25, 1978 _ Vietnam invades Cambodia to stop Khmer Rouge
border attacks that began in 1977. Khmer Rouge forces are driven to
the Thai border area.
   Jan. 10, 1979 _ Vietnam installs the government of President
Heng Samrin in Phnom Penh.
   Feb. 1979 _ China conducts a border war against Vietnam to
punish it for the invasion.
   June 22, 1982 _ The Khmer Rouge and guerrilla groups led by
Sihanouk and former Premier Son Sann form a resistance coalition.
   Aug. 16, 1985 _ Vietnam announces it will withdraw all its
troops by 1990 with or without a political settlement.
   July 29, 1987 _ Indonesia, representing the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, and Vietnam sign an agreement calling for
talks among all the warring parties.
   July 29, 1987 _ Sihanouk holds unprecedented peace talks in
France with Premier Hun Sen of the Vietnam-sponsored government in
Phnom Penh.
   May 26, 1988 _ Vietnam says it will withdraw 50,000 soldiers,
described as half its force in Cambodia, by the end of the year.
   June 30, 1988 _ Officials say Vietnam's high command is
withdrawn from Cambodia and the running of the civil war turned
over to Phnom Penh.
   July 25-28, 1988 _ Vietnam meets the Cambodian resistance for
the first time in peace talks at Bogor, Indonesia. A consensus
emerges that Vietnamese withdrawal must be linked to preventing a
return to power by the Khmer Rouge.
   Nov. 6-8, 1988 _ Sihanouk and Hun Sen hold their third meeting,
this time joined by Son Sann.
   Dec. 19, 1988 _ China's Premier Li Peng says China will decrease
aid to the resistance as Vietnam withdraws and halt aid when the
troops are gone.
   Feb. 1-4, 1989 _ Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze makes the
highest-level Soviet visit to China in 30 years and broad agreement
is reached on Cambodia. May 15-18 for the first summit since the
1950s.
   Feb. 9, 1989 _ The latest resistance peace plan calls for a
2,000-member U.N. force to supervise Vietnam's withdrawal and
prevent a Khmer Rouge return, a four-party coalition government and
a limit of 10,000 fighters in each faction.
   Feb. 16-18, 1989 _ Disagreement arises at preparatory meetings
for a second round of peace talks.
   Feb. 19-21, 1989 _ The second session of talks in Jakarta,
Indonesia, ends with no progress and ``divergences'' of views,
participants say. The resistance accuses Vietnam and its Cambodian
ally of blocking peace.
   Wednesday _ Vietnam announces it will withdraw all forces by
Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
