<DOCNO> AP890405-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2021EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Poland-Solidarity     04-05 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Solidarity,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chronology of Survival of Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key events in the history of Solidarity:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1980</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 14 _ Electrician Lech Walesa leads occupation stike at
Gdansk's Lenin shipyard and starts worker revolt against communist
state.
   Aug. 31 _ Legal registration makes Solidarity Soviet bloc's only
independent union. During its 16 months of legal activity,
olidarity membership will grow to an estimated 10 million and a
sense of renewal will sweep the nation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1981</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 13 _ Martial law declared by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, Solidarity activities are suppressed and thousands of
members are interned, including Walesa.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1982</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 8 _ Solidarity banned and official trade union alliance
created to take its place. United States expands economic sanctions
against Poland.
   Nov. 11 _ Walesa freed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1983</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   July 22 _ Jaruzelski lifts martial law but leaves many
restrictive edicts.
   Oct. 5 _ Walesa wins Nobel Peace Prize.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   July 21 _ Amnesty is approved for political prisoners, including
11 prominent union leaders jailed after martial-law crackdown.
   Oct. 19 _ Popular pro-Solidarity priest, the Rev. Jerzy
Popieluszko, is slain. Four state security police will be tried and
convicted in the murder.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31 _ Walesa accuses government of presiding over a
political, economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide
mark fifth anniversary of Solidarity's birth.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1986</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 11 _ Government orders release of 225 political prisoners,
including all senior Solidarity leaders.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 19 _ Last of U.S. sanctions against Poland lifted.
   Nov. 29 _ Poles vote in first referendum in 41 years, but deny
government support for economic reform package.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   April 24-May 10 _ Strikes hit steel mills, shipyards and other
plants across Poland. Police break up one strike, others gradually
die out.
   Aug. 16 _ Workers declare a strike at July Manifesto coal mine.
Strikes spread, creating Poland's worst labor strife in seven years.
   Aug. 31 _ Walesa holds first meeting with government officials
in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes.
   Sept. 3 _ Strikes end after 19 days as Walesa asks for time to
talk with government.
   Oct. 25 _ Talks postponed as government objects to opposition
participants.
   Nov. 30, 1988 _ Walesa and Alfred Miodowicz, head of official
union alliance, hold live television debate. Walesa's convincing
performance rekindles plans for talks.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 17 _ Communist Party leadership decides Solidarity can be
legalized under certain conditions, meeting Solidarity's
prerequisite for talks.
   Feb. 6, 1989 _ Talks begin.
   Feb. 24, 1989 _ Negotiators agree on allowing legal independent
unions, including Solidarity, the farmers' Rural Solidarity and
students' union known as NZS.
   March 9, 1989 _ Negotiators agree on election reforms that will
create a senate, first freely elected legislative body in East
bloc. They also agree to create office of presidency, expected to
be retained by Communist Party, which is guaranteed a majority in
existing Sejm legislature for first election.
   Wednesday _ Walesa sealed a historic deal with the government to
restore the legal status of Solidarity and give Poland its first
democratic elections since World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
