<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Khrushchev-Speech 1stLd-Writethru a0667 04-05 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khrushchev-Speech, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0667,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khrushchev Speech Condemning Stalin to be Published in USSR</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 1 graf with circulation of magazine.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets soon will get their first chance to read
the ``secret speech'' that Nikita S. Khrushchev gave 33 years ago
condemning Josef Stalin's bloody years in power.
   Soviet TV, in its evening news broadcast ``Vremya,'' said a full
text of the speech is contained in the April edition of News of the
Communist Party Central Committee.
   For years, prominent Soviets have called for the publication of
Khrushchev's speech at the 20th Communist Party Congress on Feb.
25, 1956, three years after Stalin's death.
   The text was leaked almost immediately to the West and some
Soviets learned about it from summaries read at party meetings at
the time. But for the Soviet public at large, the details of the
speech have been a mystery.
   In the speech, ``On the cult of personality and its
consequences,'' Khrushchev accused Stalin of seriously damaging
Soviet society by purging the party. He said Stalin had used
torture, arrests and fabricated charges.
   He did not tell the whole story of Stalin's crimes, however,
omitting reference to Stalin's war against the peasants and
ignoring Khrushchev's own participation in the reign of terror.
   Khrushchev freed many people imprisoned under Stalin and pulled
back from other repressive measures, but the ``destalinization''
stopped after Khrushchev left office in 1964. President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev has resumed it, and discussion of Stalin's repressions is
now widespread.
   The News of the Communist Party Central Committee is the same
publication that in February printed another famous secret speech,
that of former Moscow party boss Boris N. Yeltsin. In that speech,
delivered at a Central Committee meeting in October 1987, Yeltsin
said Gorbachev was being glorified and that the Soviet people had
gained virtually nothing from the Soviet leader's reforms.
   The monthly says it has a circulation of 650,000, but ``Vremya''
said subscriptions were being expanded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Spill     04-05 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Spill,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contaminated Oil Spills into St. Maurice River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROIS RIVIERES, Quebec (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmental officials worked
Wednesday to contain a spill of about 1,768 gallons of oil laced
with toxic PCBs upstream from the city's supply of drinking water.
   ``We still don't know how serious it is for the drinking water
in Trois Rivieres,'' said Yvon Gelinas, spokesman for the
provincial Environment Department.
   He said the oil leaked into the St. Maurice River on Tuesday
while it was being transfered at the Consolidated-Bathurst Inc.
pulp and paper plant. Trois Rivieres, a city of 53,000 people, is
midway between Montreal and the city of Quebec.
   ``We're trying to recover as much oil as we can from the river
and put together an evaluation of the impact on the environment,''
Gelinas said.
   PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, are used mainly as a coolant
in electrical transformers. Their production has been banned in
Canada.
   In August, a fire at a warehouse storing PCB-laced oil forced
the evacuation of 3,300 people from a Montreal suburb.
</TEXT>
