<DOCNO> AP890405-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CruseTrial     04-05 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Trial,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Rejects Insanity Defense, Convicts Palm Bay Gunman of 32 Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury on Wednesday convicted a former
librarian of all charges that he shot and killed six people and
wounded 10 others in a rampage at two shopping centers in 1987.
   William Bryan Cruse Jr., 61, stood with bowed head and crossed
arms as Circuit Judge John Antoon read off the 32 guilty verdicts.
There was no reaction or comment from the frail, bearded defendant.
   The jury deliberated 10{ hours over two days before finding
Cruse guilty of six counts of first-degree murder, 22 counts of
attempted first-degree murder, two counts of attempted
second-degree murder, one count of kidnapping and one count of
false imprisonment.
   ``We're happy that the jury rejected the insanity defense and
found it was an act of cold-blooded murder,'' said State Attorney
Norm Wolfinger.
   The sentencing phase of the trial, in which jurors recommend a
non-binding verdict of death or a life sentence, begins April 17,
just a week before the second anniversary of the rampage at two
Palm Bay shopping centers.
   It would be up to Cruse to decide whether to appeal, said Public
Defender J.R. Russo, whose office represented the defendant.
   ``I've said all along I wanted him found guilty, that I wanted
him executed, and that I wanted to pull the switch,'' said Vi
Johnson, mother of Gerald Johnson, one of two police officers among
the six people killed.
   Her 27-year-old son lay wounded on the pavement next to his
patrol car in the Winn-Dixie supermarket parking lot when Cruse
approached with his high-powered rifle and fired three more bullets
into him.
   The prosecution argued this was only one example rebutting
defense contentions that the gunman was insane and didn't know what
he was doing.
   The defense argued that Cruse had been mentally ill for years
and was acting under delusions that everyone considered him
homosexual. Psychiatrists on both sides of the issue agreed on his
mental illness but disagreed sharply on the issue of legal insanity
under Florida law.
   In addition to mental illness, this requires a finding that the
defendant not know what he was doing or the consequences, and that
he did not know it was wrong.
   The shootout started when Cruse drove up to the Publix store
after an afternoon of drinking beer. He began firing from his car
and almost immediately killed Nobil Al-Hameli, 25, and Al-Tawakuly,
18, Kuwaitis attending a local college, as they emerged from a
store.
   Cruse then drove across the street into Sabal Palm Square, got
out of his car, shot Johnson and Officer Ronald Grogan, 28, and
fired dozens of other shots as motorists and pedestrians fled and
sought cover.
   He killed 67-year-old Ruth Green as she sat in her car. He shot
out the front windows of the Winn-Dixie Store, stormed in,
sporadically firing his semiautomatic Ruger Mini-14 and sending
dozens of shoppers fleeing out the back. The sixth victim, Lester
Watson, 51, was killed at that time.
   Cruse then found two store employees hiding in a restroom and
forced them out. He released one but held the other hostage for
about seven hours. At about 2 a.m., he released her and police
fired tear gas to force him out.
   Cruse has a history of mental instability and bizarre actions
daing to the 1970s in his hometown of Lexington, Ky., according to
psychiatrists and defense witnesses. He came to Florida in 1985.
   His main trial lawyer, Marlene Alva, called Cruse ``a madman, a
crazy person, someone who went berserk.''
   Wolfinger agreed Cruse was mentally ill. However, ``that's not
enough to find him legally insane,'' he said. ``We will seek the
death penalty.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Kenya-Rights     04-05 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Rights,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Hit Kennedy Clan For Criticizing Rights Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenyan legislators, taking their cue from
President Daniel arap Moi, are lambasting the Kennedy clan for
attacking this East African nation's human rights record.
   Moi kicked off a continuing orgy of vituperation Saturday by
rebuking the daughter of the late Sen. Robert F. Kennedy for her
criticisms.
   Kenya ``does not need a foreigner to supervise us,'' Moi told a
fund-raising party where he again denied his government abuses
human rights.
   The next day, Moi's words were echoed by a district chairman of
Kenya's sole legal political party, who announced plans for a
massive anti-Kennedy rally. The rally was canceled, but criticism
of the Kennedys continues.
   On Tuesday, Parliament set aside two hours for Cabinet members
and legislators to join the fray.
   More than 15 politicians stood to cast abuse on Mary Kerry
Kennedy, daughter of the one-time attorney general; her mother,
Ethel Kennedy; and her uncle, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.
   Vice President Josephat Karanja accused the Kennedys of being
``part and parcel of a campaign to discredit Kenya.''
   ``Democracy in Kenya is not at risk. It is very safe. It is the
reputation of Kuria and the Kennedys which is at risk.''
   All three of Nairobi's English-language newspapers carried
extensive coverage of the session in Wednesday editions that
dwelled on politicians' descriptions of Ms. Kennedy, 29, as ``this
little girl,'' ``this particular calf'' and ``this baby.''
   The Kennedys found no defenders.
   Kerry and Ethel Kennedy visited Nairobi last week to present the
1988 Robert F. Kennedy Human Rights Award to the country's leading
human rights lawyer, Gibson Kamau Kuria.
   The award was presented in Nairobi because the government
confiscated Kuria's passport, barring him from attending the
November ceremony at Georgetown University in Washington.
   Kuria was arrested in 1987 and detained as a security risk for
nine months without charge. He was arrested the day after he sued
the government for release of three political prisoners whom he
charged had been starved, confined in flooded cells and severely
beaten by their jailers.
   The award citation called Oxford-educated Kuria, 42, ``one of
the few lawyers in Kenya who defends political prisoners.'' It said
those who do ``fear government harassment, or worse.''
   Before departing Friday, Ms. Kennedy, executive director of the
Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Center for Human Rights, said she is
concerned about a Kenyan law permitting unlimited detention of
prisoners without charge or trial and Parliament's removal of
guaranteed tenure for judges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
