<FIRST>r i AM-India-Carbide     04-05 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Carbide,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Directs Union Carbide to Submit to Indian Courts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday asked the
government and Union Carbide Corp. to disclose all the negotiations
that led to a $470 million settlement for victims of the Bhopal gas
leak.
   The Press Trust of India news agency said a five-judge panel
asked the government to file an affidavit within three weeks
disclosing all documents, negotiations, and people involved in the
negotiations.
   The panel, headed by Chief Justice R.S. Pathak, said it was
passing the order to ascertain whether the Feb. 14 settlement was
reasonable, PTI said.
   Several opposition politicians and newspapers have termed the
settlement inadequate. The government originally sued Union Carbide
for $3 billion in connection with the 1984 gas leak in Bhopal.
   More than 3,000 people died and at least 20,000 were injured
when deadly methyl isocynate gas leaked Dec. 3, 1984 from a
pesticide plant run by the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide.
   Under a special law passed in Parliament, the government became
the sole representative of more than 500,000 people who claimed to
be Bhopal victims.
   The validity of the law has been challenged by at least two
petitions in the court.
   A five-judge panel of the court Wednesday heard arguments by
attorney Raj Kumar Garg on one of the petitions.
   ``This uncontrolled power appropriated by the government ...
would render the settlement void on the ground of impermissible and
excessive delegation of legislative function,'' PTI quoted Garg as
saying.
</TEXT>
