<FIRST>r i AM-India     04-05 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Curfew Imposed to Curb Riots; Five Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARUN JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government deployed troops and imposed a
curfew in the northern town of Anantnag on Wednesday to quell
violence by Moslem youths protesting the death of a leader in
police custody, a senior official said.
   Policemen were ordered to shoot rioters, who burned a Cabinet
minister's house, and hurled stones at police, said Moosa Raza, the
top administrator of Jammu-Kashmir, India's only Moslem majority
state.
   At least five people were injured when angry mobs in nearby
Srinagar clashed with police on the third consecutive day of a
Moslem strike to protest alleged police violence and the arrests of
Moslem youths, Raza said.
   Since the strike was called Monday, at least two people died and
39 others were injured, Raza said.
   On Wednesday, a bomb exploded in a suburb of Jammu, shattering
windows but causing no injuries, Raza said.
   Police in Anantnag, 75 miles north of Jammu, used tear gas to
disperse armed youths who stoned and set fire to the house of
Revenue Minister P.L. Handoo, a Hindu, Raza said. The town is
predominantly Moslem.
   Moslem mobs also attacked and burned a police station,
government buildings and the houses of several Hindus, Raza said. A
curfew was imposed and the army called in after police failed to
curb the violence, he said.
   The Moslems were protesting the death of Gulam Mohammed Shah,
who allegedly was beaten by police. According to Shah's son, Shabir
Ahmed, his father was dragged from his home and beaten by police,
allegedly for giving shelter to a pro-Pakistan Moslem militant.
   Police said the elder Shah died of natural causes when he was
called in for questioning.
   Jammu-Kashmir state is claimed by both India and Pakistan. The
neighbors have fought three wars since both became independent from
Britain in 1947. Troops from the United Nations patrol the state's
disputed borders.
</TEXT>
