<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1714EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Poland-Glance     04-05 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Glance,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>The `Round Table' Agreement at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What the government and opposition gained
and lost in the ``round-table'' talks that concluded Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TRADE UNIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The government agreed to allow the formation of independent
unions, specifically giving legal status to the independent trade
union Solidarity, and to legalize under a separate law the farmers'
union Rural Solidarity.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said restoration of the
independent groups, banned since the imposition of martial law in
December 1981, was the minimum requirement from the talks.
   An early victory for Solidarity in the talks was the agreement
by authorities to amend the existing labor law so that Solidarity
could be registered nationwide in one step, and not need to
register separately its internal structures.
   At the end of the talks, authorities agreed to a Solidarity
demand that workers fired for union activities after martial law be
legally entitled to reinstatement.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POLITICAL REFORMS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Elections _ Solidarity agreed to participate in parliamentary
elections, scheduled for June, in which the Communist Party and its
allies will be assured of a 65 percent majority in the 460-member
Sejm. Solidarity agreed to this essentially undemocratic
arrangement on condition it be for one time only. It poses the risk
Solidarity will be perceived as legitimizing communist rule.
   The government agreed to Solidarity's demand that subsequent
elections will either be fully or much more democratic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Senate _ A 100-member senate would be created and become the
first fully democratically chosen legislative chamber in the East
bloc. Anyone who collected 3,000 signatures could get on the ballot.
   The Senate would advise the Sejm and exercise veto powers over
its bills. It would take a two-thirds Sejm majority to override a
Senate veto. The government wanted the Senate to be weaker, while
Solidarity wanted the Senate's veto power to be strong.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   President _ The post of president would be created to be elected
by the Sejm and the senate to a six-year term this year. The
Communist Party, with its majority in the larger Sejm, could be
expected to control the election of the first president, who would
likely be the current party leader, Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski. The
president will be able to dissolve the National Assembly and call
new elections in cases of constitutional crisis, and be able to
veto Sejm acts the same way as the senate can.
   Solidarity originally had wanted either no presidency or a
weaker presidency, but agreed in exchange for the freely elected
senate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Associations _ Various pro-Solidarity professional associations,
for groups like artists and journalists, and the Independent
Students Association banned after martial law would be legalized.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL ISSUES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Indexation _ Wages would be indexed to increases in prices to
reduce the impact of inflation, now running at about 60 pecent
annually. Solidarity and the government agreed that wages would be
compensated at the rate of 80 percent of the inflation rate, unless
the payments would bankrupt the employer.
   The government had originally opposed indexation, saying it
would fuel inflation. The official trade union OPZZ raised an
objection that the cost-of-living compensation should be 100
percent, not 80 percent, and paid in a lump sum to workers rather
than a percentage of their pay.
   Media access _ The opposition would get access to the media,
including a daily newspaper and two weeklies and at least one
program a week on national TV and radio, with a Solidarity
supporter who is also agreeable to the government serving as host.
Censorship would be eased.
   Solidarity failed to win its aim for the opposition to have
sovereign control of an allotted block of TV and radio time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
