<SECOND>AM-Witness Bombed,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness In Drug Probe Killed In Truck Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEBRING, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck bombing killed a witness in a
3-year-old federal drug smuggling investigation and authorities
fear it was ordered by targets of the probe.
   James Collins Sr., 60, of Sebring, died of massive burns and
injuries Tuesday after plastic explosives detonated in the truck he
was driving, said Sam Jones, an agent with the Florida Department
of Law Enforcement. The explosives were hooked to the truck's
battery, he said.
   ``Mr. Collins, his sons and his son-in-law were all witnesses in
pending federal drug cases,'' Jones said. ``Those cases are
ongoing, and we've placed family members and other associates of
the victim in protective custody.''
   Philip Ramer, head of the law enforcement agency's Tampa office,
said he believed the explosion was connected to Collins'
cooperation with federal authorities.
   Collins was backing the truck along a driveway when the cab
exploded, witnesses said.
   Anthony Simonetti, sitting in his garage across the street, said
the blast knocked him back six feet.
   ``There was a lot of flame, and then I saw that poor old man
trying to squeeze through the window,'' he said.
   Debris was thrown up to 100 feet away.
   The drug investigation, dubbed Operation Overlook, is being
conducted by the Fort Myers office of the state law enforcement
agency in conjunction with U.S. Customs, the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration and other agencies, Jones said.
</TEXT>
