<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PulloutResults     04-05 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pullout Results,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam's Pullout From Cambodia Could Mean Better Relations With
U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Vietnam-Cambodia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Esper spent 10 years covering the Vietnam
War for The Associated Press and recently completed his second
reporting visit to the country since the war ended in 1975.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE ESPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Vietnam's announcement Wednesday that it will withdraw
all troops from Cambodia by Sept. 30 appears to be a major first
step toward diplomatic relations with the United States after more
than 40 years of estrangement.
   But a historic exchange of ambassadors between Washington and
Hanoi still appears a way off.
   A verifiable withdrawal of the estimated 70,000 Vietnamese
troops in Cambodia and compliance with other U.S demands including
the restoration of peace and an elected government in a neutral,
non-aligned Cambodia, would remove major obstacles to U.S.
recognition.
   Diplomatic relations between the United States and Vietnam would
probably bring American aid, which Hanoi needs badly to catch up
economically and technically with the rest of the world.
   Diplomatic recognition could expedite humanitarian concerns.
These include a quicker accounting of as many as possible of the
2,383 Americans listed as missing in action and more rapid
immigration to the United States of 10,000 to 16,000 Amerasians,
children of American fathers and Vietnamese mothers born during the
war between 1963 and 1975.
   Ending the U.S. trade embargo could open the way for American
investment in Vietnam, including oil exploration, and improve
Vietnam's trade imbalance. The country now imports three times more
than what it exports.
   Realizing it cannot survive with 25 percent unemployment and
high inflation, Vietnam appears to be emerging as more open and
conciliatory. It is opening its doors and its harbors, even
courting capitalism, and welcoming American visitors back more than
ever before.
   Vietnamese officials seem to think that the withdrawal of their
troops from Cambodia after 10 years will accommodate the United
States and save Vietnam's failing economy. Vietnam has been
ostracized and isolated from Western aid because of its occupation
of Cambodia.
   ``As the U.S. has repeatedly said that they will normalize
relations with Vietnam after we withdraw all our forces from
Cambodia, we're now waiting to see if they keep their promise,''
said Ha Huy Thong, a spokesman for Vietnam's Permanent Mission to
the United Nations.
   ``That's not exactly what we said,'' declared Ken Bailes, a
spokesman for the State Department's Office of Vietnam, Laos and
Cambodia Affairs.
   ``We do believe that if the withdrawal is carried out, it would
be a positive development,'' the State Department said in a
statement.
   The U.S. position is that it is prepared to move ahead with
normalization of relations with Vietnam once there is an acceptable
settlement in Cambodia, of which the withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops is only one component.
   ``We believe any agreement which fails to address Cambodia's
future in a comprehensive manner would not be sustainable,'' said
Bailes. ``Important differences remain, particularly on the
formation of an interim government pending elections.''
   As part of a comprehensive accord, the United States has
proposed safeguards against the return of the communist Khmer
Rouge, under whose reign an estimated 2 million Cambodians _
one-fourth of the country's population _ were executed or died of
famine.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, ousting the Khmer
Rouge and installing a government headed by Prime Minister Hun Sen.
   Vietnamese troops have kept Hun Sen in power by beating back a
coalition of Cambodian resistance forces led by Prince Norodom
Sihanouk. The coalition consists of two non-communist factions and
the Khmer Rouge.
   The Khmer Rouge, backed by China, is by far the strongest of the
three factions.
   The United States believes that in any acceptable settlement,
Sihanouk, a former Cambodian leader during the American war, must
head the interim government preceding elections. This is another
stumbling block in U.S.-Vietnamese relations.
   Hun Sen opposes the demand that his government be set aside in
favor of an interim government. He and Sihanouk are scheduled to
meet in Jakarta, Indonesia, on May 2 in efforts to reach an
agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0169 </DOCNO>
