<FIRST>r a AM-LaRoucheAide     04-05 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LaRouche Aide,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>LaRouche Associate Convicted of Nine Counts of Securities Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEESBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rochelle Ascher, an associate of political
extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr., was convicted Wednesday of nine
counts of securities violations stemming from LaRouche's
fund-raising activities.
   A Loudoun County Circuit Court jury convicted Ms. Ascher, 38, of
Towson, Md., on single counts of selling an unregistered security
with intent to defraud, sale of a security by an unregistered agent
with intent to defraud, conspiracy, and six counts of securities
fraud involving six sales to four individuals.
   The trial began Jan. 23, and the jury deliberated for more than
five days. The jury fixed the sentence at 86 years in prison.
Virginia Attorney General Mary Sue Terry said the length of the
prison term was ``extraordinary, for a crime in which violence was
not an element.''
   In a statement issued from prison, LaRouche accused both the
jury and Judge Carlton Penn of being ``crooked.''
   LaRouche is serving a 15-year federal prison term for scheming
to defraud federal tax collectors and conspiring to deliberately
default on $30 million in loans from political supporters. LaRouche
failed in presidential bids in 1976, 1980, 1984 and 1988.
   State officials said Ms. Ascher, 15 co-defendants and five
LaRouche organizations were part of a fund-raising operation that
allegedly bilked hundreds of people out of millions of dollars.
   State and federal officials raided LaRouche's Leesburg
headquarters in 1987 to cap an investigation by the Virginia
attorney general's office into allegations that LaRouche supporters
secured loans under false pretenses.
   The trial of other defendants has been moved to Roanoke,
officials said.
   Some of Ms. Ascher's fellow defendants and several former
members of the LaRouche organization testified for the prosecution,
describing the group's fund-raising methods. The money paid for
LaRouche publications, his Leesburg ``safe house'' and television
commercials during his presidential bids.
   During the trial, Ms. Ascher testified she was aware of ``some
problems with repaying loans.'' She said, however, there was never
a policy against repaying the loans.
   Ms. Ascher, who left a teaching position at the Medical College
of Virginia in Richmond in 1980 to join the LaRouche organization,
was a victim of poor record-keeping, her attorney contended during
the trial.
</TEXT>
