<HEAD>USDA Will Boost Purchases to Spur Sagging Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government purchases of pork for donation to
schools and other institutions will be stepped up to help bolster
sagging hog prices paid to farmers, Agriculture Secretary Clayton
Yeutter said Wednesday.
   The Agriculture Department ``not only has bought more pork this
year, but it also has bought a greater variety of pork items than
in prior years,'' Yeutter said.
   Frozen hams and canned pork are the main items bought by USDA
for distribution to schools and other domestic programs. In
addition, the department soon will begin buying canned luncheon
meat, including pork, he said.
   Farmers have marketed ``unusually high'' numbers of hogs in
recent months, which has helped depress market prices, Yeutter
said. Since July 1, the beginning of the current purchasing year,
USDA has spent more than $96 million for pork, compared with $30
million the previous year.
