<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BabySwap     04-05 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Swap,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Who Believe Baby Was Swapped at Birth Petition Appelate Court
Anew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUCHULA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple want an appellate court to
reconsider a decision they say could keep them from getting to know
a girl they believe is their daughter lost in a hospital baby swap
a decade ago.
   Ernest and Regina Twigg of Langhorne, Pa., asked the 2nd
District Court of Appeal in Lakeland on Tuesday to reconsider a
ruling last month ordering them to suspend their quest unless they
prove it won't hurt the 10-year-old Sarasota girl they suspect is
their natural daughter.
   Before a judge orders genetic testing of Kimberly Mays, the girl
the Twiggs believe is their daughter, the Twiggs must be specific
about what kind of relationship they want with the girl and must
prove their search won't harm her, a three-judge panel said last
month.
   The ruling backed Robert Mays, a Sarasota roofing contractor who
said his daughter Kimberly might suffer emotional harm if forced to
undergo a genetic test that could threaten her sense of security.
   The Twiggs believe their newborn daughter was swapped 10 years
ago at a Wauchula hospital for the child of Mays and his late wife
Barbara.
   The child raised by the Twiggs, named Arlena, died of congenital
heart disease in 1988. Tests showed Arlena was not related to
either Ernest or Regina Twigg.
   The Twiggs later asked a Sarasota Circuit judge to determine
whether Kimberly is their child. Mays has resisted efforts to test
Kimberly, saying he will not jeopardize his custody of the daughter
he has raised and loved.
   John Blakely, the Twiggs' attorney, asked to make oral arguments
before the appellate court, for review by all 12 judges or for the
court to refer the key questions to the Florida Supreme Court.
   At the heart of the case is whose interests the court should
consider.
   The appellate judges said the child's welfare supersedes the
rights of the parents. Blakely disagrees, saying the ruling
overlooks the Twiggs' constitutional right to custody of a natural
child.
   After the Twiggs declare what sort of relationship they seek
with Kimberly, the appellate panel said a circuit judge would have
to determine if she would be hurt by such a relationship before
allowing a genetic test.
   Mays' attorney, Arthur Ginsburg, could not be reached Wednesday.
His assistant, Judy Lee, said he had not read the court documents
and wouldn't comment until he did.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
