<FIRST>r i AM-Hamadi     04-05 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hamadi,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Told Voice On Dramatic Recording Could Be Confessed Hijacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court-appointed translator said
Wednesday one voice in a dramatic conversation recorded between a
hijacked TWA jetliner and Beirut Airport likely is that of
confessed air pirate Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   The Frankfurt court also heard Wednesday that the Lebanese
Shiite Moslem terrorist was 21 years old at the time of the 1985
hijacking, and a document he produced claiming he is several years
younger is forged. The ruling will affect sentencing.
   Hamadi is charged with murder and piracy. U.S. Navy diver Robert
Stethem was murdered and 39 Americans were held hostage 17 days
during the ordeal.
   On Wednesday, the court played a tape recording made after the
hijacked airliner, which was flying from Athens to Rome, landed at
Beirut Airport on June 14, 1985.
   The tape recorded the crew's pleas to land at Beirut, with one
saying: ``He (a hijacker) has two hand grenades. We must land at
Beirut, no alternative.''
   It includes sounds of the crew being beaten, and a shout of
``Help!''
   Later, after the plane landed and the hijacker's demands for
fuel were not quickly met, a crewman shouts: ``They are threatening
to kill the passengers! They are beating the passengers! We want
the fuel now _ immediately!''
   At one point an excited voice tells the tower in Arabic: ``Our
grenade is armed! Our weapons are ready! If something doesn't
happen in 1{ minutes I will throw out the first corpse!''
   The following day, Stethem was shot and his body was thrown onto
the airport tarmac. Hamadi says Stethem was killed by his
accomplice, Hassan Ezzedine, who is a fugitive.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger asked translator Chesar Magdi
for her opinion of the Arabic voice on the tape, obtained from the
British Broadcasting Corp.
   Mrs. Magdi is considered an expert on Hamadi's speech pattern.
She told the court she felt Hamadi had not spoken on another tape
produced by the FBI.
   She described that voice as deeper than Hamadi's, and said the
Arabic dialect used for the word ``minute'' did not match Hamadi's.
   However, she said the hijacker's voice on the BBC tape ``is more
the lighter voice. The use of the word `minute' I mentioned earlier
also matches.'' The bearded Hamadi sat quietly, showing no reaction.
   Also Wednesday, Mueckenberger said Lebanese officials confirmed
that a verification document listing Hamadi's birthday as July 15,
1968, is forged. Hamadi is being tried by a juvenile court because
of conflicting claims, with court records showing he was born June
13, 1964. Under West German law, Hamadi's maturity at the time of
the hijacking could affect his sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
