<DOCNO> AP890405-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PayRaise     04-05 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pay Raise,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Weighs Judicial Pay Raise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is seriously considering
proposing a 25 percent pay raise for federal judges, a senior
administration official said Wednesday.
   Discussing Bush's thinking on the condition he not be named
publicly, the official also said that the presidential pay raise
recommendation could come in conjunction with an ethics bill to be
sent to Capitol Hill next week.
   But this official also said that ``no final-decision memo'' has
yet reached Bush's desk for the president's consideration.
   Last week, Bush said he would make ``very specific proposals''
on pay increases for top federal officials, even though Congress
two months ago rejected a proposal that would have given lawmakers
a 50 percent pay raise.
   That proposal, advanced by the Commission on Legislative,
Executive and Judicial Salaries, would have included hikes for
federal judges and approximately 7,000 top executives.
   The Bush administration official said Wednesday that, among
other options still under consideration at the White House, was a
series of pay hikes for certain categories of federal officials
rather than an across-the-board raise.
   The Washington Post reported in its Wednesday editions that Bush
would propose a 25 per pay hike for the judges. Most federal judges
now make $89,500 per year, the same salary as members of Congress
and top federal officials.
   An administration source said that Bush had not yet settled on a
figure. But another official noted that a commission studying
federal jobs had recommended a 25 percent pay raise, and that that
figure was the one being focused on by the White House. The
commission, headed by former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker,
made its report public late last month.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, a former
federal judge himself, said Wednesday that it was ``premature to
speculate on what is not yet a recommendation.''
   Mitchell said ``no one had talked to him'' from the
administration about a pay raise for federal judges.
   As for separating Congress from the pay raises, Mitchell said,
``There appears to be a widespread feeling that de-linking salaries
would make it more difficult for members of Congress ever to get
increases in pay.''
</TEXT>
