<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Right     04-05 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Right,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Crash Rally Led By Former SS Soldier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 protesters shouting ``Nazis
Out'' crashed a rally led by a former Nazi SS soldier on Wednesday
night and were thrown out by participants.
   Witnesses said fistfights broke out between some demonstrators
and participants acting as security guards in the crowded community
center in the Bonn suburb of Bad Godesberg.
   About 1,200 members of the ultra-rightist Republican party and
their supporters gathered at the hall for the first national rally
held by the party.
   Outside, about 700 people protested in a driving rain.
Demonstrators threw eggs at helmeted riot police, and shoving
matches broke out between some protesters and Republican supporters.
   Several hundred police officers, some with attack dogs, manned
barricades in the area.
   Activists who say the Republican party harbors anti-Semitic and
neo-Nazi sentiments had vowed to disrupt the rally, and about 50
demonstrators sneaked in using phony invitations.
   When party leader Franz Schoenhuber began to deliver his speech,
the infiltrators began shouting ``Nazis Out.''
   Most of the protesters were thrown out, but some who were quiet
during the initial outbreak remained. Five of them leaped up and
blasted air horns when Schoenhuber began explaining his service as
a Nazi SS soldier during World War II.
   ``This is a neo-Fascist party and must be stopped,'' said Klaus
Drosten, one of those evicted from the hall. ``We find it
frightening that this party is becoming a rallying point for
nationalist zealots.''
   Schoenhuber, 66, told his supporters, ``I am not a Nazi, I am a
German patriot.''
   He also predicted that the Republicans would become a prominent
political party.
   ``Next year we will be thousands, and in three years we will be
hundreds of thousands. I promise you that in 1990 we Republicans
will be the third-strongest party in the federal republic,'' he
said.
   The party now has 13,000 members, 70 percent of them under 30
years old, Schoenhuber said.
   Left-wing organizations accuse the Republicans of being
neo-Fascist and hostile toward the millions of foreign workers and
immigrants living in West Germany.
   The party surprised many when it won 7.5 percent of the vote in
Berlin elections in January with a campaign that called for halting
the influx of foreigners seeking asylum. Some fear the foreigners
are taking jobs and housing from native West Germans.
   More than 200,000 immigrants of German descent arrived in West
Germany last year from the Soviet Union, Poland and other East
European nations. More than 50,000 other foreign workers won
political asylum.
   ``We are of the opinion that the country can no longer bear the
economic costs of allowing guest workers from Turkey to seek asylum
here,'' Schoenhuber said at the rally.
   He said his position was grounded in economics, not racism.
   He also disclosed he was earlier married to an American, and
that his 29-year-old daughter, Susanne Schoenhuber-Baer, lives and
works in Washington.
   Schoenhuber said he was never a member of the Nazi party and
dismissed his service as a SS soldier as the ``freely taken
decision of an 18-year-old attracted by uniforms and adventure.''
</TEXT>
