<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-05 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Plans Coalition To Take Over Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four political parties planned Wednesday to form a
coalition shadow government they hope will govern if a major
stock-profiteering scandal forces Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
to resign.
   Party leaders planned an opposition summit for Friday as
Takeshita suffered another blow _ news reports that the company at
the scandal's center contributed $381,700 to fund-raising parties
for him in May 1987.
   Despite public opinion polls showing his popularity as low as 9
percent, Takeshita refuses to resign. Instead, he vows to make
reforms and regain public trust.
   The proposed opposition coalition excludes the Japan Communist
Party, which has differences with most other parties. Prospective
coalition partners also differ over such issues as U.S.-Japan
security arrangements, the two Koreas and atomic power plants.
   Their leaders, however, propose setting those aside to work for
Takeshita's downfall.
   They plan to meet Friday in Kyoto, western Japan, to discuss
strategy against Takeshita's Liberal Democratic Party, which holds
297 of the 512 seats in the parliament's lower house, and 143 of
the 252 in the upper house.
   Takako Doi, chairman of the largest opposition Japan Socialist
Party, told reporters Tuesday, ``The only alternative left for the
government is to resign en masse and accept the people's judgment
(at elections).''
   Others in the proposed coalition are Komeito, or Clean
Government Party, the Democratic Socialist Party and the United
Social Democratic Party.
   Takeshita disclosed Friday that Recruit Co. spent $152,700 on a
fund-raising party for him in May 1987, when he was a leading
contender for prime minister.
   The nationwide newspaper Asahi Shimbun and others reported
Wednesday that Takeshita received another $229,000 from Recruit at
another fund-raising party that month.
   Takeshita refused to comment. ``I do not have detailed
information,'' he told reporters.
   But one of his aides, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed Recruit had bought tickets to the second party, though he
did not know how many.
   Recruit, an information services conglomerate, sold
bargain-priced unlisted shares in a subsidiary to about 150
influential politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen, who profited
handsomely when public trading began.
   So far, 14 bureaucrats and businessmen have been arrested on
charges of bribery or violating securities laws in the deals. Three
Cabinet ministers linked to the scandal have resigned.
   Japanese politicians customarily use fund-raising parties to
sidestep legal restrictions on political donations. Large
corporations buy large blocks of party tickets, but Takeshita
acknowledged last week that Recruit's purchases were ``slightly
excessive.''
   Such parties are considered legal ``as long as the price of each
ticket is within the range of common sense and the number of
tickets purchased is within a reasonable limit of what a company
can possibly use,'' a Home Affairs official said on condition of
anonymity.
   ``With his ties with Recruit coming into light bit by bit,
Takeshita's already faltering leadership is deteriorating
rapidly,'' Asahi Shimbun said in a Wednesday editorial.
   At least 17 politicians, including former Prime Minister
Yasuhiro Nakasone, have been implicated in the scandal. None has
been arrested, but prosecutors still are questioning politicians
and their aides.
</TEXT>
