<HEAD>Chad Officials Reported Arrested After Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>N'DJAMENA, Chad (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One top-ranking government official was
arrested, one fled and another was missing after participating in a
weekend coup attempt against the government of President Hissene
Habre, diplomats said Wednesday.
   People trying to enter or leave the capital were stopped at
military roadblocks, according to sources who asked not to be
identified.
   Interior Minister Mahamat Itno was arrested after Saturday's
unsuccessful coup, while Army commander, Hassan Djamous fled
N'Djamena and the president's military adviser, Idriss Debi, was
missing, sources said.
   A Chadian nationalist group issued a statement in Brussels,
Belgium Wednesday, saying mass arrests were occurring in the
capital.
   Itno, Djamous and Debi reportedly staged the coup after Habre's
Anakaza tribe attempted to take key government administrative and
military posts. The officials hoped to maintain the Hadjarai and
Zakawa tribes in the government, sources said.
   In November 1987, Habre signed a peace pact in Baghdad, Iraq,
with former rebel leader Ibn Omar, who was appointed foreign
minister earlier this year.
   The pact led to the government's reconciliation with numerous
political opponents.
