<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1751EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru a0677 04-05 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says He's Encouraged By Talks With Shamir</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Wednesday he was encouraged by suggestions by Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir for settling the Arab-Israeli dispute and
hoped they would form a basis for advancing peace in the Middle
East.
   While U.S. and Israeli officials would not say what Baker and
Shamir had discussed, the prime minister said last week he would
propose holding elections among Palestinian Arabs under Isareli
control to select their leaders for talks with his government.
   Avi Pazner, the prime minister's media adviser, said Shamir and
Baker had decided ``not to say anything, not to reveal anything''
about Shamir's proposals. Pazner did say that a joint group of
Israeli and U.S. officials had beeb convened to discuss the
suggestions in advance of Shamir's meeting Thursday with President
Bush.
   Meanwhile, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, in an interview
with Cable News Network, said Shamir's proposal for elections
without the participation of the Palestine Liberation Organization,
if carried through, ``will be a grave mistake, it will not solve
the problem.''
   Baker, after his two-hour meeting with Shamir, called their talk
``very productive, useful and very friendly.''
   For his part, Shamir said he had offered ``some ways to solve''
problems in the Mideast and remarked:
   ``I feel we have started a very serious discussion. Our
conversation was very friendly.''
   There were widespread expectations before Shamir's meeting with
Baker that the Bush administration would talk a tough stance toward
Israel. A senior U.S. official, briefing reporters at the White
House on Tuesday under rules of anonymity, prediced a ``candid''
discussion, the diplomatic way of predicting disagreements.
   But Pazner told reporters afterward, ``I didn't see any
hardening of position.''
   Shamir said last week he would propose elections among the 1.4
million Palestinian Arabs who live under Israeli control on the
West Bank and in Gaza, with the aim of picking leaders to negotiate
with Israel over the Palestinians' future.
   Israel has controlled the West Bank and Gaza since its lightning
victory over Egypt, Jordan and Syria in the 1967 Six-Day War. On
Monday, Bush called on Israel to end what he said was its
``occupation'' as part of an overall settlement with the Arabs.
   Since December 1987, when the Palestinians launched a concerted
campaign to challenge Israel, the territories have been shrouded by
violence in which 419 Palestinians and 18 Israelis have died.
   Shamir has ruled out negotiating with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which he holds responsible for that violence and for
an unceasing campaign of terrorism against Israel.
   He told a conference of Jewish-American organization leaders
that sitting with the PLO would ``bring disaster.''
   Instead, he has sought to revive the 1978 Camp David agreements'
promise of a transitional period of autonomy for the Palestinians
and then negotiations for an overall settlement.
   ``The prime minister has made some suggestions,'' Baker said.
``We are going to continue our discussion with the objective of
moving the peace process forward, if it's possible to do so. They
were very encouraging. Hopefully they will form the basis under
which we can move the peace process forward.''
   Shamir followed Mubarak to Washington. The Egyptian leader said
toward the end of his visit on Tuesday that he saw no way to stop
the violence in the territories.
   ``If anybody could stop it, we would be very pleased,'' Mubarak
said, asking, ``But how?''
   Baker suggested last month that Israel might have to talk to the
PLO, with which the United States opened its first talks in
December.
   Mubarak, in the CNN interview, said he would like Bush to
explain to Shamir that a Mideast peace conference would lead to
direct Arab-Israel peace talks.
   Such a conference would not have the power to dictate to either
the Israelis or the Arabs or veto their decisions, and ``Shamir
knows this,'' Mubarak said.
   ``Direct negotiations will be coming by hook or by crook through
this international conference,'' he said.
   Shamir is reluctant to enter a peace conference in which the
Soviet Union might play a prominent role. He is concerned the
Soviets would be inclined to favor the Arabs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
