<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2121EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Children'sTV     04-05 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children's TV,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bills Introduced to Restrict Ads on Children's TV Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to stem the ``crass
commercialization'' of children's television was introduced in the
House and Senate on Wednesday to the applause of public groups
trying to reduce the amount of cereal, toy and candy advertising on
the programs.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said he was co-sponsoring the
Senate measure on behalf of his six grandchildren and all the
nation's youngsters.
   He said broadcasters ``have failed to meet their obligations to
children'' and it was necessary, therefore, for Congress to
intervene since the Federal Communications Commission repealed ad
restrictions on children's television in 1984.
   ``The FCC's hands-off approach has created an environment where
broadcasters have focused not on children's developmental needs but
on crass commercialism ... cash, cash and more cash,'' Metzenbaum
said.
   The bill, sponsored by Metzenbaum and Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J., in the Senate, would limit ads on children's shows to 10{
minutes per hour on weekends and 12 minutes per hour on weekdays,
effective next year.
   It also would require the FCC to consider how well a broadcaster
has been committed to the educational and informational needs of
children in its overall programming.
   The House and Senate bills are virtually identical to
legislation passed by Congress last year but vetoed by
then-President Reagan.
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., said the bills were adopted in
cooperation with the three major television networks, the National
Association of Broadcasters and the Association of Independent
Television Stations.
   ``This legislation is needed to ensure that broadcasters treat
children as consumers of information and new ideas, not just
consumers of candy, cereal and toys,'' Markey said.
   Markey is chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, which will hold
hearings on the bill Thursday.
   The bill was introduced in the House by Reps. John Bryant,
D-Texas; Matthew Rinaldo, R-N.J., and Terry Bruce, D-Ill., and had
14 co-sponsors.
   The legislation has wide support from psychiatric, health and
educational groups, and has been a 20-year aim of Peggy Charren of
Action for Children's Television in Boston.
   Charren, who introduced each lawmaker at the news conference,
said the bill would impose on broadcasters the ``three R's of
television: restriction, requirement and reporting.''
   She said it was a ``cost-effective way to provide information
and education to young audiences without raising taxes, without
raising the deficit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Vets-Derwinski     04-05 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vets-Derwinski,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Hospitals Will be Closed, Secretary Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veterans Affairs Department doesn't intend
to close any of its hospitals but may change some of their
assignments, the head of the newest Cabinet department said
Wednesday.
   All 172 veterans hospitals ``cannot be all-purpose entities,''
Secretary Edward Derwinski said in answering questions after a
luncheon speech at the National Press Club.
   ``Logically, there has to be a degree of specialization.''
   Veterans hospitals already have scores of agreements for using
military hospitals and vice versa, and Derwinski said he hopes to
expand those. He did not directly answer when asked what he thought
of merging the veterans and military hospital systems.
   ``We have, if anything, a shortage of facilities,'' Derwinski
said. He and other officials have said they expect that as the
nation's 27 million veterans age, many will retire to the Sunbelt,
putting pressure on veterans facilities in those states.
   ``We have no intention whatsoever of closing any veterans
medical facilities,'' Derwinski said. In addition to the hospitals,
the department operates 226 outpatient clinics and dozens of other
installations.
   Derwinski served 24 years in the House as a Republican from the
Chicago suburbs. He told his audience that he well recognized that
all members of Congress must try to protect the federal
installations in their districts, and ``We're going to cooperate
with them.''
   ``To demonstrate that this must not be a parochial issue, let me
cite the example of Chicago _ my own home base. There are four VA
medical centers in the Chicago area, three of them within 12 miles
of one another,'' he said in a passage in his prepared text that he
did not deliver.
   ``Our ability to provide quality care to veterans in the future,
with some degree of geographic equity, depends on a serious review
of the costs of duplication and other problems posed by overlapping
services,'' the text continued.
   On other subjects, Derwinski said:
   _He will appoint a ``totally balanced, objective group'' to try
to reach consensus and advise him within 90 days on what to do
about Agent Orange. The department's predecessor agency, the
Veterans Administration, maintained there was no evidence that
soldiers exposed to the herbicide in Vietnam suffered adverse
health effects; many veterans advocates say they did.
   _Reporters should ``investigate what we're doing. You help me
shake up the system and make it work better'' by reporting problems.
   _Veterans organizations ``are not really a powerful lobby,'' but
are among the rare lobbies that have no opposing lobbies: ``Nobody
in his right mind is against veterans.''
</TEXT>
