<FIRST>r w AM-SuperCollider     04-05 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Super Collider,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says Collider Devoid of Support In Scientific Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The super collider is ``virtually devoid of
support'' in the scientific community, a Pennsylvania Republican
told Congress Wednesday during a hearing to review the selection
process that awarded the $4.6 billion particle accelerator to Texas.
   ``The real question is not how, it is now where, not when, it is
if'' it will be built, Rep. Don Ritter said after the House
committee hearing. ``The real issue is, are we going to commit $10
billion.''
   Ritter said he has found a ``decided lack of interest'' within
the engineering and scientific community and even ``hostility''
toward the proposed spending of what he estimates as $10 billion
over the next decade on the high-energy physics project.
   The Energy Department estimates construction costs at $4.6
billion.
   Ritter said scientists outside the high-energy physics community
were never involved in Congress' decision to pursue construction of
the collider, which backers hope will help science better
understand the fundamental nature of matter.
   ``This program is virtually devoid of support from the
scientific and engineering community,'' Ritter told the House
Science, Space and Technology Committee.
   Rep. Ralph Hall, a Texas Democrat and member of the committee,
said he agrees there is some opposition to the project in the
scientific community, as well as support.
   `It's hard for me to believe there's quote `no' support at any
level of science,'' Hall said. ``I think there is some support for
it, but it's correct to say there's some opposition.''
   The subcommittee on energy research and development was
scheduled to decide Thursday whether to authorize construction of
the project, but officials say the real battle in Congress will be
over the level of financing and what is essential to begin actually
building the 53-mile underground tunnel on farmland south of Dallas.
</TEXT>
