<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-05 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunder In Florida, Rain Along The East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wet weather spread over much of the East on Wednesday, while
high wind blew across the central Rockies and southern California
had another unusually hot day with temperatures of 100 and more.
   Showers were scattered ahead of a cold front that stretched from
southern New England across the middle Atlantic Coast states to the
Florida Panhandle.
   Strong thunderstorms developed in warm, moist, unstable air over
the central Florida Peninsula.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
0.73 of an inch at Panama City, Fla.
   Very cold, unstable air over the Great Lakes contributed to the
development of showers across that region. Hail the size of peas
fell west of Springfield, Ill.
   High wind blew over the central Rockies. In western Wyoming,
wind gusted to near 70 mph at Crowheart.
   The wind created blowing-snow conditions across sections of the
Colorado Rockies, where as much as 6 feet of snow had fallen by
Wednesday from a storm that stalled for a week. Some ski resorts
considered extending their seasons.
   Light rain fell over the northern Rockies and along the coast of
Washington state.
   Also in the Northwest, warming weather was blamed for an
avalanche that covered all four lanes of U.S. 2 at Stevens Pass in
Washington's Cascade Mountains early Wednesday. There were no
injuries and one lane was reopened by midday.
   Sections of southern California and the desert Southwest had
readings in the 90s and above. By midday, downtown Los Angeles had
reached 96 degrees and Santa Ana sizzled at 100 degrees.
   On Tuesday, Los Angeles hit a record 100 degrees and Los Angeles
County lifeguards telephoned reserves for extra help, adding dozens
of lifeguards to monitor an estimated 100,000 beachgoers.
   The unseasonably warm weather was a result of an upper level
high pressure system off the southern California coast. But the
Santa Ana winds that began Sunday and ushered in the April
temperatures began diminishing Wednesday, allowing smog to invade
the region.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 104 at Ontario, Calif. Wednesday's
low in the Lower 48 states was 14 degrees at Alamosa, Colo.
   For Thursday, showers and some thunderstorms were forecast from
eastern sections of the middle Atlantic Coast states to New
England. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast over the
northern Plains and southern sections of the upper Mississippi
Valley. Rain also was forecast from coastal Washington state to
western Montana.
   Highs in the 30s were predicted from northeastern Minnesota to
Upper Michigan; in the 40s and 50s from the coast of Washington
state across the northern Rockies, the northern Plains and
Nebraska, much of the upper and middle Mississippi Valley, the
Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and all of the Appalachians to New
England; in the 80s over the southern Florida Peninsula, and from
south-central and southwestern Texas across southern New Mexico and
western Nevada to the central Pacific Coast; in the 90s across
southern Arizona and southern California; above 100 across the
desert Southwest; and generally in the 60s and 70s over the
remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
