<FIRST>r p AM-MadisonMayor     04-05 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Madison Mayor,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mayor Captures Wisconsin Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former three-term mayor ousted the
incumbent three-term mayor in an mayoral election that observers
said Wednesday was dominated by image rather than substance.
   Paul Soglin, a former anti-war demonstrator who was mayor from
1973 to 1979, garnered almost 57 percent of Tuesday's vote in
defeating three-term incumbent Joseph Sensenbrenner.
   ``Joe carried a lot of image baggage of `Joe the bumbler,'''
City Council President Ron Trachtenberg, a Sensenbrenner supporter,
said Wednesday. ``In trying to form consensus quietly he was seen
as a wimp, which he shouldn't be seen as.''
   Soglin also brings political baggage to the mayor's office, said
local politician Rick Berg. ``It remains to be seen whether this is
the same old Paul Soglin or a new Paul Soglin,'' he said.
   Soglin, whose legacy as an anti-war protester in the 1960s
helped put him in the mayor's office during his previous three
terms, recaptured his old job by running as a fiscal conservative,
although he still describes himself as a political liberal.
   ``I think I got greater support among conservatives because they
felt I could handle budget issues better ... better than before and
better than Sensenbrenner,'' Soglin said.
   With all 66 wards counted in the college city of 175,000
residents, Soglin had won with 34,537 votes to 26,280 votes for
Sensenbrenner.
   Meanwhile, state elections officials said a recount was probable
after close results on a constitutional amendment regarding
property tax relief.
   The unofficial result was 404,758 against the referendum and
404,403 in favor of it.
   The amendment would change the state constitution to allow
selective property tax relief. Its complicated, long-winded wording
made the measure especially difficult for voters to understand.
</TEXT>
