<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1835EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     04-05 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Called By Sinhalese Stops Activity Nationwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike called by Sinhalese
extremists to commemorate a rebellion 18 years ago brought activity
to a halt nationwide Wednesday, and three people were killed, the
military said.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said the government planned to
offer a cease-fire to the extremists, who belong to the Marxist
People's Liberaton Front. He said the offer probably would be made
next Wednesday.
   Bombs exploded in Colombo and other towns, and an army officer
was killed when he tried to defuse a bomb in the town of
Ambalantota, 90 miles south of Colombo, said the military
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   They said the extremists shot two people in the central district
of Kandy but did not give further details.
   Three police officers were injured in a blast in the town of
Panadura, 10 miles south of the capital. Explosions also were
reported in a Colombo suburb.
   The leftist Sinhalese militants have been waging their latest
anti-government rebellion since 1987.
   They called the strike to commemorate the April 5, 1971,
uprising against the government. As many as 20,000 people were
believed to have died before the rebellion was crushed.
   The government then outlawed the People's Liberation Front, but
it regrouped in 1986.
   Wednesday's strike call was a virtual rejection of earlier peace
proposals by President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who has offered the
Sinhalese militants unconditional amnesty, seats in parliament and
money for their weapons if they end the fighting.
   Residents in southern Sri Lanka, the Sinhalese heartland, said
the strike had crippled daily life.
   ``There is heavy patrolling by troops and police but everything
is at a standstill,'' said a trader in Galle, 70 miles south of
Colombo. ``Shops, banks, offices and businesses never opened and
even the small tea kiosks put up shutters.''
   The trader, contacted by telephone, spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Most of the shops, businesses, and government offices in Colombo
were closed and heavily armed troops and police patrolled the
streets.
   An Associated Press photographer and two other cameramen were
detained by police when they tried to take pictures of soldiers
breaking into closed shops in the town of Kalutara, 25 miles south
of Colombo. They were released after two hours in custody.
   The militants began their current campaign against the
government to thwart a peace accord aimed at ending fighting by
Tamil rebels. The Sinhalese say the accord would give too many
concessions to the minority community.
   The predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, but they are a majority in the Northern
Province. Sinhalese Buddhists make up 75 percent of the population
and control the government and the military.
   Tamil militants want an independent homeland in the island's
north and east. They began fighting in 1983, claiming the Sinhalese
have discriminated against them in jobs and education.
   Premadasa also has offered his peace proposals to the Tamil
rebels but they have not yet responded.
   More than 12,500 people in the island nation in the Indian Ocean
have been killed in the Tamil insurrection and the Sinhalese
backlash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
