<FIRST>u i BC-Poland-Excerpts     04-05 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Poland-Excerpts,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poland `Round Table' Excerpts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts of remarks by Lech
Walesa, founder of Solidarity, and Interior Minister Czeslaw
Kiszczak at the conclusion Wednesday of negotiation between the
government and opposition, as translated by The Associated Press:
   WALESA: There is no freedom without Solidarity. This is truth
with which we came to the round table.
   In the speech that I delivered at the opening of the talks, I
said that our country was ruined and it was hard for working people
to live. I said it was not dwarfs who were to blame for it, but the
system which we did not choose for ourselves.
   At the round table we met with people of this system and we
became convinced that they are aware of that fact. By starting
talks with us, by allowing our uncensored remarks on television,
they gave proof of readiness for a radical change of the system.
   Nine weeks of talks about the most important problems of our
fatherland made us realize that, in the situation where we are now,
there cannot be any talk about trading between sides, but only
about the great concern that everybody who feels responsible for
Poland carries.
   As a nation, we are either able to build by peaceful means a
Poland independent, sovereign, safe through equal alliances, or we
will drown in the chaos of demagogy and, as a result, of a civil
war in which there will be no winners.
   This way, together, we discuss the repair of the Peoples'
Republic. But I also have to say that for those I am addressing
now, and on whose behalf I am speaking, freedom goes together with
bread.
   We are changing political structures in order to have my Gdansk
shipyard, and thousands of factories, steel works and mines with
it, live a life for the good of the country, that the worker, or
farmer, member of the intelligentsia or a pensioner can live in
dignity and without poverty, which humiliates through fear.
   We want a normal life and reforms have to serve this purpose.
   KISZCZAK: We came a long distance to the round table; we covered
a difficult road. Thus one should value the agreement achieved.
   A truly common work has been accomplished. Common is the
achievement and satisfaction resulting from it. It would be bad if
speculations appeared about who has won, and how much, and who has
lost and how much.
   There is only one winner: the nation, our fatherland. Even at
the most difficult moments of the debates, we were accompanied by
the hopes of Polish society.
   A part of the divergencies remained, but there is nothing
strange in that. Differences exist and they will appear in the
future; such is the nature of society.
   However, the feeling of joint responsibility for the course of
events should lead to moderating them. The essence is to create
effective instruments to overcome discrepancies, not keeping them
secret or remaining silent about them.
   The round table was the first extremely significant step toward
this. This is why the dialogue ... can turn out to be a priceless
element in the accomplishments of our work.
</TEXT>
