<FIRST>r w AM-DC-Crime 400   04-05 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-Crime, 400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Wants More Federal Control Over District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suburban Virginia congressman, citing the
drug-related crime in the District of Columbia and the homicides
associated with it, introduced legislation Wednesday to give the
federal government control of the city's public safety system.
   Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., said Mayor Marion S. Barry Jr. and
other city officials have not found creative and effective ways of
dealing with the city's crime problem.
   ``What we are experiencing here is as much a crisis of
leadership and resources as it is a crisis of death and social
destruction,'' Parris said at a news conference. ``I think this is
the only approach to a situation that has literally resulted in a
criminal justice breakdown.''
   Parris' bill would authorize President Bush to appoint a
National Capital Public Safety Administrator, who would have
authority over the city's police and fire departments, its
emergency ambulance service, and its prison and court systems.
   The legislation comes amid a wave of crime and violence that has
thrust Washington's drug problem into the international limelight.
   Through Wednesday, 130 people had been killed in the city,
compared with 86 at the same time last year. In 1988, a record 372
persons were killed, and police blame drugs _ particularly crack
cocaine _ for more than 60 percent of those killings.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M. said during a Senate
committee hearing on the District of Columbia that he is very
pleased with the city police department's efforts to close a crack
house located near the Catholic school where the senator's son
teaches.
   ``They are doing everything they possibly can to close down the
crack house,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Domenici. ``It's
to say that Sen. Domenici is very pleased with the police reaction,
and we're confident the matter will be resolved.''
   While the Parris bill does not call for more federal money for
the city's anti-drug efforts, it requests more federal personnel be
brought into the city's drug war.
   The bill directs Attorney General Dick Thornburgh to authorize
federal marshals in Maryland and Virginia to work on city anti-drug
efforts, and requests federal officials to appoint more judges to
the D.C. Superior Court in order to handle the flow of drug cases.
   The only authorization of federal money in the bill would be for
additional jail space, but only if the prison is constructed within
the city.
</TEXT>
