<FIRST>r a AM-ObsessiveEscape     04-05 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obsessive Escape,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Determined Suspect Flees Police Five Times</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the kind of love _ or obsessive
attraction to a woman _ that brooked no interference, not even from
police.
   Authorities said Michael Bailey escaped five times over three
days, finding time during his flight to make threatening phone
calls to the woman in question.
   By Wednesday the initial complaint of telephone harassment had
ballooned to felony charges of assault on a police officer and
escape, and the 26-year-old was still on the lam.
   Bailey's ramble began about 6:45 p.m. Saturday.
   A female employee told security officers at University Medical
Center that Bailey had made at least 10 phone calls threatening her
and her automobile, said Buddy Shavers, a medical center police
investigator.
   ``Her story is he is obsessed with her,'' Shavers said. ``The
man has been pursuing her for about a year, and she says she gave
him no encouragement.''
   Security officers increased patrols around the woman's car, but
between patrols the windshield and back window were broken.
   Bailey finally was spotted behind the back door of a nearby
restaurant. He struggled with medical center officer Charles
Tillman, police said.
   ``He threw a cup of water on the officer and struck him in the
chest area and then ran,'' Shavers said.
   Jackson police were called in and officers went to Bailey's
home, Shavers said.
   ``He came out and ran,'' police spokesman Sgt. Chip Pippen said.
   Bailey was spotted about 4 a.m. Sunday and fired a shotgun at
Sgt. Freddie Weeks, Pippen said.
   Bailey fled, was spotted, fled again.
   A SWAT team was brought in; Bailey was detained.
   During the chase, he continued to call the medical center.
   Monday morning, Bailey again fled _ this time from the basement
of the Jackson Police Department while being returned to the city
jail from a hearing at which he pleaded innocent to charges of
malicious mischief and making harassing phone calls. His handcuffs
had been removed for the court appearance.
   ``I never seen anybody run that fast,'' said Constable John
Brown, who was escorting Bailey.
</TEXT>
