<FIRST>r i AM-Libya-US     04-05 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-US,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Says Reports of Reprisal Attacks Are `Lies'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's news agency JANA on Wednesday described as
``lies'' reports that Libya plans reprisal attacks on U.S. targets
timed to the April 15 anniversary of the U.S. bombing of Libya in
1986.
   It said in a dispatch monitored in London that the allegations
were made by the ``radio of the Zionist enemy'' _ a term it uses
for Israel _ and the CBS network in the United States.
   ``The Libyan people ... is well aware of the significance and
goal of such lies and allegations,'' JANA said.
   ``We are used to hearing such lies every time the American and
Western intelligence services as well as the Zionist Mossad start
to draw up a new plot aimed at carrying out a hostile attack ... to
divert the world's attention from their despicable intentions.
   ``We in the great Jamahiriyah (Libya) ... denounce terrorism in
every shape and form, from state-organized terrorism ... to the
hijacking of planes and the unjustified kidnapping and killing of
innocent people.''
   On April 15, 1986, U.S. warplanes bombed Tripoli and Benghazi in
what the Reagan administration described as a reprisal for Libya's
involvement in terrorist actions against Americans.
   The State Department said Tuesday that U.S. security personnel
worldwide were told to be on alert for anti-American terrorism
timed to the bombing anniversary but that it was not aware of any
specific threats.
   CBS, citing intelligence, said Libyan leader Col. Moammar
Gadhafi asked three groups to plan the reprisals.
</TEXT>
