<SECOND>AM-BRF--Jill Long,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Congresswoman Long Sworn In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jill Long, who scored a Democratic victory in
Dan Quayle's old congressional district last month, was sworn into
office in the House of Representives on Wednesday, drawing applause
and a standing ovation from both Republicans and Democrats.
   The newest member of Congress took the oath of office, which was
administered by House Speaker Jim Wright, at midafternoon, and was
quickly surrounded by colleagues, shaking hands and clapping her on
the back.
   Long won a special election after Rep. Dan Coats, a Republican,
was appointed to fill out the Senate term of Vice President Quayle.
   She scored her surprise victory over Republican Dan Heath,
winning 65,160 votes, or 51 percent, to 63,388, or 49 percent, for
Heath.
</TEXT>
