<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AirlineReport     04-05 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Report,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Complaints Decrease Against Airlines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only a third as many consumers are complaining
about the major airlines as a year ago, the Transportation
Department said Wednesday.
   The department, in its monthly air travel consumer report,
listed 970 complaints during March, compared to 2,651 for the same
month a year ago. The total complaints received for the first three
months of the year declined from 8,633 in 1988 to 3,207 this year,
the report said.
   The department, which keeps data on more than 20,000 flights,
gave no explanation for the decrease.
   In the same report, the 13 major carriers reported that 72.4
percent of their flights were on time during February, compared to
76.7 percent in January and 74.7 percent in February 1988.
   Worse winter weather conditions during the month accounted for
most of the increase, the department said. Delays caused by
mechanical problems are not counted.
   Mishandled baggage reports for February declined from 8.75 per
1,000 passengers a year ago to 7.36 this year. The January figure
was 7.86.
</TEXT>
