<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--DetroitNewspapers     04-05 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Detroit Newspapers,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit JOA Opponents Ask Court to Take Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the partial merger of The Detroit
News and Detroit Free Press on Wednesday asked the Supreme Court to
consider blocking the business combination.
   The advocacy groups Public Citizen and Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press in their petition said the case raises legal
issues important to the survival of newspaper competition and
constitutional issues touching on relations between the executive
and judicial branches, and so merited review by the highest court.
The opponents had made their petition public last week.
   The court was unlikely to act on the petition before the middle
of May.
   The News, owned by Gannett Co. Inc., and the Free Press, owned
by Knight-Ridder Inc., applied for an antitrust exemption in 1986
under the Newspaper Preservation Act.
   The agreement would allow the newspapers to combine business,
production and circulation operations while retaining separate news
and editorial departments, with the owners splitting profits or
losses equally the last 95 years of the century-long joint
operating agreement.
</TEXT>
