<FIRST>r a AM-NYCLiberals     04-05 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Liberals,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Liberals To Back Republican In NYC's Jumbled Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Liberal Party, which traditionally endorses
Democrats for New York state and city offices, is reportedly
backing Republican Rudolph Giuliani for mayor.
   Giuliani, the former U.S. attorney in Manhattan, needs the
Liberal endorsement if he is to run a successful campaign in a city
where Democrats outnumber Republicans about 5-to-1.
   Giuliani has not yet announced whether he will run, but is
generally expected to do so.
   City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin, who had also sought the
Liberal nod in his quest to succeed Mayor Edward I. Koch, said
Tuesday that Liberal Party Vice Chairman Ray Harding had told him
of the party's planned endorsement of Giuliani.
   Harding and Russ Schriefer, Giuliani's campaign manager,
declined to confirm Goldin's information. Harding said the party
would announce its choice for mayor at a future date after a
meeting of its policy committee.
   Koch, a Democrat, has unofficially said he is seeking a fourth
term. The Liberal Party has never endorsed Koch in his previous
three runs for mayor.
   The last Republican to get the Liberal nod for mayor was John V.
Lindsay, who won reelection in 1969 on the Liberal Party line after
he lost the Republican primary.
   By endorsing Giuliani, the Liberal Party risks incurring the ire
of Gov. Mario Cuomo, who could get the small party knocked off the
ballot. A political party must receive 50,000 votes in a
gubernatorial election to guarantee a permanent slot on the ballot
for the next four years.
   If Cuomo, a Democrat, runs for a third term as governor and
decides he does not want to belong to a club that would endorse a
Republican, he could reject the Liberal endorsement.
   However, in response to Giuliani's reported endorsement, Cuomo's
spokesman Gary Fryer said: ``The governor is content to let the
people of New York City decide who the mayor should be.''
</TEXT>
