<FIRST>r p AM-AlabamaCongressional     04-05 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alabama Congressional,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Governor Denies Party Chances Dimmed By Congressional Loss</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Democrats Cheer, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Gov. Guy Hunt denied on
Wednesday that a landslide loss by a GOP candidate for a vacant
Alabama congressional seat is a bad omen for Republicans seeking
gains in the South in 1990.
   But Alabama Democrats said the victory of Secretary of State
Glen Browder in the 3rd Congressional District race amounts to a
revival for state Democrats.
   ``The news of the death of the Democratic Party was premature in
Alabama,'' said U.S. Rep. Ronnie Flippo, a Democrat from Florence,
at a news conference in Washington.
   ``It shows the Republicans aren't taking over Alabama,'' said
U.S. Sen. Richard Shelby, D-Ala., who joined Flippo at the news
conference.
   Browder, 46, a former political science professor at
Jacksonville State University, defeated Republican John Rice, 37, a
state senator from Opelika, by nearly a 2-1 margin.
   Complete, unofficial returns from Tuesday's election showed
Browder with 47,229 votes, or 65 percent, to Rice's 25,008, or 35
percent. Browder won all 13 counties, including Rice's home county
of Lee and hometown of Opelika.
   Just last November, President Bush got 60 percent of the vote in
the east Alabama district, carrying 11 of the 13 counties.
   The seat became vacant with the death in December of Rep. Bill
Nichols, a Democrat who held the district for 22 years. Without an
incumbent in the seat, which covers a rural and mostly white
conservative district, national Republican strategists looked for a
possible off-year gain to set the stage for a raid on Dixie in 1990.
   Browder, with more money and backing from organized labor,
battered Rice in television ads depicting the Republican a ``hand
grenade'' who favored cutting federal aid to the elderly in half.
Rice attempted to brand Browder as a tax-and-spend liberal out of
tune with the district.
   Rice, who called Browder ``a wimp'' and ``a liar'' during the
campaign, blamed the loss on a lack of money to counter the
television assault. Browder played down the campaign name-calling
after his victory, saying his goal is to ``bring people together''
to work for the district.
   Hunt, who campaigned for Rice, said each candidate is viewed
individually by voters and the loss Tuesday does not dim Republican
chances to make major gains in Alabama and elsewhere in 1990.
   Hunt, who in 1986 became the first Republican elected governor
of Alabama this century, also said he feels he remains popular in
the east Alabama district.
   Hunt also gained the advantage of being able to name a
Republican to succeed Browder as secretary of state. He said
Wednesday he has just begun to consider the matter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
