<DOCNO> AP890405-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brite     04-05 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brite,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philadelphia Zoo will get a new occupant
April 29, and zoo visitors will vote on whether the creature is a
beauty or a beast.
   Big Pig, an African warthog, will appear through Labor Day.
During his stay visitors can fill out ballots to help decide
whether Big Pig is cute-ugly or just plain ugly.
   Zoo spokeswoman Arlene Kut said the zoo's Warthog Election
Central will tabulate votes, and a telephone line has been set up
to dispense the latest warthog news.
   Warthogs are a rarity in the United States; they were banned
because of quarantine restrictions until recently. Big Pig was born
at the Moscow Zoo in 1986 and was kept at the Los Angeles Zoo
before his trip to Philadelphia, Ms. Kut said. The Cincinnati and
Los Angeles Zoos also have warthogs.
   Big Pig weighs about 250 pounds, somewhat larger than average,
and is fed food pellets, carrots, apples, and grapes. He is also
fond of alfalfa. In the wild, warthogs eat short grasses, bark,
roots, and occasionally fruit, Ms. Kut said.
   Warthogs, members of the pig family, are native to sub-Saharan
Africa and inhabit savannah woodlands and grasslands. Although they
would rather run than fight, they do use their large upper tusks to
defend themselves against predators and can be dangerous when
cornered.
   Warthogs use their sense of smell to identify one another since
their eyesight is poor. Their hearing is acute. Their ``warts'' are
large bumps of skin that are prominent in males. These bumps may be
used to help deflect blows inflicted by the tusks of other male
warthogs during territorial battles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
