<FIRST>r i AM-France-Hezbollah     04-05 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Hezbollah,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Convicted Terrorist Claims To Be Hezbollah's European Spokesman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jailed terrorist claims he is the European
spokesman for Hezbollah, the umbrella group for factions holding
Western hostages in Lebanon, a news agency reported Wednesday.
   Anis Naccache issued a statement from his cell ``calling on all
Moslems in Europe to preserve their unity faced with plots aimed at
Islam and Moslems,'' Agence France-Presse reported.
   Naccache is serving a life sentence for the unsuccessful attempt
to assassinate former Iranian Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar in
1980. He signed the statement: ``Anis Naccache. Spokesman of the
Hezbollah in Europe.''
   His lawyer, Jacques Verger, confirmed that Naccache issued the
statement, AFP reported.
   Hezbollah, meaning Party of God, is made up of Iranian-backed
Lebanese Shiite Moslem extremists. It is believed to be the
umbrella group for various factions holding 15 foreigners,
including nine Americans, in Lebanon.
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Naccache called on fellow Moslems to support Iranian Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's call for the death of Salman Rushdie, author of
``The Satanic Verses.''
   Many Moslems believe the book blasphemes Islam because its
characters include prostitutes who take the names of the prophet
Mohammed's wives. The novel also suggests that Mohammed wrote the
holy Koran rather than receiving it from Allah.
   Rushdie has been in hiding in Britain since Khomeini called for
his death on Feb. 14.
</TEXT>
