<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1903EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Scene 1stLd-Writethru   04-05 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0752,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Who Is That Gate Crasher? It's Walesa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `But some...' with five grafs to UPDATE with
details of reception and Walesa eating dinner. Pickup 15th pvs, ``The fight...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Let's move,'' shouted historian Adam
Michnik, and a band of top Solidarity activists trooped out of the
hotel bar where they met Wednesday before heading to a government
palace to conclude an agreement to legalize the banned union
movement.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa led the animated group down a busy
street to the main palace gate, where police stopped them and told
them to join spectators standing across the street.
   Walesa simply laughed and strode right into the palace.
   Inside, the Solidarity representatives quickly sank into
burgundy-cushioned chairs around the large round table and waited
for the government delegation to appear.
   The government and Solidarity sides eyed each other warily until
the grim delegates of the official trade union OPZZ marched through
a maze of camera cables. They had delayed the opening by 10 minutes.
   The Solidarity side listened politely as Interior Minister Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak read his speech. There was no applause when he
finished.
   But Michnik and others smiled broadly when Walesa opened his
speech with the familiar saying: ``There is no freedom without
Solidarity.''
   Security was lax. A group of specially invited Solidarity
supporters chatted in the wings or pressed up against the backs of
security guards to get a glimpse of the proceedings.
   Several Western reporters were allowed to quietly watch some of
the proceedings from corner seats.
   Even before they returned to the ornate halls at the Council of
Ministers palace in central Warsaw where they had negotiated with
authorities for the past nine weeks, the Solidarity delegation
sensed victory.
   ``We have a chance. We will have to see if we can use it,'' said
Jacek Kuron, a leading political theorist who has fought communist
authorities for more than a quarter of a century.
   ``It's good. It's really good. What else can I say?'' said
Zbigniew Bujak, who managed to escape capture during the December
1981 martial-law crackdown and led underground Solidarity until his
arrest in 1986.
   Each of the delegates to the talks autographed a small cardboard
sign lettered with the familiar red-and-white Solidarity logo in
the bar of the Hotel Europejski, which had served as the union
press office during the talks.
   While some members of the Solidarity delegation drank wine and
ate hors d'oeuvres with authorities at a reception at a government
palace, Walesa quietly ordered dinner in the nearly empty dining
room of the nearby Europejski Hotel.
   ``I am exhausted and I don't like eating standing,'' he said as
he and Krzysztof Pusz, his longtime aide, dined on a platter of
cold cuts, sliced bread and tea with lemon.
   When asked why such a modest dinner on such an important night,
Walesa deadpanned: ``The country is in crisis.''
   He declined to make any substantive comment on the outcome of
the talks, but said he would be ready in the morning for a
scheduled news conference.
   Some Solidarity leaders seemed acutely aware that much remains
to be done before the political and economic reforms on which the
union has staked its reputation bear fruit.
   ``The fight has just begun,'' said Alojzy Pietrzyk, a Solidarity
leader from southern city of Jastrzebie, where a wave of strikes by
angry coal miners last August prompted authorities to propose the
round-table talks.
   ``I thought it would be a bigger success, even though we got
more than we hoped for,'' said Grzegorz Stawski, another Jastrzebie
miner. ``The battle has just begun.''
   ``But I sure would like my wife to have seen this,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
