<FIRST>u w AM-BountyHunters     04-05 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bounty Hunters,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Bounty Payments for Informants on Contract Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Wednesday to authorize bounty
payments of up to $250,000 for informants who help prosecutors root
out multimillion dollar contracting fraud against the federal
government.
   The bill went to the House on a 82-16 vote, as senators rejected
an argument that the rewards would encourage Americans to spy on
each other and avoid their duty to report crimes solely out of
patriotism, without getting paid.
   The attorney general would have sole discretion to grant the
rewards from Justice Department funds, but he could seek
court-ordered reimbursement later from criminal fines levied
against convicted violators.
   Federal employees who furnish information in the performance of
official duties could not receive a reward, nor could those who
themselves violated the 1988 Major Fraud Act, which imposed stiff
penalties for contract fraud.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, chief sponsor of the bill,
said $250,000 ``is not a large amount of money when you're talking
about multimillion dollar fraud.''
   ``We are dealing with a serious problem and have to do
everything we can ... before tax dollars are lost and people are
injured. With better information, we can nip contract fraud in the
bud,'' he said.
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., in emotional arguments, said the bill
would encourage the type of neighbor-against-neighbor spying that
occurred in Nazi Germany and in communist countries. But his
amendment to wipe out the proposed rewards was tabled by a vote of
55-43.
   ``I find the provision so repugnant, so repulsive, so demeaning
that we're giving up on America'' by paying people to do their
civic duty, Bumpers argued before the vote.
   ``Are we caving in and saying, `There aren't enough patriots in
this country to do their job so we have to pay them ...?''' he
asked. ``How much do we have to bribe'' informants?
   To be eligible for the money, the informant must give his
information to his employer before contacting authorities, unless
there is a valid reason not to do so. The whistleblower also could
not collect if the information was previously disclosed, unless the
informant was the original source of the information.
</TEXT>
