<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     04-05 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Denounce US Military Presence In Honduras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government claimed Wednesday the
United States is increasing its military presence in Honduras
despite what Nicaragua described as international support for
demilitarizing Central America.
   The accusation was made in a communique published on the front
page of Barricada, the official newspaper of the ruling Sandinista
party.
   Nicaraguan Indian leaders in neighboring Honduras said thousands
of Indian exiles would to return home to vote in Nicaragua's 1990
presidential election.
   Also on Barricada's front page was a dispatch from Havana
quoting Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev as reaffirming
solidarity with Nicaragua.
   It said Gorbachev, who ended a four-day visit Cuba on Wednesday,
soon might visit Nicaragua, which depends on the Soviet bloc for
economic and military aid.
   In the communique, the Sandinistas said it is ``worrisome and
abusive of international law that the United States government
insists on disarming Nicaragua'' and denying it ``necessary means
for its defense, while that same government continues
systematically placing its troops'' in the region.
   The Bush administration has said regional peace efforts would be
advanced it the Soviets cut their military ties with Nicaragua.
   Gorbachev said Tuesday the superpowers should renounce military
intervention in Latin America, but promised military aid to
Nicaragua as long as the United States arms other Central American
nations.
   President Daniel Ortega's government based its accusation about
U.S. military activity on proposed amendments to an agreement on
joint U.S.-Honduran military maneuvers.
   Honduran legislators are considering amendments that would
extend tax and customs privileges to U.S. military personnel on
maneuvers.
   The Sandinista communique described the amendments as a protocol
with ``grave'' implications for peace in Central America and a
``lamentable step ... irreconcilable with the efforts now
developing to reach a durable and just peace in the region.''
   Honduras also has served as a refuge, training ground and
staging base for Nicaraguan rebels supported by the United States.
U.S. and Honduran forces have conducted joint maneuvers for years.
   In Tegucigalpa, capital of Honduras, a spokesman for Indian
leaders Steadman Fagoth Muller and Brooklyn Rivera, told The
Associated Press up to 20,000 refugees might return to Nicaragua
before the presidential election scheduled for Feb. 25, 1990.
   Kendy Medina said Fagoth Muller and Rivera, former rebel
leaders, would join Nicaragua's political opposition.
   ``We plan to leave Honduras over the next nine months to take
advantage of the political opening in Nicaragua,'' Medina said.
``We are convinced we must fight in our own country and with our
own civilized arms.''
   Tens of thousands of Miskito, Rama and Sumo Indians began
leaving their tribal homelands along the Caribbean coast in 1981
after the Sandinistas tried to assert authority over the remote
area and said it would move the Indians to relocation camps.
</TEXT>
