<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Scene     04-05 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Scene,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tugs, Tide Yank Tanker From Reef</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE GLACIER QUEEN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six tugboats took up the
slack on tow lines Wednesday and slowly but surely hauled the
oil-spilling tanker Exxon Valdez from a reef that had held it solid
for 12 days.
   The tanker that had spewed more than 10 million gallons of crude
oil into Prince William Sound then had to evade thousands of
icebergs, some as big as houses, that dotted the sea.
   ``We're not going to move fast,'' said Gary Gorski, Exxon's
salvage coordinator. ``We're trying to work our way around these
little dorky bits out here.''
   Icebergs calving from the nearby Columbia Glacier often clog the
tanker lanes in spring and summer.
   The tanker was towed at 3 mph for a 10-hour trip to an already
oil-fouled bay on secluded Naked Island, where temporary repairs
will be made.
   Two skimmers and boats pulling two containment booms trailed the
tanker, mopping up a sheen of oil.
   ``We're just thrilled it appears to have been pulled off so
smoothly,'' said Exxon Shipping Co. spokesman Tom Cirigliano.
   The 987-foot tanker, the second-newest and one of the two
largest vessels in Exxon's 19-tanker fleet, ran aground March 24 on
Bligh Reef, a well-charted and marked navigational hazard 25 miles
south of Valdez, the port at the southern end of the trans Alaska
pipeline.
   The reef tore holes in eight of the tanker's 13 oil tanks and
two of its four ballast tanks.
   For 12 days while the ship was hard aground, water rose and fell
inside the ruptured tanks with the fluctuating tides.
   Tanker Capt. Bill Wallace gave the order Wednesday morning to
seal off vents in those tanks and an inert gas was pumped in under
pressure to force out some of the water. Inert gas, usually
nitrogen, is used to produce an oxygen-free environment and ensure
that petroleum fumes in the tanks can't ignite.
</TEXT>
