<FIRST>u a AM-ScarfoTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0736 04-05 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scarfo Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Finds Scarfo Guilty In Mobster Killing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT mobster to Mafia member. Pick up 4th
graf, `Scarfo, 60 ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mob boss Nicodemo ``Little Nicky'' Scarfo
and seven associates were convicted Wednesday on first-degree
murder charges in the 1985 slaying of another gangster and could
face the electric chair.
   Jurors deliberated about three hours before returning the
verdict on all counts in the slaying of Frank ``Frankie Flowers''
D'Alfonso in July 1985.
   The jury will begin consideration Thursday on whether the
defendants should face death in the electric chair. No other Mafia
member in the nation, organized crime investigators say, has ever
been sentenced to death.
   Scarfo, 60, is considered head of organized crime in the
Philadelphia-South Jersey area even though he's been in jail for
nearly two years serving a 14-year sentence in a $1 million
extortion. He also faces over 40 years more for a federal
racketeering conviction that included nine murders.
   The key to the prosecution case was the testimony of two
gangster informants who said Scarfo gave the order to kill
D'Alfonso late in the winter of 1985. D'Alfonso was shot to death
nearly six months later on a South Philadelphia street near his
home.
   Defense lawyers said the witnesses, Thomas DelGiorno and Eugene
Milano, were liars who had made deals to save their own lives. Both
had admitted participating in the D'Alfonso conspiracy.
   Assistant District Attorney Charles Grant called the defendants
``brigands of death'' and ``a pack of wolves'' and praised the
informants' courage.
   Milano, who had been one of the defendants in the case, decided
to plead guilty to third-degree murder, thus avoiding the
possibility of execution, and agreed to testify against the others,
including his younger brother, Nicholas, or ``Nicky Whip.''
   The defense, which put on no witnesses, argued prosecutors
failed to prove their case beyond a reasonable doubt.
   Scarfo's lawyer, Robert Simone, said in a plea for acquittal
that there were no fingerprints on the guns police found after the
shooting, no witnesses who could identify any of the defendants as
the killers.
   He blasted DelGiorno as a witness ``who violated almost every
commandment that Moses brought down from the mountain'' and Milano
for testifying against his own brother.
   ``This case is full of lies and imagination,'' Simone said.
   Grant, however, said the only way to convict mob members was to
use informants, and denounced the defense allegations that
DelGiorno and Milano were ``vicious vermin, ravenous wolves.''
   ``We have the pack of wolves and the leader of the pack in this
room for the cowardly kill of D'Alfonso,'' Grant said.
   Besides Scarfo and the younger Milano, the others convicted were
Joseph Ligambi, 48, and Philip Narducci, 26, identified as the
shooters; Frances ``Faffy'' Iannarella, 32, accused of supplying
the two murder guns; Salvatore ``Chucki'' Merlino, 47, and his
brother, Lawrence ``Yogi'' Merlino, 32, and Frank ``Windows''
Narducci Jr., 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
