<DOCNO> AP890405-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Mecham     04-05 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mecham,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeached Arizona Governor Says He'll Run Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mainstream Republicans were on the defensive
Wednesday after former Gov. Evan Mecham's announcement that he will
try for a second term as governor despite being impeached and
ousted part way through his first one.
   State Senate President Robert Usdane, meanwhile, rejected
Mecham's call for a new impeachment trial, clearing the way for
Mecham to take his case to court.
   One Republican, state Rep. Jim Hartdegen, wore a black armband
to the House floor Wednesday in mourning for the Republican Party.
   ``The death was last night,'' Hartdegen said. ``The burial will
be in November 1990.''
   Mecham told a cheering rally Tuesday night that he would win the
GOP primary in 1990 and would beat his replacement, Democratic Gov.
Rose Mofford, in the general election.
   ``I committed no impeachable offense,'' said Mecham, a former
auto dealer elected in 1986 on his fifth try for governor.
   ``We'll get about 60 percent in the general,'' he predicted.
   Mrs. Mofford, who automatically replaced Mecham because she had
been elected as secretary of state in 1986, said she wasn't
surprised at Mecham's announcement.
   ``I will match my record with his any time,'' she said. ``I will
not stand by and let him or anyone else turn the clock back
socially, culturally, economically or any other way.''
   Editorial writers and prominent Republicans had urged Mecham not
to run.
   ``There'll be a terrible primary,'' said former Republican House
Speaker Joe Lane, one of the pro-impeachment lawmakers ousted by
Mecham supporters in last fall's elections. ``Democrats will be
organized and we'll have a bloody primary, and I just hate to see
that.''
   Former U.S. Sen. Barry Goldwater predicted Mecham's defeat, and
The Arizona Republic, which has feuded with Mecham for years, said
in an editorial Wednesday that Mecham's strength among GOP party
workers would not translate into voter support.
   ``Taking over the Arizona Republican Party is one thing,'' the
newspaper said in reference to right-wing resolutions that Mecham
backers forced through at last January's state meeting. ``Winning
an election for governor after having been impeached is something
else again.''
   The Mesa Tribune, in an editorial titled ``He's Back,'' said the
GOP, ``already staggering, stumbling, straining for balance, has
been knocked on its tail'' and ``can be expected to tear itself
apart in the months to come.''
   Mecham insisted that there would be no bloodbath.
   ``I want to send word out to everyone in Arizona that I think we
can have a kinder and gentler Arizona,'' he told a crowd of more
than 400 at a hotel ballroom. ``I think the 19 months between now
and the general election of 1990 can be a time of spirited debate
on the issues but not name-calling and not accusations without
basis.''
   Mecham said he held no bitterness toward his critics, but added:
``I do believe that I've been the object of more venemous
name-calling than anyone in our state and possibly in America.''
   The maverick conservative, now 64, was impeached by the
Republican-controlled House on Feb. 5, 1988 and charged with
obstructing justice, misusing state money and concealing a campaign
loan.
   The Republican-controlled Senate convicted him on the
obstruction and money charges. It left the third allegation to a
Maricopa County Superior Court jury for consideration as a criminal
case, and jurors there acquitted Mecham.
   Mecham won election in 1986 with about 40 percent of the vote in
a three-way race.
   Controversial appointments, actions and statements that offended
blacks, Jews, Orientals and others ate away at his popularity
despite a no-tax stand that won him support from many voters.
</TEXT>
