<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 4thLd-Writethru a0804 04-05 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0804,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least 22 Killed in Beirut Shelling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 2nd, `The Arab...' to UPDATE with radio reporting
shells falling. Pick up 3rd pvs, `Police gave...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Life, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shells blasted street markets and a
hospital Wednesday, killing at least 22 people in another of the
fierce Christian-Moslem artillery duels that have kept residents in
bomb shelters for a month.
   The Arab League appealed for a cease-fire and the shooting
stopped at the appointed hour of midnight, at least temporarily,
although the Christian military commander had not agreed to the
truce.
   However, a Christian radio reported six shells falling in
different locations in the Christian area in the first hour after
midnight, and a pro-Syrian Moslem radio reported one shell hit the
Moslem area.
   Police gave the death toll and said 70 people were wounded. It
was the fifth day Moslem and Christian residential areas have been
bombarded without letup.
   At least 159 people have been killed and 576 wounded since the
battle began March 8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian army
units and an alliance of Druse militiamen and Syrian troops.
   Nearly all the casualties have been civilians. It is the worst
fighting since 1985 in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah, Kuwait's foreign minister and head of
an Arab League mediation team, called for the truce after meeting
in Damascus, Syria, with Lebanese Moslem leaders.
   ``We appeal to all the warring parties to observe a cease-fire
as of midnight,'' he said. Sabah urged belligerents to end attacks
on ports and airports, and to permit opening of crossing points
between Moslem west Beirut and the Christian eastern sector.
   Acting Premier Salim Hoss endorsed the cease-fire.
   ``I urge all sides to comply with the proposed truce out of
mercy for the battered population,'' said Hoss, who heads the
Moslem cabinet in what has been a dual government since a political
crisis arose in September.
   Jibran Kourieh, spokesman for Hafez Assad, did not say whether
the Syrian president endorsed the cease-fire but said he supported
the committee's work.
   ``President Assad stressed the necessity that all cooperate to
save Lebanon from the difficult circumstances it is going through
so (it) becomes united ... and cooperates with the Arab nation,''
Kourieh said.
   Aoun, who leads the Christian cabinet in addition to commanding
the 20,000 Christian army troopers, rejected any truce that does
not name the Syrian army as his main adversary.
   ``There is only one power on the other side that can cease or
unleash fire,'' he said in an interview broadcast on Christian
stations in Beirut. ``It is the Syrian army, and any Lebanese cover
for the Syrian army is unacceptable.''
   If Syria accepts a cease-fire, he said, ``Then I will accept.''
   He said he would negotiate whatever arrangements Syria needs to
``ensure its military and political security, but the Syrian army
must go. We shall settle for nothing less.''
   Assad has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab League and has become the country's main
power broker. Aoun calls the Syrians an occupation army and has
vowed to drive them out.
   In an interview published earlier, the London-based newspaper
Mideast Mirror quoted Aoun as saying he was willing to lift a
blockade of illegal militia-run ports if the ports were not used
for narcotics or arms traffic.
   The fighting began March 8, two days after Aoun's forces closed
the ports, which deprive the government of an estimated $100
million of duties and other revenue.
   Syrian troops in turn blockaded the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave north and east of Beirut, where 1 million Christians live,
with the aid of Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, who leads Lebanon's 22,000
Moslem soldiers. Khatib's men are poorly equipped and have stayed
out of the fighting.
   A police spokesman said most of the casualties Wednesday were in
Moslem west Beirut, where shells fired by Aoun's gunners hit three
vegetable markets and the Barbir hospital, one of the Moslem
sector's four major medical centers.
   He said the Murr tower, an unfinished 40-story skyscraper Syrian
troops use as a base for snipers and artillery spotters, took
several direct hits from 155mm howitzers.
   Syrian soldiers were seen evacuating casualties from the tower,
firing automatic rifles into the air to clear the way for emergency
vehicles. There was no word on casualties from headquarters of the
12,000 Syrian soldiers stationed in Beirut.
   Foreign Minister Roland Dumas of France, the ruling power in
Lebanon until independence in 1943, called Lebanon ``a community in
peril'' and said his government was sending two ships loaded with
food and medical supplies.
   Jean-Francois Deniau, vice president of the French National
Assembly's foreign affairs committee, arrived in Beirut for
meetings with leaders of both sides.
   More than 700 Lebanese who fled the fighting got off the ferry
Baroness on Wednesday in Larnaca, Cyprus. Capt. George Papadimatos
said the ferry waits outside the Lebanese Christian port of Jounieh
all day, then slips in without lights after dark to load passengers.
</TEXT>
