<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0818,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Step Up Attacks After Threat</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd pvs, `Eight rebels...' to UPDATE with
attack on artillery brigade. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The rebels...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked
army and civilian targets in central and eastern El Salvador on
Wednesday and sabotaged power lines, leaving much of the capital
without power.
   Eight rebels were killed and seven wounded in two days of
combat, the army said.
   In the afternoon, the rebels also made an unsuccessful attack on
the Artillery Brigade in San Juan Opico, 16 miles northeast of the
capital, an army official said.
   The rebels' Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front threatened
last week to step up attacks and present President-elect Alfredo
Cristiani with ``an ungovernable country'' when he takes office on
June 1.
   Guerrillas destroyed seven power pylons and fired rifles at army
positions in Quezaltepeque, about 16 miles northwest of San
Salvador, the armed forces press office said. No casualties were
reported.
   It said that in Nueva Guadalupe, 74 miles east of San Salvador,
rebels early Wednesday destroyed a telecommunications office, the
town's judicial chambers and several vehicles owned by a
construction company, and slightly damaged the local civil defense
headquarters.
   Guerrillas dynamited a textile mill in Soyapango, four miles
east of San Salvador, in an attack National Police blamed on urban
commandos of the Farabundo Marti.
   Urban guerrillas exploded dynamite charges late Tuesday at 10
local bank offices and destroyed five electrical pylons in the
capital, creating panic in some neighborhoods and leaving most of
the city in darkness. One explosion slightly injured a child,
officials said.
   Troops exchanged gunfire with guerrillas in Jucuaran, 80 miles
east of San Salvador, killing one rebel and wounding two, the press
office said. It said no army casualties resulted.
   The armed forces said soldiers of the Belloso counterinsurgency
battalion killed seven rebels and wounded five Tuesday in an attack
on a guerrilla base camp in Suchitoto, 27 miles north of the
capital. Troops discovered mines, explosive charges and medicines
inside the camp, it said.
   Troops also dismantled two guerrilla camps in northern
Chalantenango province, a rebel stronghold.
   Ana Guadalupe Martinez, a member of the Farabundo Marti's
political directorate, warned last week of increased guerrilla
attacks before Cristiani takes office.
   Cristiani, of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, won
the March 19 presidential elections.
   The Farabundo Marti has waged a 9-year-old civil war against the
U.S.-supported government. More than 70,000 Salvadorans, most of
them civilians, have been killed.
</TEXT>
