<FIRST>u a AM-Tanker-Captain     04-05 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker-Captain,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bail Set At $500,000 For Fired Captain of Exxon Valdez</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge set bail on Wednesday at 20 times
the amount that prosecutors sought for the fired captain of the
Exxon Valdez, the ship that caused the nation's worst oil spill.
   A pale, shaken and sweating Joseph Hazelwood, whose lawyer had
sought $5,000 cash bail, was led from the courtroom in handcuffs
after Judge Kenneth Rohl set bail at $1 million bond or $500,000
cash.
   ``These misdemeanors are of such a magnitude that has never been
equaled, at least in this country,'' Rohl said. ``He's got to think
about that. We have a man-made destruction that has not been
equaled, probably, since Hiroshima.''
   The U.S. atom bombing of Hiroshima in 1945 killed or injured
nearly 130,000 people and leveled 90 percent of the Japanese city.
   A judge in Alaska had set bail for Hazelwood at $50,000.
   The size of bail shocked both prosecutors and defense attorneys.
   ``We can't take out our wrath on one individual,'' said Suffolk
County District Attorney Patrick Henry. ``It's oversimplification
to settle on one individual.''
   Michael Chalos, an attorney for Hazelwood, said: ``It was tough
for our client to hear, especially after the district attorney had
recommended $25,000 bail. It was very harsh, we thought.''
   Hazelwood was arraigned in Suffolk County court on a fugitive
warrant and granted 30 days to prepare for a hearing on his
extradition to Alaska.
   Authorities there have charged him with three misdemeanors:
operating a ship while intoxicated, reckless endangerment, and
negligent discharge of oil. He faces 2\ years in prison.
   A $1 million bond can be secured with as little as 10 percent
collateral in cash, officials said.
   Rohl said that even though Hazelwood faces only misdemeanors,
``We are not talking about someone breaking someone's windshield.
We are talking about a global catastrophe.''
   Hazelwood allegedly admitted drinking before the tanker ran
aground and caused the 10.1 million-gallon oil spill. As such, he
is ``the architect of an American tragedy,'' prosecutor Philip
Castellano Jr. told the judge. He recommended bail be set at
$25,000.
   Another attorney for Hazelwood, Thomas Russo, had sought $5,000
bail on the grounds his client was not a fugitive and not a
criminal.
   It was unclear how quickly the captain might make bail.
   ``A million dollars is a lot of money,'' Chalos said.
   The Exxon Valdez hit a reef in Prince William Sound on March 24,
and Hazelwood apparently left Anchorage the next night on a flight
for New York. The 42-year-old seaman is a resident of the Long
Island community of Huntington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
