<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv07   04-05 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 07,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs April 7, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Undercover Religion Tamer Now But Still An Alternative</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slipping bits of religion into countries that
oppose it used to be high adventure but it has mellowed, says a
practitioner. Still, he adds, many barriers remain.
   The Rev. Robert K. Hawley, director of ``Open Doors, USA,'' says
that while some of the suspense and drama of its operations have
waned, the organization continues tackling the stiffest restraints
on faith.
   ``We go to the most restricted of restricted countries,''
seeking to bolster religious life, he said in an interview. ``We do
it officially if we can. If we can't, we do it unofficially.
   ``We always obey the government unless it's contrary to the
Gospel.''
   He heads the U.S. branch of an interdenominational,
international organization with an $11 million annual budget, a
staff of 250, headquarters in the Netherlands and operations in 30
countries.
   The U.S. branch, with offices in Santa Ana, Calif., has a staff
of 36, along with hundreds of volunteers spending time in aided
areas. Hawley, 40, is a Texas-born Baptist clergymen who previously
led California congregations.
   The organization was founded in 1955 by a Dutch Reformed
minister, Brother Andrews, its president, with the objective of
supplying Bibles and other religious materials in areas of
religious oppression.
   His widely sold book, ``God's Smuggler,'' put a picturesque
stamp on the organization _ the undercover activities, secret
missions and meetings, clandestine rendezvous _ and some of that
aura lingers, though tamer now.
   ``This kind of ministry has matured,'' he said. ``The world
generally has recognized religious restrictions as a human rights
issue.''
   However, code names still are given to various undertakings,
such as ``Project Philip,'' by which Western volunteers now are
providing theological training in homes in Soviet-bloc countries to
equip ministers.
   Hawley said 1,800 students now are involved, and 250 have become
pastors.
   He said circumventing regulations still is necessary in some
cases, even in the thawing communism of China. Although Bibles now
printed there go to registered church members, he said ``house''
Christians are left out.
   ``To buy a Bible, you usually have to show you are a member of a
registered church,'' he said. In this category are about nine
million Protestants and Catholics, but an estimated 50 million
others worship in homes.
   In trying to hand-carry Bibles to the ``house'' Christians last
year, he said a batch of 200 in his bags were confiscated by
customs agents, who cited a law forbidding entry of outside
religious material.
   ``When they say they're open now, it's only what they define as
open,'' he said. ``We have about 500 couriers going into China
every year. Many get caught. But many don't. We call it a miracle
of God.''
   He said Chinese contacts are alerted in advance, with meeting
places arranged to begin the distribution process. Rejecting
criticism by some church officials that such smuggling worsens
conditions for believers, he said:
   ``They encourage it, they encourage us,'' he said. ``We as a
ministry never take materials into a country unless specifically
requested by Christians there. Our job is not to jeopardize but
help them.''
   Nevertheless, he said, the situation has eased in most communist
areas, and much work that once was done covertly now is carried on
in the open, with official approval.
   He has just returned from a two-week trip to the Soviet Union,
and said he is ``cautiously optimistic'' about its expanding
religious vitality. ``There is more freedom,'' he said.
   His organization now has a government-approved project under way
to ship a million New Testaments, with Psalms, to Russian Orthodox
Christians this year, the first batch of 100,000 delivered while he
was there.
   He said various groups, including the United Bible Societies,
have shipped more than a million Bibles to the Soviet in the last
two years with official permission.
   More than 400 new churches opened there last year and l,000 more
are expected to be opened this year, bringing the total to more
than 15,000, he said. He said prospects are that two Russian
Orthodox prelates will be made members of the Supreme Soviet,
limited in the past to the Communist Party.
   He said that just as Stalin in 1942 eased anti-religious
measures in order to mobilize Christian support for the war with
Nazism, the present communist regime realizes church people are
essential to reviving the Soviet economy.
   ``The church is the Soviet's largest labor union for
revitalizing the economy,'' Hawley said, adding that church
membership there exceeds 70 million.
   He said that for the first time, ``the church has been
recognized by the government as a valuable and viable insitution
for the moral training and character of society.''
   However, he added, ``until there are Bibles in Soviet schools,
bookstores and the church, the society is not free.'' When it was
noted that U.S. public schools shun Bible courses because of
church-state separation, he said, ``That doesn't make it right.''
   End Adv Fri PMs April 7
</TEXT>
