<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionRoundup Adv07   04-05 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Roundup, Adv 07,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, April 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mennonites are seeking to develop 500 new
religious congregations by 1995. Officials say it is their first
effort to reach beyond their Dutch origins to people who are
``unchurched.''
   ``Our goal is to build a new identity as Mennonites, as being
more open, receptive, warm,'' said the Rev. Regan W. Savage.
   Mennonites are the descendants of the German-speaking religious
rebels who were among the first Pennsylvania settlers.
   ``Some children of Mennonite families have been going out the
back door while new people have been coming in the front door,''
said Luke Beidler, a Mennonite official. He says the church wants
``not only to invite new people in, but to close the back door.''
   The program, called Vision 95, was launched in 1985. According
to the Mennonite Board of Missions, based in Elkhart, Ind., 46 new
congregations have been added since 1985. There are now 1,296
congregations, with membership totalling about 100,000.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRIBOURG, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Protestant community of women has
converted to Roman Catholicism. Nine nuns and a novice of the
Lutheran Community of the Daughters of Mary of Vadstena have joined
a Benedictine abbey.
   Sweden is 95 percent Lutheran. Three other Lutheran communities
have switched to Roman Catholicism in recent years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rabbis of Conservative Judaism say they will
train their own specialists in religious divorce, circumcision and
conversions because the Orthodox wing won't cooperate in such
matters.
   Rabbi Albert Lewis of Cherry Hill., N.J., president of the
Rabbinical Assembly, told its annual assembly the moves were
prompted by a ``militant separatist Orthodoxy'' that denies
equality to other Jews in such life-cycle events.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Register says the number of
arrests for anti-nuclear civil disobedience increased by nearly 60
percent in 1987 to a total of 5,300, with about 120 persons having
served, or serving, prison sentences. Many of the demonstrators
have claimed religious motivations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three leaders of China's ``post-denominational''
Protestant church, including two bishops, are on a six-week visit
to the United States, seeking to build ecumenical ties in
theological education.
   Representing the China Christian Council, the delegation's
cross-country schedule continues through May 8. It is being
coordinated by the China program of the National Council of
Churches.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concluding a lengthy Vatican inquiry into
Roman Catholic religious orders in this country, Pope John Paul II
says they are mostly rendering ``outstanding service.''
   In a letter to U.S. bishops made public last week, the pope said
the evaluation of religious communities carried out between 1983 to
1986 had been largely positive. He wrote:
   ``Please thank them in my name and in your name, in the name of
Jesus Christ and the church.''
   The Vatican-named commission that carried out the inquiry was
headed by Archbishop John R. Quinn of San Francisco.
   Its work has ``proved to be informative and beneficial both to
you and to the religious,'' the pope said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs April 7.</NOTE>
