<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-05 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0900</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter V. Ueberroth, the former baseball
commissioner and Olympic impressario, is expected to announce that
his group has agreed to purchase Eastern Airlines from Texas Air
Corp., The Associated Press learned.
   Ueberroth, whose group unexpectedly made a $464 million offer
for Eastern last week and then withdrew the bid just as suddenly,
traveled from his California home to New York on Tuesday night, and
airline industry and baseball sources said Ueberroth expected the
deal would be announced today.
   Robin Matell, an Eastern spokesman in Miami, said Tuesday night,
``I wouldn't have any comment on a report like that.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales in the United States tumbled
18.3 percent in late March compared with the same period last year,
as the annual spring car buying boom started off as more of a pop.
   Vehicles sold at an average daily rate of 42,451 in the March
21-31 period this year, the companies said Tuesday, compared with a
51,960 daily rate during the same time last year. Car sales were
off 18.1 percent and light truck sales were 18.7 percent behind
last year's pace.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior administration official praised the
Senate Banking Committee's savings and loan proposal for
maintaining tough capital standards, but criticized it for creating
a loophole in the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law.
   The committee is meeting behind closed doors this week in
preparation for public bill-writing sessions next week. On Tuesday,
the panel began going over a series of changes to the
administration plan proposed by the staff of the committee
chairman, Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's Third World debt
initiative won key endorsements from the two international agencies
expected to implement the strategy.
   Both Michel Camdessus, the managing director of the 151-nation
International Monetary Fund, and Barber Conable, president of the
other global lending organization, the World Bank, said Tuesday
they recognized the need for urgency in addressing the debt crisis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission said it
would not stand in the way of British Telecommunications Inc.'s
$1.5 billion investment in McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., the
nation's biggest cellular phone company.
   The FCC said Tuesday the purchase of a 22.4 percent share of
McCaw did not involve a transfer of control of McCaw to British
Telecom USA and it also was in line with federal restrictions on
foreign involvement in U.S. broadcasting and common carrier
companies.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's largest manufacturers enjoyed their
most prosperous year in recent history during 1988 as continued
economic growth brought record profits and soaring sales, Fortune
magazine said in its latest ranking of the 500 biggest U.S.
industrial companies.
   Fortune 500 sales topped $2 trillion for the first time, while
total profits for the group jumped 27 percent to a record $115
billion in 1988, the magazine said Tuesday.
   General Motors Corp. again topped the Fortune 500, while Ford
Motor Co. bumping Exxon Corp. from the No. 2 spot.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration said it would oppose
any move to close the Alaska pipeline but acknowledged it was
unclear whether the federal government has legal authority to
prevent it.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Tuesday the
authority issue was ``an open question.'' However, he said, ``I
don't honestly believe anybody wants to close the pipeline.''
   Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper has threatened to shut the pipeline
unless Exxon and other oil companies produce a better plan to deal
with oil spills such as the one that dumped 10 million gallons in
Prince William Sound on March 24.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Gold Fields PLC unveiled a novel
defense against a hostile bid from Minorco SA, promising to pay its
shareholders $2.2 billion in dividends if it doesn't meet its own
profit forecast.
   South African-based Minorco, whose offer values all of the
British mining group at about $5.4 billion, is trying to overturn a
U.S. court decision that threatens the bid. Consolidated disclosed
the defense Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Teamsters denied contacts
with organized crime but, in an animated appearance before a Senate
subcommittee, testified the men who preceded him as head of the
nation's largest union did have such ties.
   ``One is a schemer and one is a liar and both were mixed up with
La Cosa Nostra,'' William J. McCarthy said of former Teamsters
presidents Roy Williams and Jackie Presser. ``I didn't care for
either one of them.''
   McCarthy testified Tuesday at the opening hearing of a Senate
Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations that is reviewing
government efforts to rid unions of corruption.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back in moderate trading as the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials fell 6.60 to 2,298.20.
   Bond price rose on signs the economy may be slowing.
   The dollar continued to decline amid more signs that the major
industrial nations want to bring the U.S. currency lower.
   Futures prices for coffee surged and corn, soybeans and energy
futures were higher while wheat prices fell, frozen pork bellies
were off sharply and livestock was mixed.
</TEXT>
