<FIRST>r f PM-PreditorsBall Bjt   04-05 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preditors Ball, Bjt,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minus Milken, Junk Bond Gathering Still Draws 3,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be lead after 10 a.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Predators Ball'' begins
today, but the life of the party isn't around.
   Michael Milken, top junk bond trader for Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., can't be at the annual event the company calls the
Institutional Research Conference, which attracts a who's who of
corporate takeover artists.
   Milken, who was charged last week with 98 counts of securities
fraud and racketeering in connection with alleged trading
violations, is officially on leave from his job as Drexel's junk
bond guru.
   The Predators Ball, actually a 3{-day conference on high-yield
bond financing and finance in general, was scheduled to open early
today at the Beverly Hilton Hotel with a talk by Jaime Escalante,
the high-school math teacher whose success with underpriveleged
students was the basis of the movie ``Stand and Deliver.''
   John H. Kissick, Milken's successor as head of Drexel's
high-yield bond unit in Beverly Hills, planned a get-acquainted
talk at the early-morning session.
   Despite his absence, Milken's image looms large over the meeting.
   ``He was omnipresent,'' said Clark Johnson, chairman and chief
executive of Pier 1 Imports Inc. of Fort Worth, Texas, a
participant. ``You saw him around and of course he was running the
show. He was having meetings. He was doing deals. He was being his
usual energetic, indefatigable self.''
   Even without its guiding light, the meeting is a unique
convention of American entrepreneurs who have built or bought
companies with junk bonds, Johnson said.
   ``You always come away re-energized, with a lot of new ideas,''
Johnson said in a telephone interview before the meeting. ``These
have been the growth companies, the companies that are doing
things, the companies that are rebuilding corporate America.''
   Drexel is downplaying Milken's absence from the conference, much
as it is working to assure investors the firm can remain a prime
mover in the high-yield bond market without him.
   The conference is the most heavily attended yet, said Drexel
spokesman Steve Anreder, who emphasized the varied schedule of
sessions on subjects ranging from Third World debt to employee
stock plans to the savings and loan industry.
   ``I think what that says is the high-yield market has been
validated and there's a lot of interest,'' the spokesman said.
   Milken is credited with building the multibillion-dollar market
in junk bonds, the high-risk, high-interest bonds used by
entrepreneurs and corporate takeover artists to raise cash.
   In addition to popularizing use of the bonds _ dubbed ``junk''
because they receive lower than investment-grade ratings from
bond-rating agencies _ Milken was at the center of a newtork of
traders who both sold bonds for their own projects and could be
tapped to invest in junk bonds sold by others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0244 </DOCNO>
