<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   04-05 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Incentives Test Under Way As Car Sales Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. automakers' new incentive packages are
getting a big test in the midst of the traditional spring
car-buying season as sales continued lower than expected, down 18.3
percent in late March compared with last year.
   ``They (carmakers) have got to be a little bit nervous,''
analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York
said Tuesday after the sales figures were reported.
   Vehicles sold at an average daily rate of 42,451 in the March
21-31 period this year, compared with a 51,960 daily rate during
the same time last year. Car sales were off 18.1 percent and light
truck sales were 18.7 percent behind last year.
   ``There's no question that the consumers may be cinching up
their belts a little bit,'' Phillippi said. ``It could be a tough
go here in the month of April. April is absolutely critical.''
   In years past, car shoppers flocked to showrooms in March and
April to get ready for the summertime driving season. But the
figures reported Tuesday showed there was some hesitation.
   During March, cars and light trucks made in both North America
and overseas sold at an average daily rate of 47,848 vehicles, down
12.6 percent from the 54,756 daily rate during March 1988, when the
industry was establishing the second-best sales year in history.
   ``Normally, the month of March is a very critical month for
determining the kickoff of the spring selling season,'' Phillippi
said. ``We didn't have a kickoff.''
   Sales manager Ham Klosterman of Lamar Ferrell Chevrolet in
Decatur, Ga., outside Atlanta, said March sales were better than
February's. But that, he added, ``isn't saying a whole heck of a
lot.''
   ``If it hadn't been for the last five to seven days of March, it
would have been a disaster,'' Klosterman said, noting that
consumers were pushed toward showrooms by a 1 percentage point
increase in the Georgia sales tax effective April 1.
   Automakers themselves gave a good indication of their concern
during the past week by offering new incentive packages that
included more vehicles than previous programs, boosted some cash
rebates and slashed interest rates as low as zero percent at
Chrysler and 2.9 percent at Ford and GM on two-year loans.
   ``I guess the key is that everybody was still sort of getting
their incentive programs into place (in late March), and a lot of
buyers were hanging back to wait and see what would happen,''
Phillippi said.
   There was a question about how long car buyers would hold back,
especially those who have been hit by increased mortgage payments
and other higher monthly bills because of climbing interest rates.
   ``If the zeros and the 2.9s don't work, then we're in deep
trouble,'' Phillippi said.
   Chrysler's late March car sales fell to an average daily rate of
3,544, 26.4 percent lower than the 4,813 car-a-day rate during the
period last year. Chrysler said it sold 21.6 percent fewer cars
through March 31 this year compared with the same time last year.
   Chrysler's truck sales during late March were 19.8 percent
behind last year's rate, but for the year were up 0.7 percent.
   GM reported a 23.9 percent decline in late March car sales,
dropping to a daily rate of 12,159 during the period this year
compared with a rate of 15,973 cars during the same time last year.
For the first three months of 1989, GM's car sales were running
14.6 percent behind last year's pace during the same time.
   Sales of GM's light trucks fell 18.2 percent during the March
21-31 period this year, and were down 6.6 during January-March.
   Ford said its sales of North American-made cars averaged 8,077 a
day during late March, compared with a rate of 9,359 in late March
1988, a decline of 13.7 percent. For the year, Ford's car sales
were down 4.1 percent.
   Sales of light trucks made by Ford were off 23.8 percent in late
March this year, and down 5.8 percent for the first quarter,
compared with the same periods in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
