<FIRST>r f PM-Pickens-Japan     04-05 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pickens-Japan,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING for those needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Japanese Company Surprised By Pickens Stock Acquisition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese auto parts maker in which U.S. corporate
takeover specialist T. Boone Pickens Jr. has taken a substantial
stake today said it was surprised by the move, which made Pickens
its largest shareholder.
   Pickens held 20.2 percent of the stock in Koito Manufacturing
Co. as of March 31. The second-largest stockholder, Toyota Motor
Corp., holds 19.1 percent.
   A Koito spokesman, Mikio Tsuruta, said the unusually large
investment by an American in a Japanese company took the
manufacturer of automobile lighting systems by surprise.
   Koito has contacted its lawyers and its major shareholders,
including Toyota and Nissan Motor Co., which owns 5.95 percent, he
said.
   ``We haven't done anything else yet, because this has been a
very sudden event for us,'' Tsuruta said.
   ``We have no idea why he bought our shares,'' he added.
   Asked if the Japanese company is worried about the 20.2 percent
purchase of its stock by a U.S. company, Tsuruta said, ``Of
course.''
   The company would not comment on speculation that the purchase
by Boone Co., a privately held merchant bank formed in 1986 and
controlled by Pickens, could involve a ``greenmail'' attempt.
   On Tuesday, Boone Co.'s vice president of finance, Sidney
Tassin, would not comment about the firm's intentions toward Koito
or its strategy involving the investment but said he doesn't regard
the stake as hostile in intent.
   ``We believe that the Japanese-American involvement and
relationship is of increasing importance and opportunity,'' said
Tassin.
   Keith Donaldson, an analyst at James Capel Pacific Ltd. in
Tokyo, said ``It looks like a case of greenmail to me. If you want
to do this sort of thing, the best target is Toyota because they've
got 2 trillion yen ($15 billion) in cash.''
   Greenmail is a term used for a method of reaping profits by a
hostile corporate suitor when his stock is purchased at a premium
by another shareholder friendly to the company.
   ``There's no way Boone Pickens is interested in a small car
parts manufacturer,'' said Donaldson. ``There's also no way he
would be able to take the company over because Toyota will come in
and buy him out.''
   Donaldson and other analysts in Tokyo said they believe a
Japanese luxury car importer, Azabu Motors, is behind Pickens'
acquisition of 32.4 million shares of Koito.
   The Azabu group, which reportedly has targeted other Japanese
companies for greenmail in the past, bought 48 million shares of
Koito in 1988. A large block of those shares was registered under
the name of T. Boone Pickens.
   ``Some believe Azabu is only using Boone's name to greenmail
Toyota. Others believe T. Boone is the actual owner,'' said Ben
Moyer, an automobile analyst at Merrill Lynch in Tokyo.
   The Koito purchase is the second major acquisition of stock in a
Toyota group company by a third party in the past two years. In
1987, Nippon Land successfully maneuvered Toyota into buying back a
large portion of shares in Toyoda Automatic Loom, Moyer said.
   Pickens has launched takeover attempts of oil companies
including Unocal, Diamond Shamrock and Phillips, but has never
succeeded in purchasing a company as a result of a hostile bid.
   He has, however, made huge profits on some deals after friendly
investors or the target company itself purchased his shares.
   Boone Co. is not connected with Pickens' Mesa Limited Partners
oil and gas company.
</TEXT>
