<FIRST>r f BC-India-Carbide     04-05 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-India-Carbide,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING for those needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Wants Details On Carbide Negotiations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court asked the Indian
government and Union Carbide Corp. to disclose all details of
negotiations leading to a $470 million settlement in the Bhopal gas
leak, Press Trust of India reported Wednesday.
   The news agency said a five-judge panel asked the government to
file an affidavit within three weeks, disclosing all documents,
negotiations, and persons involved in the talks.
   The panel said it needed to ascertain whether the Feb. 14
settlement was reasonable, PTI said.
   Several opposition politicians and newspapers have termed the
settlement inadequate. The government originally sued Danbury,
Conn.-based Union Carbide for $3 billion.
   The court also said Union Carbide would have to indicate if it
had earlier agreed to a settlement higher than $470 million
dollars, PTI said.
   The government and Union Carbide reached a Supreme
Court-supervised settlement to pay $470 million as compesation to
the victims of the gas leak in the central Indian city of Bhopal.
   More than 3,000 people died and at least 20,000 were injured
when deadly methyl isocynate gas leaked out on Dec. 3, 1984 from a
pesticide plant run by the Indian subsidiary of Union Carbide.
   The government became the sole representatives of more than
500,000 people, who claimed to be victims, through a special law
passed in Parliament. The validity of that law has been challenged
by at least two petitions in the court.
</TEXT>
