<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices were mostly higher in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts said soybeans were showing strength, bolstered by
commission house buying after opening lower.
   Ted Mao of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said traders believed
price movement among soy futures had been limited since Friday's
bearish supply report.
   Speculation of new export sales buoyed wheat prices, and corn
followed the momentum, Mao said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 3} cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.05 a bushel; corn was { cent to
1} cents higher, with May at $2.63} a bushel; oats were unchanged
to { cents lower, with May at $1.88 a bushel; and soybeans were \
cent to 7{ cents higher, with May at $7.15 a bushel.
   Futures prices for livestock and meat were higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, cattle were .32 cent to .57 cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in April at 77.87 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .25 cent to .40 cent higher, with April at 79.77 cents
a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .15 cent higher, with April at
40.75 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .22 cent to .25
cent higher, with May at 35.00 cents a pound.
   On Tuesday, most livestock and meat prices were lower.
