<FIRST>u f PM-UtilityBid 1stLd-Writethru f0093 04-05 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Utility Bid, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0093,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Utility Bids for Lead Seabrook Owner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvx, The offer ..., with one graf to CORRECT to
$850 million sted $850 billion. Picks up 5th graf, Public Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts utility today offered
$2.35 billion for Public Service Company of New Hampshire if the
Seabrook nuclear power plant operates and $1.4 billion if the
troubled reactor doesn't.
   New England Electric System of Westboro made the offer
conditional on the future operation of the plant, which is
completed but lacks an operating license because of regulatory
challenges on its emergency evacuation plans.
   Public Service is the lead owner of Seabrook.
   The offer calls for running the utility under state rather than
federal regulation and a promise to buy $850 million worth of power
if Seabrook operates. It also includes an annual rate increase
ceiling of 7 percent for three years.
   Public Service, which is in bankruptcy reorganization, is banned
by state law from charging consumers for Seabrook before the plant
operates. It has courted Federal Energy Regulatory Commission
regulation to bypass the prohibition.
   New England Electric already has been spending money on a media
campaign aimed in part at letting Public Service's 360,000
customers know it has a long-standing presence in the state. It
owns Granite State Electric Co., which serves 60,000 customers.
   Northeast Utilities of Connecticut, New England's largest
electric company, in January proposed a buyout bid it valued at $2
billion. Public Service says about eight other companies also have
expressed interest in acquiring some or all of its assets.
   Public Service sought bankruptcy court protection more than a
year ago after becoming mired in Seabrook debt.
</TEXT>
