<DOCNO> AP890405-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Northwest     04-05 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis: Financing For Takeover Wouldn't Require Selling `Strategic
Assets'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buying Northwest Airlines for $2.62 billion
would not require selling the carrier's ``strategic assets'' to
finance the takeover debt, suitor Marvin Davis announced today.
   The investor made the statement in a letter to the board of
directors of NWA Inc., the parent of the nation's fourth largest
air carrier.
   Davis, a billionaire whose holdings include real estate and
entertainment properties, last week offered to pay $90 for each of
NWA's 29.1 million shares in a deal he insists is friendly.
   Northwest Chairman Steven Rothmeier has said the board of
directors will review the offer, but he has not said when the board
will meet.
   The airline also said it intends to remain independent and state
officials have rallied behind the carrier, introducing legislation
intended to thwart a hostile takeover.
   ``No divestitures of strategic assets are required to service
the debt that would be incurred to effect the acquisition,'' Davis
said in his letter, which was dated Tuesday and released to the
media today. ``With the equity we are prepared to commit and the
anticipated structure of the balance of the financing, the
company's projected cash flow is adequate to service the debt
involved.''
   Davis repeated in his letter an earlier statement that he
intends to expand the airline's domestic and international routes
and keep the headquarters in Minnesota, where Northwest is one of
the state's largest employers. He also said his plans call for ``no
employee layoffs, workforce reductions or alterations in seniority
schedules.''
   The letter said Northwest management would be retained in the
event of a takeover, but the letter also said, ``we intend to
effect only those management changes required to improve NWA's
performance.''
   ``Since we have no current airline operations, there are no
redundancies or overlaps that would require layoffs or similar
employee reductions,'' the letter said. ``We wish to buy NWA to
operate and expand it.''
   Analysts have said takeover debt could impair Northwest's fleet
modernization plans. But Davis said in his letter that the
acquisition plan ``in no way calls for the reduction of the
company's present capital investment program'' or
``maintenance-related matters.''
   Kevin Whalen, a Northwest spokesman, confirmed that the board of
directors received the letter. He said there would be no comment
from the company until the board reviews Davis' offer.
   The letter did not say that financing was in place for Davis'
proposal.
   In morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange, NWA stock was
selling for $84.75 a share, up $1 from Tuesday's close.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-DefenseProbe 2ndLd-Writethru f0097 04-05 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Probe, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0097,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Executive Testifies He Knew Bribes Were Being Paid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, ``If the farmers ...'' to delete extraneous
sentence; note contents of 12th graf. A version moving on general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former marketing executive for a
defense contractor testified today that he knew bribes were being
paid to a Navy engineer in exchange for inside information about a
lucrative contract.
   But Michael Savaides told the jury he never informed his
superiors at Teledyne Electronics in Newbury Park, Calif., about
the bribery scheme.
   Savaides, who has pleaded guilty to conspiracy to commit bribery
and is cooperating with federal investigators in the case, worked
in Washington as the marketing manager for the firm that was
seeking a $24 million contract for hand-held radar equipment in
1985.
   At that time the California company had already lost one or two
government contracts and had ``fears of losing another program,''
he said. Thus there was some pressure to win the Pentagon business.
   Testifying at the trial of three former executives of Teledyne
Electronics, Savaides said that at the same time he was employed by
the firm he had entered into a secret agreement with two private
consultants, William Parkin and Fred Lackner. Both men have pleaded
guilty in the case.
   In November 1985, Parkin reached a deal with Teledyne
Electronics to be paid $10,000 in exchange for trying to obtain the
contract. At the same time Parkin said Teledyne agreed that he
would be paid $150,000 if he was successful.
   ``If he was not successful, then there would be no fee paid,''
Savaides said.
   When he learned of Parkin's arrangement with Teledyne, Savaides
said, ``My reaction was pure amazement and shock....I didn't
believe Teledyne would enter into an agreement like this.''
   Savaides testified that after Parkin reached the deal with
Teledyne, he, Parkin, Lackner and Berlin were to split the money
equally. Savaides was given some of his portion.
   Savaides' testimony came on the third day of the trial, the
first in the long-running investigation of the defense procurement
case.
   On Tuesday, the prosecution played a tape of a telephone
conversation in which Lackner and Parkin joked about what would
happen if ordinary Americans discovered their bribery scheme.
   ``If the farmers in Indiana knew what you sons of bitches were
doing with their money, they would come up there and kill you with
their pitchforks,'' Lackner told Parkin on the tape.
   Lackner's comment, recorded by one of four FBI bugs placed on
Parkins' home and office telephones in 1987 and 1988, was on two
hours of tapes played for jurors at the trial.
   Lackner's remark drew hearty laughter from Parkin.
   The tapes included numerous conversations between Lackner and
Parkin, detailing their efforts to obtain confidential bid
information that would help Teledyne in its negotiations with the
Pentagon.
   They also provided evidence of repeated requests for such
information by Eugene R. Sullivan, one of the three Teledyne
executives on trial in U.S. District Court in this suburb of
Washington.
   During a conversation June 19, 1987, Lackner furnished Parkin
with details sought by Sullivan about how much the Army, Navy and
Air Force were prepared to spend to procure hand-held radar testing
devices.
   ``The deal is just a tad over $4.2 million,'' Lackner reported.
``Always helpful to know when you're negotiating,'' he said with a
laugh.
   After Teledyne negotiated the contract, Parkin pressured company
executive George H. Kaub, another defendant, to make good on
Teledyne's promise to pay Parkin a $150,000 consulting fee.
   During a conversation July 8, 1987, Parkin told Kaub that he had
helped eliminate Teledyne's competition so that the company would
qualify as a ``sole-source provider'' of the military equipment.
   ``Since it's sole source, you should have much more than enough
to take care of our little pets,'' Parkin told Kaub, referring to
his contacts in Washington who helped get information.
   Kaub said he wasn't sure the contract was that lucrative but
concluded by saying: ``I understand.''
   Complaining also to Sullivan that the money had not been paid,
Parkin threatened to use his influence to get the Defense
Department to cancel its options to buy additional equipment.
   ``The only thing we can do is cancel next year by making sure
it's not exercised,'' he told Sullivan.
   Parkin remarked that his friends, whom he never identified, were
``getting goosey'' about not getting paid.
   ``They have finessed this thing an awfully long way,'' he told
Sullivan.
   The defense contends that Sullivan, Kaub and Dale Schnittjer,
the third Teledyne executive on trial, did not know that Parkin was
engaged in illegal activity after he was retained by Teledyne to
help it get the contract.
   But conversations played on the tapes suggested that Sullivan
and Kaub understood that illegal influence was being exerted.
   In one conversation with Parkin, Sullivan praised his friend's
ability to get him information about the contract. ``I thought I'd
come to the magic swami and have him check it,'' Sullivan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
