<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Skyhawk-Skylark     04-05 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Skyhawk-Skylark,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buick Says Goodbye To Skyhawk, Expands Skylark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Wednesday that it
will halt production of the Buick Skyhawk model cars and increase
output of Skylarks for the 1990 model year.
   The Skyhawk is manufactured in Janesville, Wis., and its
elimination will mean no loss of jobs there because of increased
production of the Chevrolet Cavalier, also made at the plant,
spokeswoman Corby Casler said.
   Starting in the 1990 model year, which officially begins Oct. 1,
Flint-based Buick will offer four Skylark models _ a standard,
custom, luxury edition and gran sport.
   The Skyhawk was introduced in 1982 as a coupe and a sedan. A
station wagon was added the following year and hatchback models
were introduced for the 1986 and 1987 model years.
   Through March of this year, Skyhawk sales were running 43.1
percent behind last year's pace. Skylark sales during the same
period were down 11.4 percent. Overall, GM's car sales for the year
were off 14.6 percent compared with the same time last year.
</TEXT>
