<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-OffshoreOil     04-05 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Offshore Oil,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Companies Win Santa Barbara Offshore Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp. expects to begin
production near Point Arguello later this year as part of a project
designed to supply enough energy to fuel 2.9 million cars a day,
according to a company attorney.
   Chevron lawyer Doug Uchikura made the statement Tuesday night
when the Santa Barbara County Board of Supervisors voted that a
group of companies led by Chevron be allowed to start oil and
natural gas operations. The board voted 4 to 1 that the $2 billion
project meets county safety requirements.
   Uchikura said the company still needs board approval for using
tankers to move oil from Point Arguello to California refineries,
including Chevron's huge facility at Richmond. He said that once
approval for the tankers is received the company plans to start
operations in July or August.
   The other companies in the partnership include Texaco Inc.,
Phillips Petroleum Co., Pennzoil Co., Sun Co. and Union Pacific
Corp.
   The plan calls for three offshore drilling platforms and two
27-mile pipelines that transport crude oil and gas to separate
purifying plants in Gaviota.
   Chevron agreed to install an alarm system on the pipeline that
would detect a hydrogen sulfide leak. The county planning
commission earlier rejected th plan, saying the companies
underestimated by 65 percent the amount of hydrogen sulfide in the
field's natural gas.
   Chevron also agreed to lower pipeline pressure to reduce the
spread of a potential leak in an area that was hit by a 3 million
gallon oil spill by Union Oil Co. in 1969.
   Backers say that by the 1990s the field's production could hit
93,000 barrels of oil and 60 million cubic feet of gas a day, more
than the current output for the entire Santa Barbara Channel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
