<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0052 04-05 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0052,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates thruout with closing prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed lower on Wednesday as the
market remained preoccupied about the outlook for the pound and
British interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 4.6
points, or 0.2 percent, to 2,078.2.
   Volume was 440.7 million shares, down from 508.2 million shares
Tuesday.
   Traders were concerned that the British government would be
forced to raise base lending rates above the current 13 percent
level in order to defend the currency, dealers said.
   With the interest rate outlook uncertain, share prices drifted
lower, remaining locked in a tight range for most of the day.
   The pound fell again on Wednesday, but remained above the level
at which the government would trigger a rate rise, said Paul
Walton, an equities analyst at the British brokerage firm Warburg
Securities. In the meantime the government prefers to defend the
pound through aggressive public comments and Bank of England
intervention, Walton added.
   However players were looking ahead to the April 14 release of
the British retail price index for March, with anyve the
predicted 7.9 percent annual rate likely to provide anoter test
for the pound, Walton said.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 3 points lower at
1,705.4. The Financial Tis 500-share index closed at 1,182.21,
down 3.85.
</TEXT>
