<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2054EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FundRankings     04-05 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fund Rankings,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release at 12:01 a.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Risk Had its Rewards and Losses, Mutual Fund Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors in mutual funds that held stock in
certain small, fast-growing companies made a tidy profit in the
first quarter, but those involved in equally risky worldwide
fixed-income funds fared poorly, a survey of mutual fund
performance said.
   Alger Small Capital and the Kaufman Fund were the biggest
gainers among nearly 1,700 funds surveyed during the three months
ended March 31, with rates of return of 20 percent and 19 percent,
respectively, according to a tally released Thursday by Lipper
Analytical Services Inc.
   The strategy of both funds was to pick small companies that
showed potential for rapid growth.
   In terms of specific industries, Lipper said the top performing
funds had significant positions in broadcast, cellular and selected
telephone issues. Leading the pack were health and biotechnology
funds, which gained 11.04 percent on average and natural resource
funds, which gained 8.63 percent.
   Less successful were funds specializing in foreign bonds, which
lost on average 2.20 percent, thanks mainly to weakness in many
foreign currencies, Lipper said. Utilities funds had a 2.25 percent
gain, it said.
   Eight of the 10 biggest quarterly losers were funds in the world
income category, which are most sensitive to fluctuations in
currencies and interest rates. International Cash: Swiss Franc and
T. Rowe Price International Bond headed the list with losses of
8.98 percent and 6.08 percent, respectively.
   Lipper's tally assumes that investors reinvest all dividends and
capital gains distributions that the funds pay out.
   Overall, investors who put their money in stock funds fared
better than those choosing bonds, according to Lipper.
   The average general equity fund gained 6.57 percent, compared
with a 1.17 percent return for fixed-income funds.
   ``As the average fixed income returns were below the interest
rates earned on the portfolios, we believe it is reasonable to
assume that many fixed income funds had a modest loss in terms of
principal only performance,'' said A. Michael Lipper, the firm's
president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
