<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-WangLayoffs     04-05 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wang Layoffs,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wang Trims Work Force By 880</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wang Laboratories Inc. has cut 880 people
from its worldwide work force and will continue to trim, a company
spokesman said Thursday.
   The Boston Globe reported Monday that the computer company is
also considering a write-down of some underperforming corporate
assets, but spokesman Joseph Roy would not comment.
   ``In November, we put in a hiring `frost,''' Roy said, pointing
out that the action was not a complete hiring freeze. ``As people
leave, we don't replace most people, except for crucial jobs.''
   Roy said Wang's payroll employees worldwide had dropped from
31,391 on Dec. 31 to approximately 30,700 at the end of February.
In addition, the company laid off 180 field-service engineers last
week, Roy said.
   ``We believe we can work the numbers down quite a bit without
terminations,'' Roy told the newspaper. ``Attrition has worked
well, but not well enough. We can't rule out further adjustments.''
   Analysts have been encouraging the company to cut costs. Jay P.
Stevens, who follows the company for Dean Witter Reynolds, said
Wang's general and administrative costs are ``outrageously high,
among the highest in the computer industry.''
</TEXT>
