<DOCNO> AP890405-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1808EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-05 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0610</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices soared Wednesday, recovering from five
consecutive declining sessions, and the stabilized U.S. dollar sent
gold prices lower on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   On other futures markets, prices for soybeans advanced, grains
were mixed, cattle were higher and pork declined.
   Although the trading volume was light, May copper shot up 190
points during the Comex session, then settled 90 points higher,
after falling 570 points on Monday. A point is one-hundredth of a
cent.
   Metals analyst George Anagnos of Thomson Mckinnon Securities
Inc. said the rally stemmed partly from the belief that the market
has been oversold. He also said prices rose because production has
declined and demand is rising.
   Gold and silver future prices slumped in response to what
strategists called a respectable performance by the U.S. dollar
against foreign currencies, Anagnos said.
   Precious metals usually move in the opposite direction of the
dollar.
   Copper settled .40 cents to 1.55 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in April at $1.29.85 a pound; gold was $2.30 to $3.20
lower, with April at $383.80 a troy ounce; and silver was 1.5 cents
to 4.0 cents lower, with April at $5.80 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices tumbled on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Unleaded gasoline prices were down the 200-point limit in the
most active months, inciting a selling spree in crude oil futures
and heating oil.
   Analysts believe that last week's rally was overdone, and this
week's activity is a technical correction for the market.
   Crude oil settled 43 cents to 58 cents lower, with the contract
for delivery in May at $19.99 a barrel; heating oil was 1.47 cents
to 2.01 cents lower, with May at $1.63 a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was 1.54 cents to 3.03 cents lower, with May at 66.43
cents a gallon.
   Soybean futures prices climbed higher while grains were mixed on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   After opening lower, soybeans strengthened, bolstered by large
buying orders, and finished up to 8 cents higher for the May 1990
contract.
   Ted Mao, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said traders
believed soy futures had been ovbersold during Monday's selloff, a
reaction to reports of excessive supplies.
   Rumors of new soy-oil export sales also spurred soybean buying,
traders said.
   Katharina Zimmer of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets said corn
prices were strengthened by recent Soviet purchases and wheat
prices rose because of dry-weather forecasts.
   Wheat settled 2 cents lower to 3 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in May at $4.04\ a bushel; corn was } cent lower to 2
cents higher, with May at $2.64 a bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 5
cents lower, with May at $1.83 a bushel; and soybeans were \ cents
to 8 cents higher, with May at $7.17 a bushel.
   Most cattle futures prices were higher while most pork prices
fell on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Paul Hare of Linnco Futures Inc. said cattle's strong recovery
from four losing sessions was generally due to internal market
influences.
   Cattle settled .10 cent lower to .62 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in April at 78.17 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .30 cent to .57 cent higher, with April at 79.87 cents
a pound; live hogs were .03 cent lower to .20 cent higher, with
April at 40.57 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .80 cent
lower to .15 cent higher, with May at 35.00 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
