<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-05 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Edges Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved moderately higher Wednesday
against major foreign currencies in what analysts called a
technical adjustment following its recent slump.
   Gold prices fell. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $383.30 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from
$385.90 late Tuesday.
   Wednesday's modest gains at least temporarily ended the dollar's
decline, which began last week. At that time, the central banks of
several nations intervened in the foreign exchange markets to bring
the U.S. currency lower.
   But Ronald Holzer, chief foreign exchange dealer with Harris
Trust &amp; Savings Bank in Chicago, said the dollar's advance
Wednesday was a minor adjustment and that the currency's outlook
remained bearish, partly because the seven major industrial nations
have restated their desire for stable interest rates.
   The seven nations _ the United States, Britain, France, West
Germany, Japan, Italy and Canada _ believe the dollar has been too
strong recently.
   Holzer said the focus of trading Wednesday was the West German
mark, which enjoyed strong advances against most currencies.
   However, the dollar managed to rise against the West German
currency, closing in New York at 1.8695 marks, up from late
Tuesday's 1.86835 marks. In earlier Frankfurt trading, the dollar
rose to 1.8695 marks from 1.8670 marks.
   Overseas dealers said market activity was quiet as traders
awaited Friday's U.S. unemployment figures for March which could
give some fresh insight into the direction of the American economy.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7028 late Wednesday,
cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late rate of $1.7043. In New
York, sterling fell to $1.7030 from late Tuesday's $1.7085.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's prices, included: 1.64125 Swiss francs, up from 1.63075;
6.3090 French francs, up from 6.3060; 1,371.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,370.375; and 1.19075 Canadian dollars, up from 1.18655.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Tuesday's late rates included: 1.6395 Swiss francs, up from 1.6358;
6.3150 French francs, up from 6.3100; 2.1125 Dutch guilders, up
from 2.1080; 1,372.50 Italian lire, down from 1,372.75, and 1.1895
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1875.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 131.37 Japanese yen, up
from 131.05 yen. In London, the dollar traded higher at 131.70 yen,
and it rose to 131.555 yen in New York from late Tuesday's 130.85
yen.
   Gold was bid at $383.50 a troy ounce in London, down from
$386.75 an ounce late Tuesday. The Zurich late bid price was
$383.35 an ounce, down from $386.50 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, gold traded unchanged in Hong Kong at a bid of $387.25
an ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, a troy ounce of gold for
current delivery fell to $383.80 from late Tuesday's $385.90.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of $5.83 a troy
ounce, down from $5.84 late Tuesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange, silver for current deleivery closed
at $5.816 a troy ounce, up from $5.801 late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
