<DOCNO> AP890405-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1829EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-NWA Bjt   04-05 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NWA, Bjt,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Says He'd Put Equity Into Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock of NWA Inc. rose sharply Wednesday
following an announcement by oil mogul Marvin Davis that his $2.62
billion proposal to buy the parent of Northwest Airlines would not
require selling the carriers' ``strategic assets.''
   ``We do not intend to `bust up' the company, and our planned
financing will not necessitate the sale of any of the company's
strategic assets,'' Davis said in a letter dated Tuesday to NWA's
board of directors.
   The Los Angeles-based billionaire, who owns about 3 percent of
NWA's 29.1 million shares, released the letter Wednesday to the
media. A spokesman for the nation's fourth largest air carrier
confirmed receipt of the letter, but said the company would not
comment.
   ``With the equity we are prepared to commit and the anticipated
structure of the balance of the financing, the company's projected
cash flow is adequate to service the debt involved,'' the letter
said.
   NWA stock rose $3.50 a share to an all-time high of $87.25 on
the New York Stock Exchange. More than 2.5 million shares traded
hands.
   Davis, whose holdings include real estate and entertainment
properties, offered to pay $90 a share for NWA stock in a letter
last week to company directors.
   In his second letter, Davis said his group is ``prepared to
increase the price of our offer in the context of a negotiated
transaction.''
   Northwest Chairman Steven Rothmeier has said the board of
directors will review the offer, but he has not said when the board
will meet.
   The airline also said it intends to remain independent and state
officials have rallied behind the carrier, introducing legislation
intended to thwart a hostile takeover.
   In Washington, Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich and Rep. James
Oberstar, D-Minn., met with Northwest representatives and spoke
later by telephone with Davis, and told reporters they still
opposed the billionaire's offer.
   Perpich, a Democrat, and Oberstar, chairman of the House
aviation subcommittee, said they were still worried that Davis
would have to sell parts of the airline to finance the deal. They
said that might result in layoffs and in Northwest moving its
service hub from Minneapolis' airport.
   ``I want to see his prospective balance sheet,'' Oberstar said.
   Said Perpich: ``How can you guarantee that what they say
verbally ... they'll follow through'' on.
   Guy Cook, chairman of International Association of Machinists
District Lodge 143, said he remains ``suspicious'' of Davis' offer
because Davis has not provided specifics about how he would finance
the takeover.
   ``I believe he has a history of buying and selling companies,''
said Cook, who heads the union representing two-thirds of
Northwest's 35,000 employees. ``He has ownership for a period of
time and then he sells it off.''
   Kurt Rivard, an analyst for Minneapolis-based Dain Bosworth
Inc., said the increase in the stock price Wednesday suggests
confidence on the part of investors that a higher bid is on its way.
   ``It could come from Davis, it could come from Northwest, it
could come from somewhere else,'' Rivard said.
   Before Davis made his offer to Northwest, the company disclosed
a separate group of investors was interested in buying NWA. The
identity of that group, which owns 4.9 percent of the stock, has
not been disclosed.
   Davis repeated in his letter an earlier statement that he
intends to expand the airline's domestic and international routes
and keep the headquarters in Minnesota. He also said his plans call
for ``no employee layoffs, workforce reductions or alterations in
seniority schedules.''
   The letter said Northwest management would be retained in the
event of a takeover, but the letter also said, ``we intend to
effect only those management changes required to improve NWA's
performance.''
   ``Since we have no current airline operations, there are no
redundancies or overlaps that would require layoffs or similar
employee reductions,'' the letter said. ``We wish to buy NWA to
operate and expand it.''
   Analysts have said takeover debt could impair Northwest's fleet
modernization plans because Davis would have to sell assets and cut
operating costs to service takeover debt. But Davis said in his
letter that the acquisition plan ``in no way calls for the
reduction of the company's present capital investment program'' or
``maintenance-related matters.''
   In other developments, contract talks continued Wednesday
between Northwest and its 5,000-member pilots' union.
   Northwest has discussed profit-sharing and stock ownership plans
with its unions for more than a year. Analysts have said an
employee stock ownership plan could help the carrier defend itself
against a takeover by putting more stock in friendly hands.
   Meanwhile, state Commerce Commissioner Michael Hatch told the
St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch that he is investigating the
possibility of stock manipulation in connection with takeover bids
for Northwest. But Hatch said the inquiry is not based on any
specific allegations.
</TEXT>
