<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1839EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Lockheed     04-05 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lockheed,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investor Simmons Reduces Lockheed Stake to 4.2 Pct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dallas investor Harold Simmons revealed
Wednesday he cut his stake in Lockheed Corp. a day after the maker
of the stealth fighter plane buttressed its takeover defenses.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Simmons
said he had sold 200,000 shares of recently acquired Lockheed
stock, cutting his holdings in the aerospace company from 5.3
percent to 4.2 percent.
   Officials at Lockheed headquarters in this Los Angeles suburb
refused to comment on Simmons' announcement, which came one day
after the company created an employee stock ownership plan that
would have deterred a hostile takeover.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Lockheed fell $1.12{
a share to $46.62{.
   Analysts suggested Simmons had considered a buyout bid, but gave
up because of the new ESOP would put 17 percent of Lockheed stock
in employees' hands. That would effectively block a takeover
because in Delaware, where the company is incorporated, a buyout
must be approved by holders of 85 percent of the stock.
   ``Basically, Lockheed put him in a box,'' said analyst Harold
Rubel, who follows the company for Cyrus J. Lawrence in New York.
``Simmons was out-and-out attempting to put the company into play
and management did the right thing.''
   In the filing, Simmons said he sold the shares ``in light of the
performance of the shares in the market and current developments
involving the company, including the company's sale of shares to an
employee stock ownership plan.''
   The investor, who made the purchases through his Valhi Inc.,
said in the filing he would still consider future investments in
Lockheed.
   When he revealed his investment Monday, Simmons said he didn't
intend to try buying the whole company.
   Lockheed said in announcing the ESOP that it wasn't responding
to a possible takeover bid by Simmons. The plan was intended to
boost employee performance by building their stake in the company,
and was part of an overall restructuring by the new chairman and
chief executive, Daniel Tellep.
   Included in the restructuring was acceleration of previously
announced plans to move the top secret ``Skunk Works'' aircraft
plant and other manufacturing operations from buildings next to
Burbank Airport to Palmdale and Rye Valley, Calif., and Marietta,
Ga. The factories employ 7,000 people.
   The moves would free 225 acres of land at the airport for sale
in 1991 rather than in 1992 or 1993, as previously planned.
   Lockheed also said it would sell its computer operations over a
period of time. The operations, CADAM Inc. in Burbank, CalComp in
Anaheim, Metier Inc. in Houston and Lockheed DataPlan Inc. in Los
Gatos, employ 3,900.
   ``I'm assuming he wasn't too happy with what they did, so he
took his profit and took part of his money and left,'' said John
Simon, who follows Lockheed for Seidler Amdec Securities Inc. in
Los Angeles.
   In addition to the radar-evading fighter plane, Lockheed makes
the Trident II missile, the C-5A military transport plane, and
works on NASA's space station, among other government and private
industry projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
