<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1840EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MinersStrike     04-05 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miners Strike,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miners Walk in Two States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASTLEWOOD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coal miners in two states struck The
Pittston Co. Wednesday after working 14 months without a contract.
   The strike affects 1,600 members of the United Mine Workers
union in Virginia and West Virginia. Other Pittston employees in
Kentucky remained on the job, the union said.
   ``There's a series of decisons being made about our miners in
Kentucky and a couple of different groups _ locals _ in Virginia,''
UMW spokesman Joe Corcoran said. ``The decision not to strike them
right now could be short-lived.''
   Jackie Stump, president of the UMW's Virginia district in
Castlewood, said he was not optimistic.
   ``We hope that it's settled early, but we have been telling
people they may be on strike for a year or two years _ whatever it
takes,'' Stump said.
   UMW President Richard Trumka announced the strike Wednesday
morning. In a news release from the union's Washington
headquarters, Trumka said, ``The UMW has gone the extra mile to
avoid a strike and to reach a mutually beneficial agreement with
the company both before and since the expiration of our contract
with Pittston.
   ``But Pittston's response _ an endless stream of labor law
violations and broken promises _ has been antagonistic from the
start.''
   Michael Odom, president of Pittston's coal operations, said in a
statement: ``It is unfortunate that the union has called a strike
againt the company which will undoubtedly cause much disruption and
hardship for our employees and the coalfield communities.''
   Odom also said the company will begin hiring replacement workers
where needed.
   Besides representing the strikers, the UMW represents
approximately 4,000 laid off Pittston employees and 1,500 Pittston
retirees.
   The union's contract with Pittston expired Feb. 1, 1988, after
the coal company refused to sign the national coal contract agreed
to by most major producers.
   Pittston is the nation's 15th largest coal producer and the
second largest exporter of coal.
</TEXT>
