<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1843EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Ueberroth     04-05 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Ueberroth,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ueberroth Record Reflects High-Profile Successes, Low-Profile Personal
Style</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   His roots in the travel industry go deep, but Peter V. Ueberroth
_ leader of a group that wants to buy Eastern Airlines _ made his
reputation as the man who made the Olympics and major league
baseball profitable.
   Ueberroth, 51, already had founded a hugely successful travel
business by the time he rose to prominence as president of the Los
Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee, the group responsible for
staging what generally had been a money-losing enterprise.
   The 1984 Los Angeles Olympics, expected to lose money or at best
break even, made $230 million.
   Major league owners made him baseball commissioner in 1985,
following a season in which the 26 teams reported losing $40
million on revenue of $625 million, the industry's 11th consecutive
losing year.
   Ueberroth cut the losses to $6 million in his first year and
baseball made $12 million in 1986, according to financial reports
obtained by the Associated Press. In 1987, baseball made a record
$103 million and preliminary figures for 1988 show a $100 million
profit on record revenue of $977 million.
   He also acted aggressively in helping end umpires and players
strikes and negotiating a $1 billion television package for
baseball.
   Detractors say the golden image isn't totally warranted,
claiming Ueberroth made the Olympics profitable by using huge
numbers of volunteers who worked for free.
   They also point to deteriorating labor relations in baseball at
the time of his departure, which have raised the specter of a
strike next year, and the possibility of hundreds of millions of
dollars in judgments against owners, stemming from collusion in
closing the free-agent market.
   Regardless, business success was old hat for Ueberroth even
before the Olympics and baseball, which he officially left on April
1.
   He was vice president of Trans International Airlines for two
years when, in 1963, he founded a small travel agency in Southern
California. Eventually, he built First Travel Corp. into the
second-largest business of its kind in North America and sold it in
1979 for $10.6 million, earning $4.4 million personally.
   During his baseball tenure, Ueberroth stayed active in other
businesses. He is a director of several major corporations and, as
a director of E.F. Hutton Inc., helped engineer the investment
firm's sale to Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc.
   His reputation as a man with a golden business touch has put him
in demand for other high-profile jobs.
   The National Republican Senatorial Committee wanted him in 1986
to run for office, but he said he wasn't a politician _ shaking
hands and kissing babies wasn't his style.
   Ueberroth also turned down recent offers for the chief executive
officer's posts at MGM Pictures Inc. and RJR Nabisco Inc.
   ``I didn't think I'd make enough of a difference,'' he said.
   Friends say the challenge of turning around Eastern, which has
been wracked by financial losses and labor unrest for years,
intrigues him.
   But Ueberroth's high-profile financial wizardry contrasts
somewhat with a low-profile personal style that some might even
call bland.
   He works in short-sleeve shirts, not suits, at his 17th-floor
office on Park Avenue. He walks carefully, not confidently, speaks
softly, and has employees who call him ``Peter'' not ``Mr.''
   ``I'm shy, but I think you can be shy and ruthless at the same
time,'' he once said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
