<FIRST>u f AM-GATT-WorldTrade     04-05 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GATT-World Trade,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Informal Talks Mired In Disagreement Over Farm Subsidies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Informal talks seeking a compromise accord on
liberalizing world trade in four key areas were mired Wednesday by
continuing disagreements over agricultural subsidies, trade
officials said.
   The talks held under the auspices of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, GATT, officially opened Wednesday morning but
were adjourned after one hour to allow more time for informal
discussions to reach a compromise on agriculture, intellectual
property, textiles and GATT escape clauses.
   It is recognized that agreement on agriculture is fundamental to
consensus being reached in Geneva on the other three outstanding
issues.
   ``We will have a final agreement on all four or none,'' said
Karl Falkenberg, a spokesman for the European Economic Community
delegation.
   In his opening speech at the morning plenary session GATT
Director-General Arthur Dunkel said that agreement on an
agricultural package was near.
   But eight hours of informal talks ended in disagreement between
the EEC, the United States and the so-called Cairns free-trade
group over short-term measures to freeze agricultural production
and subsidies.
   Differences between the EEC and the United States on farm policy
caused stalemate at GATT's ministerial talks in Montreal in
December.
   ``The problem appears to be the same as it was in Montreal,''
said Rubens Ricupero, head of the Brazilian delegation.
   Dunkel, who heads the 96-nation trade forum, was expected to
spend Wednesday night drafting a new set of compromise proposals to
present to GATT's plenary session Thursday morning, officials said.
   Negotiators refused to speculate on the consequences of failure
to reach agreement at the negotiations, scheduled to end Friday.
</TEXT>
