<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1849EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Drexel-Shad     04-05 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drexel-Shad,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former SEC Chairman Has Drexel Office, But No Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Predators Ball Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former head of the Securities and Exchange
Commission has moved into an office at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
but hasn't yet formally accepted the chairman's job, the troubled
investment firm said Wednesday.
   John S.R. Shad, who ordered the government's huge securities
fraud investigation of Drexel in 1986, has been working out of an
executive suite at the Wall Street firm for several weeks, Drexel
spokesman Steven Anreder said.
   Drexel, seeking to repair its image after agreeing to a record
$650 million settlement with the government for a range of criminal
securities law violations, offered Shad the post in January.
   The nation's fifth-largest investment firm currently is
negotiating with the SEC to settle separate civil charges that
include insider trading.
   Shad, 65, resigned later in January as U.S. ambassador to the
Netherlands, where he served from June 1987. He ran the SEC, the
federal agency that regulates the nation's securities markerts,
from 1981 to 1987.
   Anreder said Shad would not decide whether to accept the Drexel
chairman's job permanently until after the SEC settlement is
completed. The deal has been expected for months but negotiations
recently deadlocked.
   Anreder would not say whether Shad was waiting for the SEC talks
to end to avoid a possible conflict of interest. The spokesman also
said he didn't know whether Shad was getting paid.
   ``He has indicated all along he would wait until the SEC
settlement is in place. He set that as one of his requirements,''
he said.
   If Shad accepts the job, it would mark an ironic twist in the
legal battle. He ordered the massive government probe of Drexel in
late 1986 after Drexel was implicated in widespread wrongdoing by
former speculator Ivan F. Boesky, who is now serving a three-year
jail term.
   In addition, Drexel's chief executive officer, Frederick Joseph
was once hired by Shad 20 years ago when Shad ran the now-defunct
investment firm E.F. Hutton &amp; Co.
   Shad was out of the office and unavailable for comment, a
secretary answering his telephone said.
   Anreder would not specify Shad's activities in the office, but
said he was ``familiarizing himself with the firm, people, doing
the things one does in that process.''
   ``He is not working for the firm,'' Anreder said. ``He's been
examining the firm, getting to know it, doing his own kind of
analysis.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890405-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1855EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-PredatorsBall 1stLd-Writethru f0248 04-05 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Predators Ball, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0248,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 7 grafs saying Milken was invited to private dinner
at conference, but invitation was canceled. Pick up 5th graf pvs, Drexel
representatives ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Predators Ball'' opened
Wednesday with what amounted to an empty spot at the head table:
   Junk bond guru Michael Milken was missing from the official
agenda for the annual Drexel Burnham Lambert conference he founded
11 years ago, and was even forbidden to attend a dinner after
Wednesday's festivities.
   Milken, who was charged last week with 98 counts of securities
fraud and racketeering in connection with alleged trading
violations, is on a forced leave of absence from Drexel.
   A Drexel employee had him on the guest list for one of several
unofficial dinners that accompany the meeting, but canceled the
invitation Tuesday, according to a source familiar with the
situation, who commented on condition of anonymity.
   Drexel officials feared Milken's presence could threaten the
company's $650 million plea bargain to federal felony securities
fraud charges, the source said. Part of that deal, which has yet to
be signed, bar Drexel officials from business contacts with the
indicted trader.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder, asked to comment, said only:
``Originally he was supposed to speak at some kind of a meeting and
our lawyers advised against it because they thought it would be
inappropriate.''
   Milken was far from forgotten at the 3{-day series of meetings
and bond sales pitches at the Beverly Hilton Hotel. Drexel calls it
the 11th annual Institutional Research Conference; the name favored
by the media comes from corporate raiders who sell junk bonds to
raise funds for their exploits.
   Drexel representatives said the record attendance of 3,000
proved Milken wasn't really the main drawing card.
   But his evangelistic speeches and dynamic presence are missed by
many, said Ralph Rosenberg, chairman of Longview Capital Corp. of
Miami.
   ``I think a lot of people turned out as a tribute to Mike,''
Rosenberg said Wednesday.
   Milken's successor as head of Drexel's Beverly Hills-based,
high-yield bond department, John Kissick, paid homage to his
indicted predecessor, offering ``our honest wishes for success'' in
defending himself. But he emphasized the unspoken theme: Even
without the dynamic trader, Drexel intends to remain a powerhouse
in the junk bond market, which to date totals $183 billion.
   ``Drexel remains committed to maintaining the high quality of
this market as we move ahead,'' Kissick said in opening the
conference before a standing-room-only crowd.
   Junk bonds, so-called because the companies that issue them are
deemed among the less creditworthy by the agencies that rate
corporate bonds, pay their buyers more interest than the highly
rated bonds of blue-chip companies. Milken is credited with
popularizing the idea over the last decade or so that such bonds
are a good investment, thus making it possible to finance growing
businesses and fund corporate takeovers with the bonds.
   The Predators Ball may be more a meeting than a party, but it's
no bankers' convention. It begins each day at 6:50 a.m. _ regular
business hours for Wall Street-oriented West Coast residents like
the hard-charging Milken.
   The absent trader's stamp was evident elsewhere. He often speaks
of the importance of education, as did the morning's inspirational
speaker, Jaime Escalante, whose success teaching calculus to poor
East Los Angeles high-school students was the basis for the movie
``Stand and Deliver.''
   The business sessions, which are closed to the press, include
pitches by companies and investors selling high-yield bonds and
talks on such topics as bankruptcy and savings and loan investment
opportunities.
   Among the presenters are RJR Nabisco Inc., Braniff Inc., media
entrepreneur Ted Turner and Valhi Inc., the investment vehicle for
Dallas investor Harold Simmons.
   But more important, said many, is the chance to mingle with
fellow entrepreneurs, investors and potential business partners.
   Patrick Tillieux, who deals in mergers and acquisitions for
Bouygues SA, a French construction and entertainment company, came
to the conference to see how Americans handle leveraged buyouts _
and to soak up the high-powered atmosphere.
   ``We do not come for Michael Milken,'' Tillieux said. ``It's the
show.''
   As is typical of corporate ``roadshows'' for investors, some of
the presentations included such inducements as tote bags and
dancers dressed as Lifesavers candy.
   Not to be outdone in the gimmick department, Drexel erected a
10-foot-tall model of a space station in the hotel lobby. The
revolving model suggested an orbiting outpost of free enterprise,
bearing model buildings emblazoned with the logos of such junk-bond
issuers as Budget Rent-a-Car and AMC Theaters.
   Gray-suited conferees listened, apparently nonplussed, as a
repeating soundtrack on the space station intespersed pep talks on
the joys of junk bonds with altered versions of two pop-rock songs.
Stevie Winwood's ``Higher Love'' came out ``Life with a higher
yield'' and the Jefferson Starship hit ``We Built this City (on
Rock nd Roll)'' transformed into ``We built this city on high-yield
bonds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
