<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Kodak,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Claims More Name Recognition Than Kodak _ Not So</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Polaroid Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. was looking through the wrong end
of the viewfinder Wednesday when it said it was the only
photographic company on a list of the 25 most respected brand names
in the world.
   Polaroid's Carl J. Yankowski cited a study on corporate names by
Landor Associates to back his contention that favorable name
recognition would help sales of its new OneFilm conventional film.
   But according to Landor Associates of San Francisco, there were
a few problems with Polaroid's interpretation of its findings:
   _Canon Inc., a photographic company, was in the top 25 at No.
23, one notch behind Polaroid.
   _Eastman Kodak Co. was not on the list only because it was not
included in the European portion of the 3,000-person survey. Kodak
finished ahead of Polaroid in both the United States and Japan.
   _Esteem was only half of what Landor counted in its rankings.
The other half was simple name recognition, or what Landor calls
``share of mind.''
   The mistakes appeared to be the result of oversimplification,
not deception. Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips said the
company simply wanted to make the point that it had a good image
worldwide.
