<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Airlines-Tokyo     04-05 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airlines-Tokyo,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOT Turns Down Chicago-Tokyo Air Routes _ for Now</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation has
rejected requests from United and American airlines to establish
non-stop flights from Chicago to Tokyo, officials said Wednesday.
   But the agency left the airlines the option to re-apply for the
routes, and said in a statement that U.S. officials would discuss
the expansion of non-stop air service between the cities in trade
talks with Japan next month.
   The talks, in Tokyo, will discuss possible revisions of the
United States-Japan Air Transport Agreement of 1952, which, with
amendments, dictates what air routes are open, the Transportation
Department said in an order issued Tuesday.
   ``We remain sensitive ... to the issues raised by the
applications (from the airlines) and we are prepared to discuss
them with Japan during the next round of negotiations,'' said the
order issued in Washington.
   Currently, non-stop Chicago-to-Tokyo flights are provided only
by Minneapolis-based Northwest Airlines and Japan Air lines, said
Russell Mack, a spokesman for Chicago-based United.
   Mack said the ``principal focus'' of the talks beginning May 15
between the two governments will be the Chicago-to-Tokyo direct
routes, which is considered good news by the airline.
   ``The May 15 talks will be absolutely critical to U.S.
competitiveness,'' a United statement said. ``They are a priceless
opportunity for this administration to take concrete action on its
stated pledge to help redress the U.S. trade imbalance with Japan.''
   ``Air service between Chicago and Japan has not kept pace with
the growth in the U.S.-Japan market,'' Mack said.
   He said Asian routes are coveted because ``the Pacific is the
fastest-growing aviation market in the world.''
   United already has daily non-stop flights to Tokyo from New
York, San Francisco and Los Angeles, he said.
</TEXT>
