<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OperatorServices     04-05 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Operator Services,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Operator Services for Public Phones Debated on Capitol Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alternative operator services for telephones
in the nation's airports, hotels, hospitals and other public places
are benefiting consumers by forcing American Telephone &amp; Telegraph
Co. to improve service, Congress was told Wednesday.
   Harvey M. Berg, a member of the board of directors of the
Operator Service Providers of America, also said the advent of such
companies has led to new services.
   Berg, in testimony before the House Energy and Commerce
telecommunications and finance subcommittee, acknowledged problems
in his industry, where customers have complained of charges two to
three times those of AT&amp;T and of call ``blocking'' that doesn't
allow customers to use the long-distance carriers of their choice
for credit card or operator assisted calls.
   His group ``does not condone consumer abuses but, rather, has
acted to correct them,'' Berg said. Since its formation in April
1988, he said, ``the rate of complaints to regulators has fallen''
and ``rates have receded substantially. ... The marketplace is
working.''
   The Federal Communications Commission has received more than
2,000 complaints about ``AOS'' services from customers who often
don't know whom they're dealing with or why they get high bills
from cities they've never visited.
   And some legislators fear the situation will get worse because
of a federal judge's ruling that required all owners of hotels,
restaurants and other public places to decide by April 1 who should
provide their long-distance pay phone service.
   The companies that own and operate the phones pay commissions to
the premise owners to use their services.
   The FCC last month ordered restrictions on AOS companies that
included notices of who the AOS provider is and how to find out
rates, a ban on call blocking and a requirement that the alternate
operator connect the caller with the long-distance carrier of his
choice.
   However, the FCC did not impose price restrictions on AOS
companies.
   The House subcommittee heard testimony from a number of
witnesses on a bill by Rep. Jim Cooper, D-Tenn., that would order
the FCC to impose restrictions on AOS companies, including a
guarantee that they charge ``just and reasonable'' rates.
   The Cooper bill says that if a customer uses the credit card of
a long-distance carrier, the charge from the AOS company may not
exceed the carrier's rates.
   Berg opposed the legislation, as did Gerald Hines of AT&amp;T, who
said the company favored the FCC's approach.
   Consumer group representatives favored the bill, and Steve
Hewlett, commissioner of the Tennessee Public Service Commission,
said price caps were needed.
   Dennis Thomas, a board member of the nation's largest AOS
company, International Telecharge, said legislation was not needed
in light of the FCC order, but if a bill were passed it should seek
to ``address the inequalities of cost and business opportunity that
today discriminate in favor of AT&amp;T and impair other competitors.''
   Gerald Brock, chief of the FCC's common carrier bureau, also
said many of the bill's provisions were contained in the FCC order
last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
