<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Corn-Soviets     04-05 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corn-Soviets,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy More US Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
200,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery this year under a
long-term supply agreement, the Agriculture Department said
Wednesday.
   More than 2.3 million tons have been purchased since the Soviets
resumed buying U.S. corn on March 28 after a layoff of almost three
months.
   The corn is scheduled for delivery by Sept. 30, the end of the
sixth year of a long-term grain supply agreement between the Soviet
Union and the United States.
   Officials said the latest sales brought total corn sold to the
Soviets for 1988-89 to more than 12.5 million tons. Additionally,
sales include 4 million tons of wheat, 450,000 tons of soybeans,
1.4 million tons of soybean meal, and 507,400 tons of grain sorghum.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 200,000 tons of
corn would be about 7.9 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.46 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the latest USDA five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $20 million.
</TEXT>
